    "id": "2021_01",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "1",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the content of the debate surrounding the introduction of a public review system for Supreme Court justices and to judge whether each view is strengthened or weakened according to given information.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "Country X operates a system of public review for its Supreme Court justices. According to the Constitution of Country X, Supreme Court justices are appointed by the Cabinet, but after appointment, a public vote is held at the time of the next general election for members of the legislature. If more than half of the voters wish for the removal of a justice, that justice is dismissed. If a voter marks an '×' under the name of a justice, it is counted as in favor of dismissal; those who do not mark are considered to have expressed confidence in the justice. Afterward, justices are subject to the same public review every 10 years until their retirement age. In Country Y, there are the following opinions regarding the potential adoption of this system.<Opinions>Alice: If the appointment of Supreme Court justices is left exclusively to the president and the sovereign people have no means of control, there is no way to restrain a justice no matter how biased their way of thinking may be. We need to introduce this system to establish a mechanism for judicial oversight by the people.Bob: That’s a reasonable point. However, the method used in Country X has the problem that unless voters proactively express their desire for removal, it is treated as opposition to removal, which means it does not properly reflect the will of the voters. If this system is introduced exactly as it is, it could soon become meaningless.Charlie: If improvements are made, those concerns can be dispelled. But ultimately, if this system is introduced, Supreme Court justices will be swayed by popular opinion instead of judging cases according to law and their beliefs, and the independence of the judiciary will be undermined. <question> Which of the following is NOT an appropriate evaluation of the above <Opinions>? <choices> ① If Country Y’s constitution guarantees lifetime tenure for Supreme Court justices appointed by the president (except in the case of irreversible physical disability), Alice’s opinion is strengthened.② If in Country Y, public opinion surveys indicate endless criticisms such as \"justice depends on wealth\" regarding court decisions, and public trust in the judiciary has declined annually, Alice’s opinion is strengthened.③ If, in Country X, no Supreme Court justice has been dismissed through public review in the past 70 years and only around 10% of total votes cast each time favored dismissal, Bob’s opinion is weakened.④ If in Country Y, some Supreme Court justices have caused repeated social chaos by overturning established Supreme Court decisions purely to pursue popularity, this fact strengthens Charlie’s opinion.⑤ If in Country Y, information related to each justice’s rulings is not properly provided and media coverage mainly focuses on personal activities for entertainment value, making it difficult for sound public opinion regarding confidence in Supreme Court justices to be formed, this strengthens Charlie’s opinion.",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "① If Country Y’s constitution guarantees lifetime tenure for Supreme Court justices appointed by the president (except in the case of irreversible physical disability), Alice’s opinion is strengthened.",
      "statement_2": "② If in Country Y, public opinion surveys indicate endless criticisms such as \"justice depends on wealth\" regarding court decisions, and public trust in the judiciary has declined annually, Alice’s opinion is strengthened.",
      "statement_3": "③ If, in Country X, no Supreme Court justice has been dismissed through public review in the past 70 years and only around 10% of total votes cast each time favored dismissal, Bob’s opinion is weakened.",
      "statement_4": "④ If in Country Y, some Supreme Court justices have caused repeated social chaos by overturning established Supreme Court decisions purely to pursue popularity, this fact strengthens Charlie’s opinion.",
      "statement_5": "⑤ If in Country Y, information related to each justice’s rulings is not properly provided and media coverage mainly focuses on personal activities for entertainment value, making it difficult for sound public opinion regarding confidence in Supreme Court justices to be formed, this strengthens Charlie’s opinion."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Country X has implemented a public review system for Supreme Court justices. Justices appointed by the Cabinet are subjected to a direct public vote, and if the majority of voters judge a justice as unqualified, that justice is dismissed.In Country Y, regarding the introduction of this system, there are (i) views supporting the necessity of public judicial oversight and advocating for the introduction of public review for justices; (ii) views expressing concerns about the effectiveness of the method carried out in Country X; and (iii) views opposing the introduction due to concerns that, if implemented, justices would be swayed by popular opinion instead of their legal convictions and beliefs, thus threatening judicial independence. You must understand the claims and reasoning of each perspective and, based on the information given, determine whether their positions are strengthened or weakened.④ In Country Y, if some Supreme Court justices have overturned established Supreme Court rulings to pursue popularity, causing social disorder, the introduction of a public review system would likely make more justices seek popularity. Thus, the fact that some justices have already overturned rulings for popularity and caused social chaos strengthens Charlie's concern that, under a public review system, justices would be swayed by popular opinion and their independence would be undermined. Therefore, option ④ is an appropriate evaluation.⑤ Charlie expresses concern that public review by the people would make justices overly concerned with public popularity and presents a negative opinion on the system. This means that unless sound public opinion is formed regarding the confidence in justices, the review system cannot function properly. If, in Country Y, information related to each justice’s judgments is not properly provided and coverage mainly focuses on private activities for entertainment, and sound public opinion cannot be formed, then the introduction of a public review system would likely lead justices to focus more on their image than their rulings, investing time and effort into gaining popularity rather than making decisions based on law and conscience, thus undermining judicial independence. Furthermore, in a society where sound public opinion about judicial confidence cannot be formed, verdicts would also become less just as they are influenced by public sentiment. Option ⑤ is an appropriate evaluation."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_02",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "2",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to infer the logical premises of each argument and the conclusions that follow from it.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "<Debate> Country X’s \"Criminal Act\" prohibits the production and distribution of obscene materials, while the \"Copyright Act\" protects creative works expressing human thoughts or emotions as copyrighted works for the enhancement and development of culture and related industries. There is debate about whether obscene materials should be protected as copyrighted works under the \"Copyright Act\".Alice: The \"Copyright Act\" only requires creativity as a condition for a work, and does not demand morality. In order to encourage creation and promote cultural diversity, the recognition of a work should be value-neutral.Bob: While the \"Criminal Act\" prohibits the production and distribution of obscene materials, protecting the resulting obscene materials as copyrighted works effectively grants rights to those with \"dirty hands\" who have committed illegal acts, and recognizes property value and protection for the fruits of illegal conduct, which should not be realized as property rights. This contradicts the principles of legal unity and fairness.Charlie: Clearly socially harmful obscene materials—such as child pornography or videos recording actual rape—should not be recognized as works, but for other types of obscene materials, recognizing them as works can help minimize the infringement on freedom of expression and property rights caused by regulation of obscene materials. <question> Which of the following <statements> correctly analyzes the <debate> above?<statements> (a) Alice presupposes that creativity cannot be acknowledged for obscene forms of expression.(b) Bob does not regard murals painted in legally prohibited locations or works that incite the public in violation of the National Security Act as objects of protection under the Copyright Act.(c) Charlie presupposes that even within the same era and region, the legal evaluation of obscenity may vary depending on the purpose, method, and audience of distribution. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Alice presupposes that creativity cannot be acknowledged for obscene forms of expression.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Bob does not regard murals painted in legally prohibited locations or works that incite the public in violation of the National Security Act as objects of protection under the Copyright Act.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Charlie presupposes that even within the same era and region, the legal evaluation of obscenity may vary depending on the purpose, method, and audience of distribution."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Alice, Bob, and Charlie are debating whether obscene materials should be protected as copyrighted works under the \"Copyright Act\". Alice argues that value neutrality is necessary in determining whether something is a copyrighted work and presents \"creativity\" as the sole criterion, believing that obscene materials can be included as copyrighted works. In contrast, Bob emphasizes the unity and fairness of the law and includes \"legality\" as a requirement for copyrighted works, thereby asserting that obscene materials cannot be recognized as works. Meanwhile, Charlie suggests a compromised stance that obscene materials should be differentiated in copyright protection based on the standard of \"social harmfulness\". <choices> Explanation: (a) Alice’s position is to exclude moral standards such as obscenity from the concept or determination criteria of a work and to use creativity as the determining criterion. This presupposes that creativity can indeed be acknowledged for expressions such as obscene materials, where morality is called into question. Thus, (a) is not a correct analysis.(b) Bob’s position, based on the \"dirty hands\" theory and the principles of legal unity and fairness, sees legality as an essential element of the concept of a work. Therefore, according to Bob, murals painted in legally prohibited places or works that incite the public in violation of the National Security Act, due to their illegality, cannot be regarded as copyrighted works under the Copyright Act. (b) is a correct analysis.(c) Charlie takes a compromised stance, seeking to differentiate the protection of copyrighted works by classifying obscene materials according to the criterion of social harmfulness. In this context, the legal evaluation he refers to is that of \"authorship\", not \"obscenity\", and is affected by social harmfulness. Thus, the assertion that legal evaluation of obscenity changes depending on purpose, method, or audience is not necessarily a presupposition of Charlie’s argument. Even if the legal evaluation of obscenity does not change according to such factors, Charlie’s argument still stands. Therefore, (c) is not a correct analysis.Only (b) is the correct analysis among the <choices>, so the answer is ②."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_03",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "3",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the advantages and disadvantages of two operational methods related to bankruptcy systems by comparing them.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "Country X and Country Y operate a system where bankruptcy can be declared by the court upon the application of either the creditor or the debtor. Country X: If an individual cannot repay borrowed money, they may declare bankruptcy, and all assets they possess at the time of bankruptcy are distributed to the creditors. Any remaining debts are fully discharged. The court grants debt discharge except in cases where the debtor maliciously fails to pay despite having the ability to do so. A person who has been discharged through bankruptcy faces no restrictions on the freedoms and rights they enjoy as a citizen in daily life.Country Y: If an individual cannot repay borrowed money, they may declare bankruptcy, and all assets possessed at the time of bankruptcy are distributed to the creditors. However, unless the creditor agrees, debts to that creditor are not discharged. Creditors may exercise their rights without restriction over assets acquired by the debtor after bankruptcy until their full debt is repaid. The bankrupt individual is detained for a certain period, loses the right to vote until the debts are paid in full, and the bankruptcy record is made public. <question> Which of the following is NOT a correct analysis of the above passage? <choices> ① Someone who is concerned that creditors will continue to urge bankrupt debtors to repay their debts and that related lawsuits will never cease would support Country X's system. ② Someone who believes that individuals are rational beings who make and are responsible for their own decisions, and that the state has no need to help those who have recklessly overspent, would oppose Country X's system. ③ Someone who worries that creditors may use bankruptcy filings as a means of threat in order to collect their claims ahead of other creditors would support Country Y's system. ④ Someone who fears that individuals at risk of bankruptcy will keep taking on more debt to repay existing debt, thereby perpetuating creditor–debtor relationships, would oppose Country Y's system. ⑤ Someone who is concerned that making creditor–debtor relationships after bankruptcy subject to the will of the creditor would cause social confusion, such as the emergence of fictitious creditors, would oppose Country Y's system.",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "① Someone who is concerned that creditors will continue to urge bankrupt debtors to repay their debts and that related lawsuits will never cease would support Country X's system.",
      "statement_2": "② Someone who believes that individuals are rational beings who make and are responsible for their own decisions, and that the state has no need to help those who have recklessly overspent, would oppose Country X's system.",
      "statement_3": "③ Someone who worries that creditors may use bankruptcy filings as a means of threat in order to collect their claims ahead of other creditors would support Country Y's system.",
      "statement_4": "④ Someone who fears that individuals at risk of bankruptcy will keep taking on more debt to repay existing debt, thereby perpetuating creditor–debtor relationships, would oppose Country Y's system.",
      "statement_5": "⑤ Someone who is concerned that making creditor–debtor relationships after bankruptcy subject to the will of the creditor would cause social confusion, such as the emergence of fictitious creditors, would oppose Country Y's system."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Country X's system is the institutionalization of the principle of bankruptcy discharge, which releases the bankrupt debtor from liability for unpaid debts. Country Y, on the other hand, does not employ the principle of bankruptcy discharge. While Country Y maintains the principle that freely entered contracts between parties must be observed even in the bankruptcy system, Country X, in contrast, seeks to give a new opportunity to debtors through bankruptcy. Correct Answer Explanation: ③ Country Y allows for restrictions on the rights of a debtor who has been declared bankrupt, such as detention and the deprivation of voting rights. As such, a creditor could devise a plan to use bankruptcy as a means of psychological pressure to collect payment before other creditors. In trying to avoid bankruptcy, the debtor may prioritize repaying that creditor over others or even take on new debt just to repay that creditor. Therefore, someone with such concerns would not support Country Y's system. Thus, ③ is an incorrect analysis. Incorrect Answer Explanations: ① Under Country X’s system, the creditor–debtor relationship is extinguished through bankruptcy, and related lawsuits will no longer occur. Therefore, a person concerned about ongoing lawsuits would support Country X's system. ① is a correct analysis.② Since Country X's system forgives all remaining debt upon bankruptcy, it can be criticized for granting benefits to debtors who irresponsibly increased their debts beyond their means. ② is a correct analysis.④ Country Y's system involves using the debtor’s assets at the time of bankruptcy to pay part of the debt, but continuously restricts the debtor’s rights until the full debt is paid off, forcing them to keep repaying the debt. As a result, debtors would try to avoid bankruptcy without the benefit of discharge and may continue to take out more loans as a means of debt rollover. Therefore, someone concerned about this would not support Country Y's system. ④ is a correct analysis.⑤ Because Country Y's system does not provide for a universal debt discharge, there is the risk that fictitious creditors, colluding with the debtor, will fraudulently claim rights and receive a distribution of the debtor’s assets, thereby interfering with actual creditors’ recovery. Therefore, someone with this concern would oppose Country Y’s system. ⑤ is a correct analysis."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_13",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "13",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand arguments concerning whether pre-emptive punishment can be justified and to apply the abstract principles used in these arguments to specific cases.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "Alice is planning to speed on the highway today. There are no environmental factors that could frustrate this plan, and Alice’s determination is firm. In addition, once Alice makes up her mind, she never changes it. 'ⓐ Knowing all this, the police know that Alice will speed on the highway today.' In fact, Alice did speed on the highway. In this case, is it justified for the police to impose a speeding fine on Alice before she enters the highway? In other words, is it justified to punish someone in advance simply because it is known that they will commit an act that has not yet occurred? A: The significance of punishment is to inflict harm on a person equivalent to the wrongdoing they have committed, thus maintaining a balance. As long as it is known that a wrongdoing will be committed, the exact timing of the punishment is not important. It is the same principle as whether you pay for a TV before or after you receive it — it makes no difference. Regardless of whether the police impose the fine in advance, Alice will undoubtedly speed, and the police know this. Therefore, the police’s pre-emptive punishment to maintain balance in response to this can be justified.B: Punishing an innocent person cannot be justified under any circumstance. Even if Alice’s determination is strong, it cannot be denied that she has the ability to change her mind at the last moment and not speed. As long as Alice has that ability, before she actually speeds, she is clearly an innocent person. Therefore, pre-emptive punishment against Alice cannot be justified. <question> Which of the following analyses of the passage is/are correct? Choose all that apply from <statements>.<statements> (a). If ⓐ is false, the conclusion of A does not follow.(b). There is a view that, if the agent has the ability to decide whether or not to perform an act, it is impossible for others to know in advance whether she will perform that act. If this view is correct, B is incompatible with ⓐ.(c). A terrorist is preparing an attack that will drive citizens to their deaths, and the police know that if they leave this terrorist alone, the attack will succeed. The police respond by detaining the terrorist and meting out punishment in advance equivalent to the harm that would result from the attack, thereby successfully preventing it. According to A, pre-emptive punishment could be justified in this case as well. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) . If ⓐ is false, the conclusion of A does not follow.",
      "statement_2": "(b) . There is a view that, if the agent has the ability to decide whether or not to perform an act, it is impossible for others to know in advance whether she will perform that act. If this view is correct, B is incompatible with ⓐ.",
      "statement_3": "(c) . A terrorist is preparing an attack that will drive citizens to their deaths, and the police know that if they leave this terrorist alone, the attack will succeed. The police respond by detaining the terrorist and meting out punishment in advance equivalent to the harm that would result from the attack, thereby successfully preventing it. According to A, pre-emptive punishment could be justified in this case as well."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The passage deals with \"pre-punishment,\" which might become important in a future society, and debates under what assumptions such punishment can or cannot be justified. The key feature of the presented scenario is that the police already know about Alice’s future act and the act actually occurs. A claims that, under a retributive view of punishment, pre-punishment can be justified: since the speeding will actually occur, the timing of retaliation is unimportant. B, on the other hand, holds that since Alice still has the capacity for free choice before committing the crime, she is an innocent person and thus pre-punishment cannot be justified. The key to solving the problem is recognizing that A’s position crucially assumes that the police know about Alice’s future speeding, while B’s argument crucially rests on the assumption that Alice has the ability to freely choose her action. <choices> Explanation:(a). “The police know that Alice will speed” is a key premise in A’s argument. Therefore, denying this means A’s intended conclusion does not follow. Thus, (a) is a correct analysis.(b). The core premise of B’s argument is that “Alice has the ability not to speed.” This is in tension with ⓐ (“...the police know that Alice will speed...”). The view in (b), “if the agent has the capacity to decide, it is impossible for others to know in advance,” explicitly expresses this tension. If this view is accepted, B is incompatible with ⓐ. Thus, (b) is a correct analysis.(c). The crucial difference between the terrorist case and the speeding case is whether the crime actually occurs. In the terrorist case, the act does not occur because of the pre-punishment, so punishment cannot serve as a balancing act for the wrongdoing. Therefore, in the terrorist case, pre-punishment cannot be justified under A’s retributivist perspective.Thus, only (a) and (b) are correct analyses, so the answer is ③."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_14",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "14",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to appropriately analyze the debate about what it means for an action to cause harm or benefit.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "<Theory> For an act to \"cause harm\" to someone means that, if the act had not occurred, that person would have been in a better state. Similarly, for an act to \"benefit\" someone means that, if the act had not occurred, that person would have been in a worse state. Alice and Bob have the following debate regarding <Theory>: Alice1: I could have given my friend 50,000 won for no reason but chose not to. If I had done so, my friend would have been in a better state. According to <Theory>, my act harmed my friend. But that seems unreasonable. Bob1: <Theory> doesn't have such implications. That's because doing nothing—like simply not giving your friend 50,000 won—cannot be considered an act. Alice2: If you limit \"act\" in such a way within <Theory>, other unreasonable consequences follow. Consider someone who saw a child struggling in water and had the ability to rescue them but chose not to, resulting in the child's drowning. Not saving the child clearly harmed the child. Bob2: But this case is different. The choice not to save the child is itself the result of a deliberate decision to avoid the rescue. In this sense, not saving the child should be considered an act. Alice3: Then what about this case? Imagine A bought a gift intended for B but became attached to it and decided to keep it instead of giving it to B. In this case, although not giving the gift was a deliberate decision, it doesn't seem like A harmed B. <question> Which of the following statements in <statements> is/are correct as an analysis of the above passage? <statements> (a) According to Alice1’s interpretation of <Theory>, if I could have punched my friend and broken their nose but did not do so, then, by not punching my friend, I performed an act that benefited my friend. (b) Alice2 and Bob2 differ in their judgment about whether not rescuing the child caused harm to the child. (c) If Bob, in response to Alice3, were to assert that “A’s not giving the gift to B did, in fact, harm B,” this would make Bob’s position inconsistent. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) According to Alice1’s interpretation of <Theory>, if I could have punched my friend and broken their nose but did not do so, then, by not punching my friend, I performed an act that benefited my friend.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Alice2 and Bob2 differ in their judgment about whether not rescuing the child caused harm to the child.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If Bob, in response to Alice3, were to assert that “A’s not giving the gift to B did, in fact, harm B,” this would make Bob’s position inconsistent."
    },
    "original_rationale": "<Theory> is a counterfactual comparative account that explains what it means for an act or event to cause harm or benefit to someone. According to this view, to say that an act causes harm (or benefit) to someone means that if the act had not occurred, the person would have been better (or worse) off. Alice is trying to challenge this view through a series of counterexamples, while Bob defends the view by clarifying the definition of \"act.\" The structure of the debate is as follows: Alice1: Presents the failure to give 50,000 won to a friend as a counterexample to <Theory>. Bob1: Responds that this does not count as an act, so it’s not a true counterexample. Alice2: Raises a new counterexample involving not saving a drowning child, arguing that Bob1’s solution is inadequate. Bob2: Adds further conditions to the definition of \"act\" to show the case of not saving the child is not a counterexample. Alice3: Presents a case with additional conditions to pose another counterexample. <choices> Explanation: (a): Alice1 interprets \"doing nothing\" as an act; thus, according to <Theory>, if you do not give your friend 50,000 won, your friend is worse off, making the omission an act that harms your friend. Applying this same logic, if you could have punched your friend and broken their nose but did not, \"not punching your friend\" is considered an act. Since punching would have made your friend worse off, <Theory> would interpret not punching as benefiting your friend. Therefore, (a) is a correct analysis. (b): In the scenario with the drowning child, Alice2 claims that not rescuing the child clearly harmed the child and that this case is a counterexample to Bob1’s interpretation of <Theory>. Bob2 agrees with the assessment that not rescuing caused harm but claims, through a reinterpretation of <Theory>, that this is not a counterexample. Therefore, (b) is not a correct analysis. (c): In response to Alice3, Bob could maintain consistency by sticking with the interpretation that \"A’s not giving the gift to B counts as harming B.\" Maintaining this stance would not be inconsistent with Bob2’s previously stated position. Therefore, (c) is not a correct analysis. Only (a) is a correct analysis among <choices>, so the answer is ①."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_15",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "15",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to analyze and evaluate the debate regarding whether art can provide knowledge.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "Alice: A belief that is simply true is not knowledge. For a true belief to become knowledge, it must be justified. However, \"ⓐ Even if the beliefs gained from works of art may possibly be true, they are never justified.\" For example, Dickens’ realist novel \"Bleak House\" accurately depicts the process of inheritance lawsuits in 19th-century England. However, merely reading \"Bleak House\" does not provide us with evidence for the accuracy of that depiction.Bob: According to what Alice said, an encyclopedia is no different from \"Bleak House.\" This is because, simply by reading an encyclopedia, one has no reason to believe that the information obtained from it is accurate.Alice: That is not the case. In the case of an encyclopedia, there is a procedure to confirm its accuracy by experts in the relevant field, the so-called \"institutional guarantee.\" However, in the case of \"Bleak House,\" no one is required to verify the claims the author makes within the work.Bob: \"ⓑ As a publication practice, an institutional guarantee only shows that there was a process of author or content verification, but does not show that the verification was successful.\" Simply reading an encyclopedia does not allow us to know whether such verification procedures were successfully carried out or not. <question> Which of the following assessments of the debate is/are appropriate according to the <statements> below? <statements> (a) The fact that realist novels are written after verification capable of evidential value about whether certain events actually happened weakens ⓐ. (b) The revelation that \"Hitler Diaries\" was not an autobiography written by Hitler, but was actually fabricated by someone else, weakens ⓑ. (c) Unlike a reader who seeks information from an encyclopedia, a reader of \"Bleak House\" mainly seeks reasons to believe what is depicted in the work based on personal experience; this strengthens Alice’s view. <choices> ① (b) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (a), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) The fact that realist novels are written after verification capable of evidential value about whether certain events actually happened weakens ⓐ.",
      "statement_2": "(b) The revelation that \"Hitler Diaries\" was not an autobiography written by Hitler, but was actually fabricated by someone else, weakens ⓑ.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Unlike a reader who seeks information from an encyclopedia, a reader of \"Bleak House\" mainly seeks reasons to believe what is depicted in the work based on personal experience; this strengthens Alice’s view."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The question of whether art can provide us with knowledge has a long history. Accordingly, there are various layers to the debate between the view that art can provide knowledge and the view that it cannot.There are questions about whether there is knowledge unique to art; if so, what character such knowledge would have; and if art does give us knowledge, how its epistemic value contributes to the enhancement of its aesthetic or artistic value. These constitute the different layers of the debate.This question focuses on the issue of justification in knowledge when knowledge is defined as justified true belief, and introduces a debate on this. The passage contrasts Alice's view—which argues that even if beliefs gained from works of art are true, they require extrinsic justification such as institutional guarantee to be considered true knowledge, and that realist novels do not provide such justification unlike encyclopedias—with Bob’s skeptical view on whether extrinsic justification can serve as a standard for distinguishing knowledge delivered by realist novels and encyclopedias.Explanation for <choices>: (a) ⓐ claims that our beliefs gained from works of art can never be justified, even if they happen to be true. However, if realist novels—a type of artistic work—are actually written after fact-checking with evidential value about whether specific events really occurred, this would mean that the beliefs we gain from realist novels can not only be true but also justified, thus weakening ⓐ. Therefore, (a) is an appropriate assessment."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_16",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "16",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to correctly analyze and evaluate arguments.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "Alice: Elegance is not a property that belongs to Chopin's nocturnes themselves, but merely a subjective impression you have. When I listen to the nocturnes, I just feel bored the whole time. Bob: If you only felt boredom from listening to the nocturnes, that's because you're only used to hip-hop. Try to follow the delicacy expressed by the piano's tone and the development of the melody. The fact that this piece is elegant is something that anyone with an appropriate capacity for musical appreciation can recognize under normal conditions. Charlie: Even if the elegance of the nocturnes isn't just a matter of subjective feeling, I don't think it's correct to say it's a property that anyone can recognize. Isn't it rather that only people belonging to a certain culture, who are used to a particular kind of music, regard the nocturnes as elegant? This is at least unlike properties like the yellow color or round shape of a melon, which are genuinely attributable to the object itself. Bob: Even if only people from a certain group can regard the nocturnes as elegant, I think their elegance should still be seen as a genuine property of the music. After all, yellow is only seen as yellow by people who aren't color-blind, but it's still a real property of the melon, right? In the case of the nocturnes, it's just that only people with appropriate musical sensitivity can perceive the elegance. Charlie: Isn't it a more natural explanation that you two are reacting differently to the nocturnes because you each belong to groups that share different kinds of musical sensitivity? Why should we say that only people who react by calling it elegant are perceiving a real property?<question> Which of the following analyses of this debate is/are correct, according to the <statements>?<statements> (a) Bob would oppose the claim that the group of people who can perceive elegance could be larger or smaller depending on period and culture. (b) Charlie would oppose the claim that people who find Chopin's nocturnes boring may have a different kind of musical sensitivity. (c) Bob and Charlie can both accept the claim that Chopin's nocturnes are elegant, albeit for different reasons. <choices> ① (b) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (a), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Bob would oppose the claim that the group of people who can perceive elegance could be larger or smaller depending on period and culture.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Charlie would oppose the claim that people who find Chopin's nocturnes boring may have a different kind of musical sensitivity.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Bob and Charlie can both accept the claim that Chopin's nocturnes are elegant, albeit for different reasons."
    },
    "original_rationale": "This question concerns a debate over whether aesthetic properties—using the example of \"elegance\"—are real properties belonging to an object such as Chopin's nocturnes, or not. Alice's view is that aesthetic properties are not real properties of an object, and that attributing them is merely an expression of individual subjective impressions. Bob, in contrast, argues that aesthetic properties are real properties of the object, which can be perceived by listeners possessing the appropriate musical sensitivity under normal conditions. Meanwhile, Charlie contends that, although aesthetic properties are not simply a matter of individual subjective impressions, they are not genuine properties of the object either, and should be understood as being perceived differently depending on the shared musical sensitivity within each group. The question asks you to clearly recognize these differences in perspectives and to deduce their respective implications. <choices> Explanation (a) Bob claims that only those with appropriate musical sensitivity can perceive the elegance of the musical work. Since this means only that the group who can perceive elegance is limited to those with appropriate musical sensitivity, it is compatible with the idea that the size of this group could be larger or smaller depending on the era or culture. Thus, saying Bob would oppose this claim is an incorrect analysis. (b) Charlie maintains that people react differently to Chopin's nocturnes because the shared musical sensitivity of the groups they belong to is different. According to this explanation, people who find the nocturnes boring would indeed have musical sensitivities different from those who find them elegant. Therefore, (b) is also incorrect. (c) For Bob, only those with suitable musical sensitivity can perceive the genuine property of elegance in Chopin's nocturnes, so he can accept statements by people with such sensitivity that \"Chopin's nocturnes are elegant.\" Meanwhile, for Charlie, even if elegance need not be a real property of Chopin's nocturnes, it is enough if there is a group sharing the relevant musical sensitivity who feel the music is elegant; thus, Charlie too can accept a group member's assertion that \"Chopin's nocturnes are elegant.\" Therefore, (c) is a correct analysis.Since only (c) is a correct analysis, the answer is ②."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_17",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "17",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to correctly analyze the classical debate concerning the problem of whether belief must be based on sufficient grounds.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "Alice: If I come to hold a belief based on insufficient evidence, that belief itself may not cause much harm. That belief could ultimately be true, and it might never be externally manifested in actions. However, I cannot avoid committing a crime against humanity by making myself an easy believer. The mere fact that a society holds false beliefs is a serious problem, but a greater problem is that society becomes gullible, loses the habit of examining and carefully investigating evidence, and regresses to a state of barbarism. 'ⓐ To believe something on insufficient evidence is always, everywhere, and for anyone, wrong.' - William Clifford, \"The Ethics of Belief\" - Bob: \"Believe the truth!\", \"Avoid error!\" These are the most important commandments for anyone seeking knowledge. However, these are two distinct rules. And depending on which of these one values more, one’s entire intellectual life may differ. One may prioritize the pursuit of truth and see the avoidance of error as secondary, or conversely, consider the avoidance of error most important and the attainment of truth as secondary. Clifford recommends the latter to us. He tells us that, rather than risking the dreadful possibility of believing a falsehood based on insufficient evidence, we should suspend judgment and believe nothing. As for myself, I don’t think I take Clifford’s side. In any case, what we must not forget is that our attitude toward the obligations related to truth or error is grounded not in evidence but in sentiment. People like Clifford, who say \"It is better to never believe than to ever believe something false!\" are merely expressing a fear of being naively deceived.- William James, \"The Will to Believe\" - <question> Which of the following analyses of the passages is/are correct? Choose as indicated from <statements>.<statements> (a) Alice supports her conclusion by pointing out the undesirable consequences that will arise if people do not act according to her conclusion. (b) According to Bob, Clifford's belief in ⓐ is not based on sufficient evidence. (c) Bob's argument requires the premise that 'even a belief based on sufficient evidence can be mistaken.' <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Alice supports her conclusion by pointing out the undesirable consequences that will arise if people do not act according to her conclusion.",
      "statement_2": "(b) According to Bob, Clifford's belief in ⓐ is not based on sufficient evidence.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Bob's argument requires the premise that 'even a belief based on sufficient evidence can be mistaken.'"
    },
    "original_rationale": "The passages excerpt the core of the classic debate between Clifford and James. Clifford argues that it is wrong to form beliefs based on insufficient evidence. His argument is that, if one comes to form beliefs on insufficient evidence, society becomes more susceptible to being deceived, regressing to a barbaric state as a result.James emphasizes that the pursuit of truth and the avoidance of error are distinct intellectual tasks, pointing out that Clifford’s stance is justifiable only if one prioritizes the avoidance of error—and that the choice between the two is ultimately a matter of sentiment, not evidence. <choices> Explanation (a) Alice’s conclusion is \"To believe something on insufficient evidence is always, everywhere, and for anyone, wrong.\" She justifies this by arguing that not following this leads society into a 'state of barbarism.' Thus, (a) is a correct analysis. (b) Bob argues that there are two epistemic duties, \"Believe the truth!\" and \"Avoid error!\", and that Clifford focuses only on the latter. He also claims that this choice is grounded not in evidence but in sentiment. Therefore, according to Bob, Clifford’s belief in ⓐ is not based on sufficient evidence. Thus, (b) is a correct analysis. (c) Bob’s argument is unrelated to the claim that \"even beliefs based on sufficient evidence can be mistaken.\" Even if that statement is false, that is, even if beliefs based on sufficient evidence could never be mistaken, Bob’s argument remains unaffected. He merely points out that the disposition to base belief only on sufficient evidence is itself grounded in sentiment. Therefore, (c) is not a correct analysis. Since only (a) and (b) are correct, the answer is ③."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_18",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "18",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to correctly analyze individual arguments and their grounds, using views on epistemic objectivity and the artistic judgment of critics as its subject matter.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "A: 'Epistemic objectivity' is related not so much to whether a claim is true or false, but rather to how that claim is justified. In the process of making a claim, it is necessary to ensure that healthy common sense and rationality are not distorted by the intervention of subjective elements such as bias, prejudice, herd mentality, or personal wishes, whether they belong to oneself or anyone else. In this sense, a judgment that has secured epistemic objectivity generally possesses persuasive power.B: For a work of art to have its intended effect, it must be appreciated from a particular perspective. If the critic’s situation does not align with what the work demands, the critic cannot make an appropriate judgment about the work. For example, when an advocate delivers a speech to a specific audience, he or she must consider that audience’s unique characteristics, interests, views, passions, and prejudices. If a critic from another era or country encounters this speech, in order to make the correct judgment, the critic must take all these circumstances into account and place himself or herself in the same situation as the contemporary audience. The same applies to works of art. Even if the critic is a friend or an adversary of the artist, they must set aside their own particular circumstances and adopt the perspective presupposed by the work. <question> Which of the following analyses of the above passages is/are correct? Choose all correct answers from among the <statements> as given.<statements>(a) If two people make the same judgment about a claim, according to Alice, their judgment possesses epistemic objectivity.(b) According to Alice, the judgment that Bob’s critic makes about a work of art does not possess epistemic objectivity.(c) If two critics from different eras or countries make the same judgment about a given work of art, according to Bob, their judgment is made from the perspective presupposed by the work. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If two people make the same judgment about a claim, according to Alice, their judgment possesses epistemic objectivity.",
      "statement_2": "(b) According to Alice, the judgment that Bob’s critic makes about a work of art does not possess epistemic objectivity.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If two critics from different eras or countries make the same judgment about a given work of art, according to Bob, their judgment is made from the perspective presupposed by the work."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The given passages contrast Alice’s position—that epistemic objectivity in judgment can be secured only by completely excluding subjective elements and fully exercising rationality—with Bob’s view that, for a critic’s judgment about a work of art to be appropriate, the critic must set aside his or her own particular circumstances and instead adopt the specific perspective presupposed by the work. <choices> Explanation(a) If two people make the same judgment about a claim, then, according to Alice, for their judgment to possess epistemic objectivity, subjective elements from themselves or anyone else must not have been involved in making that judgment. However, the mere fact that they arrived at the same judgment does not entail that such subjective elements have been excluded, so we cannot conclude that their judgment has epistemic objectivity. Thus, (a) is not a correct analysis.(b) According to Alice, for Bob’s critic’s judgment to have epistemic objectivity, subjective elements—whether from the critic or anyone else—must not have played a role in making that judgment. However, Bob’s critic needs to adopt the particular perspective required by the work, and that perspective, while not the critic’s own, nevertheless requires considering another person’s subjective elements. Therefore, (b) is a correct analysis.(c) If two critics from different eras or countries make the same judgment about a work of art, Bob’s view is that for their judgments to be proper, they must be made from the perspective presupposed by the work. However, the mere fact that their judgments are the same does not necessarily mean that they adopted the perspective presupposed by the work. Therefore, (c) is not a correct analysis.Only (b) among the <choices> is a correct analysis, so the answer is ②."
  },
