    "id": "2021_20",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "20",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to read a debate on when changes in scientific theories can be considered progressive, and to accurately analyze each perspective.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "Alice: It is not clear whether changes in scientific theories constitute \"genuine progress.\" Of course, if we look at the history of science, there have been instances where a successor theory replaced a previous theory by explaining and predicting a greater number of facts. However, this does not serve as grounds for claiming that the successor theory is “truly progressive.” Those cases merely show that the successor theory received more social support or that more scientists participated in its research.Bob: Even if such external factors influenced past achievements of theories, it is not impossible to judge whether real progress has taken place. This is because the judgment of progress depends not only on past achievements but also on future achievements that could be attained. And the potential achievements that a theory may have in the future are not influenced by such external factors.Alice: It is possible to compare the past performances of theories. However, it is difficult to compare the scope of explanations and predictions they will achieve in the future, that is, the future potential of the theories. This is because we cannot know all the consequences that a theory may have in the future.Bob: We can often compare the future potential of two theories. For example, for two theories T1 and T2, suppose that we can derive all statements constituting T1 deductively from those of T2, but not vice versa. In that case, T2 will make new predictions in addition to all the predictions of T1. In this case, T2 is “more general” than T1, and therefore has more future potential. <question> Which of the following analyses of the debate above is/are correct, as given in <statements>? <statements> (a) Both Alice and Bob agree that, for changes in scientific theory to constitute \"genuine progress,\" the success of a theory should not be explained solely by social factors.(b) Both Alice and Bob agree that changes in scientific theory have occurred in such a way that the successor theory preserves the explanations and predictions of the previous theory and further provides new explanations and predictions.(c) If the theory of relativity made correct predictions in areas where Newtonian theory made incorrect ones, Bob would agree that the theory of relativity is “more general” than the Newtonian theory. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Both Alice and Bob agree that, for changes in scientific theory to constitute \"genuine progress,\" the success of a theory should not be explained solely by social factors.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Both Alice and Bob agree that changes in scientific theory have occurred in such a way that the successor theory preserves the explanations and predictions of the previous theory and further provides new explanations and predictions.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If the theory of relativity made correct predictions in areas where Newtonian theory made incorrect ones, Bob would agree that the theory of relativity is “more general” than the Newtonian theory."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The prompt introduces a debate about whether changes in scientific theory constitute “genuine progress,” in what sense this is so, and how we can judge whether progress has occurred. In the debate, Alice argues that, even if we admit to the achievements of a theory in the past, those can be explained by social factors and therefore cannot be the basis for genuine progress. Bob concedes Alice’s argument regarding past achievements, but insists that we can assess genuine progress by considering the future potential of the theory. To answer the question, we must judge whether both Alice and Bob would agree with the assertions presented in <statements>. <choices> Explanations (a): Alice argues that cases of theory success merely demonstrate the influence of social factors and therefore should not be seen as evidence of progress. This amounts to claiming that the success of a theory being explained purely through social factors would preclude genuine progress; Alice would accept this. Bob also claims that progress can be judged by the future potential of theories, which is unaffected by social factors, and would agree to the same. Therefore, (a) is a correct analysis. (b): Alice does acknowledge cases where successor theories explain and predict more facts, but this does not mean she agrees that scientific change always takes the form where successor theories preserve previous explanations and predictions and then add to them. Thus, (b) is not a correct analysis.(c): If the theory of relativity correctly predicts where Newtonian theory failed, it does not necessarily mean that relativity preserves all the predictions of Newtonian theory in addition to making new predictions. Since some predictions by Newtonian theory are not preserved, relativity would not qualify as “more general” in Bob’s sense. Thus, (c) is also not a correct analysis.Therefore, only (a) is the correct analysis, so the answer is ①."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_24",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "24",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand two arguments concerning the role of human nature and culture in shaping humans, and to determine whether presented survey results or research findings strengthen or weaken each argument.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "The roles of nature and culture in human development are a matter of debate, with opinions divided as follows.<Opinions>Alice: I believe that in order to understand human development, we must start from human nature. This is because there are clear differences between groups, and especially biological characteristics play a decisive role in explaining intergroup differences. In addition, many researchers have proven that differences in intelligence quotient between individuals are due to genetic factors.Bob: The fact that intelligence quotients among groups divided by race, gender, etc. show almost no difference is an undeniable fact accepted in the scientific community. Because the human species is so homogeneous, I think that insisting on intergroup differences based on biological criteria stems from a misguided motivation to uphold unequal social hierarchies. Social hierarchy only limits human variability; humans can be shaped differently depending on culture or social environment. <question> Which of the following in <Statements> properly evaluates the <Opinions>? <statements> (a) Research results indicating that in every society throughout history, crime rates have been overwhelmingly higher in a particular group—males between the ages of 15 and 25—weaken Alice's argument.(b) Research results that various social reforms aimed at fairly developing the abilities of all members of society have failed do not strengthen Bob's argument.(c) Research results showing that, as a result of improving English education programs, the English test scores of most elementary school students increased significantly compared to before the improvement, strengthen Alice's argument and weaken Bob's argument. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Research results indicating that in every society throughout history, crime rates have been overwhelmingly higher in a particular group—males between the ages of 15 and 25—weaken Alice's argument.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Research results that various social reforms aimed at fairly developing the abilities of all members of society have failed do not strengthen Bob's argument.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Research results showing that, as a result of improving English education programs, the English test scores of most elementary school students increased significantly compared to before the improvement, strengthen Alice's argument and weaken Bob's argument."
    },
    "original_rationale": "In the <Opinions>, Alice emphasizes the importance of human nature, particularly biological characteristics, in the formation of humans. She also claims that these biological traits cause differences between individuals and groups. On the other hand, Bob emphasizes the importance of culture or social environment in human development. He argues that emphasizing biological traits amounts to supporting social hierarchy and rebutts by saying there are actually very few intergroup differences based on biological factors. He further stresses the potential for human development depending on cultural or social environmental changes. <choices> Explanation:(a) The claim that, throughout history, in every society crime rates have been high in a specific group—males aged 15 to 25—means that in any culture or social environment, there is consistently a high crime rate among a particular age group of males. In other words, regardless of cultural or social environmental change, this research result, which suggests that the biological trait of being a male of a certain age greatly influences crime rates, actually strengthens Alice's argument emphasizing biological characteristics in human development, rather than weakening it. Thus, (a) is not an appropriate evaluation.(b) Various social reforms aimed at equally developing the abilities of all members of society can be understood as attempts to promote human development by changing culture or social environment. Therefore, the finding that such reforms failed does not strengthen Bob’s claim, which argues for the potential for human variability and development through environmental change. Thus, (b) is an appropriate evaluation.(c) The fact that, due to improvements in English education programs, most elementary school students’ test scores increased greatly compared to before the improvements shows that human development can be achieved through changes in environment, especially through changes in systems. Therefore, this research result weakens Alice's argument, which emphasizes biological characteristics in human development, while strengthening Bob’s argument, which emphasizes the importance of environment. Thus, (c) is not an appropriate evaluation.Therefore, only (b) in the <Choices> is an appropriate evaluation, so the correct answer is ②."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_25",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "25",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the problems that pre-surveys can have in experimental research in social sciences and their solutions, and to find experimental results showing that viewing Black hero films reduced the degree of negative bias towards Black people.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "In social sciences, classical experimental research may not be able to generalize experimental results to the real world. For example, suppose an experimental study was conducted to determine whether ‘watching a movie where a Black person appears as a hero’ (the experimental stimulus) reduces ‘the degree of negative prejudice against Black people’, and the following findings were observed. First, in the experimental group that received the experimental stimulus, the degree of prejudice was lower in the post-test than in the pre-test. Second, in the control group that did not receive the experimental stimulus, there was no change in the degree of prejudice between the pre-test and the post-test. In this case, it can be considered that watching the movie reduced the degree of prejudice among participants in the experimental group. However, it cannot be asserted with certainty that the same effect would appear if the movie was watched by people in their everyday lives. This is because in experiments, participants may already have become sensitive to the issue of prejudice against Black people as a result of the pre-test. To solve this problem, an <experimental design> that adds an experiment without a pre-test must be implemented. If, through this, experimental results are obtained that demonstrate ‘ⓐ that watching the movie reduced the degree of prejudice’, the possibility of generalization can be increased.<Experimental Design>• Group 1: Pre-test → Experimental stimulus → Post-test.• Group 2: Pre-test → Post-test.• Group 3: No pre-test → Experimental stimulus → Post-test.• Group 4: No pre-test → Post-test.All participants in Groups 1 to 4 were randomly selected from the population. <question> Which of the following cannot be included in the experimental results that demonstrate ⓐ?<choices>① In Group 1, the degree of prejudice in the post-test was lower than the degree of prejudice in the pre-test.② The degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 1 was lower than the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 2.③ The degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 3 was lower than the degree of prejudice in the pre-test of Group 2.④ The degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 3 was lower than the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 4.⑤ The degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 4 was lower than the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 1.",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "① In Group 1, the degree of prejudice in the post-test was lower than the degree of prejudice in the pre-test.",
      "statement_2": "② The degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 1 was lower than the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group",
      "statement_3": "2. ",
      "statement_4": "③ The degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 3 was lower than the degree of prejudice in the pre-test of Group",
      "statement_5": "2. ",
      "statement_6": "④ The degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 3 was lower than the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group",
      "statement_7": "4. ",
      "statement_8": "⑤ The degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 4 was lower than the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group",
      "statement_9": "1. "
    },
    "original_rationale": "In classical experimental research in the social sciences, conducting a pre-test can make participants more sensitive to the experimental stimulus, which may in turn influence the experimental result. Therefore, the experimental results thus obtained are difficult to generalize to the real world. To solve this problem, an additional experiment without a pre-test is required. If, in the <experimental design>, results are observed showing that the level of prejudice is reduced in the experimental groups (Groups 1 and 3) due to the experimental stimulus, while there is no change in the control groups (Groups 2 and 4), it can be demonstrated that watching the movie reduces the degree of negative prejudice against Black people (point ⓐ). As a supplementary clue, it is noted that all participants were randomly selected, enabling comparisons between groups.Correct answer explanation: ⑤ If the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 4 (which did not receive the experimental stimulus) is lower than that of Group 1 (which did receive the experimental stimulus), then the effect of the experimental stimulus was not found. Therefore, ⑤ cannot be used to demonstrate ⓐ.Incorrect answer explanations:① If, in Group 1, the degree of prejudice in the post-test after the experimental stimulus is lower than in the pre-test before the stimulus, then the effect of the experimental stimulus has been found. Thus, ① demonstrates ⓐ.② If the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 1 (which received the experimental stimulus) is lower than that in the post-test of Group 2 (which did not receive the stimulus), then the effect of the experimental stimulus has been found. Thus, ② demonstrates ⓐ.③ If the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 3 (which received the experimental stimulus) is lower than the degree of prejudice in the pre-test of Group 2 (which did not receive the stimulus), then the effect of the experimental stimulus has been found. Thus, ③ demonstrates ⓐ.④ If the degree of prejudice in the post-test of Group 3 (which received the experimental stimulus) is lower than the post-test in Group 4 (which did not receive the stimulus), then the effect of the experimental stimulus has been found. Thus, ④ demonstrates ⓐ."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_28",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "28",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand a policy that changes the tiers of a progressive rate system and to determine whether each argument in the debate concerning this policy is strengthened or weakened by the presented data.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "Country X applies the following progressive billing system for monthly household electricity rates.- Tier 1: Usage up to 200 kWh, base charge is 900 won, rate per kWh is 90 won.- Tier 2: Usage over 200 kWh and up to 400 kWh, base charge is 1,600 won, rate per kWh is 180 won.- Tier 3: Usage over 400 kWh, base charge is 7,300 won, rate per kWh is 280 won.For example, a household consuming 300 kWh in a month will pay a base charge of 1,600 won, and rates of 90 won per kWh for Tier 1 and 180 won per kWh for Tier 2, resulting in a total electricity bill of 37,600 won (=1,600 + 200×90 + 100×180).Recently, Country X introduced a “Cool Summer Policy” for electricity used in the summer, changing the tiers to ‘up to 300 kWh’, ‘over 300 kWh up to 450 kWh’, and ‘over 450 kWh’, while maintaining the same rate structure as before in each tier.<Debate> Alice: In order to ensure a stable electricity supply, power generation facilities must be able to meet the peak hourly electricity demand. The introduction of the Cool Summer Policy will reduce the stability of electricity supply.Bob: Air conditioning is a necessity, not a luxury. To lower the summer electricity bill burden for most households, it would be better to switch from the Cool Summer Policy to a flat rate system with a base charge of 1,600 won and a per kWh rate of 180 won.Charlie: It is better to focus on welfare for vulnerable groups rather than all households. The Cool Summer Policy should be modified so that it applies only to vulnerable groups. <question> Which of the following, as presented in <statements>, are appropriate evaluations of the <Debate> above?<statements> (a) Data showing that peak hourly electricity consumption in Country X occurs in summer weakens Alice’s argument.(b) Data showing that most households consume 400–450 kWh per month weakens Bob’s argument.(c) Data showing that most vulnerable individuals, such as elderly people living alone, use less than 200 kWh per month weakens Charlie’s argument. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Data showing that peak hourly electricity consumption in Country X occurs in summer weakens Alice’s argument.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Data showing that most households consume 400–450 kWh per month weakens Bob’s argument.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Data showing that most vulnerable individuals, such as elderly people living alone, use less than 200 kWh per month weakens Charlie’s argument."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Unlike a flat rate system, a progressive billing system applies different rates for each tier, and even for higher tiers, the lower tier rates are applied cumulatively for the respective amount of consumption in each tier. When the usage range of each tier is expanded by changing the tier criteria, households in higher tiers receive greater discounts. For example, in the Cool Summer Policy, households that originally belonged to Tier 1 before the change already benefit from the lowest rates, so expanding the tier does not affect them. However, households that were in Tier 2 prior to the change enjoy a rate reduction of 90 won (180–90 won) per kWh for usage between 200 and 300 kWh, and also a 700-won decrease in the base charge. Households in what was formerly Tier 3 benefit not only from this but also from a rate reduction of 100 won (280–180 won) per kWh for usage between 400 and 450 kWh, and a 5,700-won decrease in the base charge for households consuming 400–450 kWh. <choices> Explanation (a). Alice claims that if the Cool Summer Policy reduces rates, summer electricity consumption will increase, leading to higher peak hourly demand in summer and thus reduced supply stability. Therefore, if data show that peak hourly demand in Country X is actually highest not in summer, and that even with increased summer consumption due to the policy this ranking does not change, Alice’s argument would be weakened. However, data that show summer peak demand is highest do not weaken Alice’s argument. Thus, (a) is not an appropriate evaluation.(b). Under a progressive system, households with high consumption still enjoy lower rates for their usage in the lower tiers. A household using 400–450 kWh per month will fall into Tier 2 under the Cool Summer Policy, paying a base charge of 1,600 won, 90 won per kWh up to 300 kWh, and 180 won per kWh beyond 300 kWh. Under Bob’s proposed flat rate (1,600 won base, 180 won/kWh for all usage), all consumption is charged at the higher rate, leading to a bigger bill than under the Cool Summer Policy. Therefore, data showing most households are in this range would weaken Bob’s argument. So (b) is an appropriate evaluation.(c). Charlie argues the Cool Summer Policy should target only vulnerable populations for welfare reasons; this only makes sense if vulnerable groups actually benefit. If most vulnerable individuals, such as elderly people living alone, use less than 200 kWh per month, their bills would be unaffected whether the policy applies universally or only to them. Therefore, data showing this would weaken Charlie’s argument. Thus, (c) is an appropriate evaluation.Since only (b) and (c) are appropriate, the answer is ④."
  },
