    "problem_idx": "33",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to properly understand (definition 1) and (definition 2) and the arguments applying these definitions to specific cases, and to derive valid conclusions from them.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "Let us accept the following two definitions. (Definition 1) \"Event Y causally depends on event X\" means that both X and Y actually occurred, and if X had not occurred, Y would not have occurred either. (Definition 2) \"Event X is the cause of event Y\" means that there exists a chain of causal dependence leading from X to Y. As soon as Alice drank a fatal dose of poison, she fell from the 10th floor of a building, hit the ground, and died. The events A~E are as follows: A: Alice drinks the poison B: The poison spreads throughout her body C: Alice falls from the 10th floor of the building D: Alice hits the ground E: Alice's death From C through D to E, all events actually occurred. However, ⓐ B did not actually occur; that is, Alice died before the poison could spread throughout her body. On the other hand, ⓑ \"If C had not occurred, E would not have occurred\" is false. If C had not occurred, the chain of causal dependence from A through B to E would have been realized. Thus, it may seem to follow that ⓒ C is not the cause of E. However, even when Z does not causally depend on X, it is possible that Y causally depends on X, and Z causally depends on Y. If C had not occurred, D would not have occurred, and if D had not occurred, E would not have occurred. <question> Which of the following analyses of the passage above is/are correct according to the <statements> given below? <statements> (a) From the passage, \"Alice's fall from the 10th floor is the cause of her death\" follows. (b) From (Definition 1) and ⓐ, \"No event causally depends on B\" follows. (c) From (Definition 1), ⓑ, and \"If C is the cause of E, then E causally depends on C,\" ⓒ follows. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c).",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) From the passage, \"Alice's fall from the 10th floor is the cause of her death\" follows.",
      "statement_2": "(b) From (Definition 1) and ⓐ, \"No event causally depends on B\" follows.",
      "statement_3": "(c) From (Definition 1), ⓑ, and \"If C is the cause of E, then E causally depends on C,\" ⓒ follows."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The sequence of events described in the passage is as follows: - There is a causal flow where C occurs → then D occurs → then E follows - There is a separate flow from A to B - That is, C → D → E, and A → B Among these two flows, the causal flow starting with C all actually occurred, but in the flow from A to B, only B did not actually occur. The sequence of causal dependence from C through D to E all actually happened (only B, shown in blue in the diagram, did not actually occur). And If C had not occurred, D would not have occurred. If D had not occurred, E would not have occurred. Both of these statements hold. However, as in ⓑ, \"If C had not occurred, E would not have occurred\" does not hold. Assume C did not occur, even though it actually did. In that case, Alice would have died from the poison. That is, the chain of causal dependence from A through B to E would have been realized. So, as in ⓒ, it seems that C is not the cause of E. However, ⓒ is not the claim of the passage. As described in the last four lines of the passage, it is not contradictory for the following two statements to be true at the same time: X - Y - Z (1) \"If X had not occurred, Z would not have occurred\" is false. (2) \"If X had not occurred, Y would not have occurred,\" and \"If Y had not occurred, Z would not have occurred\" are both true. Here, (1) corresponds to ⓑ, and (2) to the last sentence of the passage. Therefore, the claim of the passage is the last sentence, not ⓒ. <choices> Explanation (a) According to the last sentence of the passage, the following holds: (1) If C had not occurred, D would not have occurred. (2) If D had not occurred, E would not have occurred. Applying (Definition 1) to (1), (2), and \"From C through D to E, all actually occurred\" from the passage, we get the following: (3) D causally depends on C. (4) E causally depends on D. Finally, applying (Definition 2) to (3) and (4), we get: (5) C is the cause of E. That is, Alice's fall from the 10th floor is the cause of her death. This is also the overall conclusion of the passage. Thus, (a) is a correct analysis. (b) If we insert event B into (Definition 1), it reads as follows: Y causally depends on B if and only if (B occurred & Y occurred & if B had not occurred, Y would not have occurred). However, according to ⓐ, the underlined part is false, so the right side of the biconditional above is always false. Therefore, for any event Y, the left side of the biconditional above is always false. So, for any event Y, \"Y causally depends on B\" is false. That is, no event causally depends on B. (b) is a correct analysis. (c) As in the explanation of (b), (Definition 1) is a biconditional. Inserting events C and E into (Definition 1), it reads: E causally depends on C if and only if (C occurred & E occurred & if C had not occurred, E would not have occurred). However, according to ⓑ, the underlined part is false, so the right side of the biconditional above is always false and, therefore, the left side is always false. That is, E does not causally depend on C. If we add \"If C is the cause of E, then E causally depends on C\" (which is logically equivalent to its contrapositive, \"If E does not causally depend on C, then C is not the cause of E\"), we can conclude \"C is not the cause of E,\" which corresponds to ⓒ. Therefore, ⓒ can be deduced. Thus, (c) is a correct analysis. Since all of (a), (b), and (c) in <choices> are correct analyses, the answer is ⑤."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_34",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "34",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to correctly judge whether experimental results strengthen or weaken a given hypothesis.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "To test the following hypotheses, [Experiment 1] and [Experiment 2] were conducted.(Hypothesis 1) People choose actions that maximize their expected payoff*.(Hypothesis 2) The more people believe that their advantageous but unfair actions are unlikely to be detected by the other party, the more likely they are to engage in such actions.[Experiment 1] Participants are randomly assigned as proposers and responders. The proposer is to suggest one of the following ways to split 10,000 won, which they will receive from the experimenter, with the responder:• 5-5 Option: The proposer and responder each get 5,000 won.• 8-2 Option: The proposer gets 8,000 won and the responder gets 2,000 won.• Coin Option: Toss a fair coin. If heads, the 5-5 option applies; if tails, the 8-2 option applies.The responder can accept or reject the proposer’s offer. If the responder accepts the proposed 5-5 or 8-2 option, the money is split as offered. If the Coin Option is proposed and the responder accepts, the experimenter tosses the coin in front of the responder and they split the money according to the coin’s outcome. If the responder rejects any offer, both proposer and responder receive 0 won. The rules are provided to the participants in advance.[Experiment 2] Everything is the same as [Experiment 1] except for the following. If the proposer chooses the Coin Option, the experimenter tosses the coin without the responder’s knowledge and informs the responder that either the 5-5 or 8-2 option has been offered, depending on whether the coin came up heads or tails. For example, if the responder is offered the 8-2 option, they do not know whether the proposer selected it directly or the coin toss resulted in the 8-2 outcome.* Expected payoff: The sum of the values obtained by multiplying the “payoff received in each scenario due to an action” by the “probability the person believes each scenario will occur.”<question> Which of the following <statements> is/are appropriate evaluation(s) of the passage above? Choose as listed from among <statements>.<statements>(a) If 60% of responders rejected the 8-2 offer in [Experiment 1], (Hypothesis 1) is weakened.(b) In [Experiment 1], if a proposer believes that the probabilities of the responder accepting the 5-5, 8-2, and Coin Options are 100%, 20%, and 80%, respectively, and chooses the Coin Option, (Hypothesis 1) is strengthened.(c) If participants believe that the 5-5 and Coin Options are fair but the 8-2 option is unfair, and if the rate of proposers choosing the 8-2 Option is higher in [Experiment 2] than in [Experiment 1], then (Hypothesis 2) is strengthened. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c).",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(s) of the passage above? Choose as listed from among <statements>.<statements>",
      "statement_2": "(a) If 60% of responders rejected the 8-2 offer in [Experiment 1], (Hypothesis 1) is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(b) In [Experiment 1], if a proposer believes that the probabilities of the responder accepting the 5-5, 8-2, and Coin Options are 100%, 20%, and 80%, respectively, and chooses the Coin Option, (Hypothesis 1) is strengthened.",
      "statement_4": "(c) If participants believe that the 5-5 and Coin Options are fair but the 8-2 option is unfair, and if the rate of proposers choosing the 8-2 Option is higher in [Experiment 2] than in [Experiment 1], then (Hypothesis 2) is strengthened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "(Hypothesis 1) is a common-sense view that people act to maximize their expected payoff. (Hypothesis 2) states that people will choose unfair actions that benefit themselves when they think such unfairness is unlikely to be detected by the other party.In [Experiment 1], the proposer chooses one of three possible options:5-5 Option: Both proposer and responder get 5,000 won.8-2 Option: The proposer gets 8,000 won, the responder gets 2,000 won.Coin Option: A fair coin is tossed. If heads, the 5-5 Option is selected; if tails, the 8-2 Option is selected.The responder can accept or reject the offer. If rejected, both get 0 won. If the proposer selects the 5-5 or 8-2 Option and the responder accepts, the money is split as proposed.If the proposer selects the Coin Option and the responder accepts, the experimenter tosses the coin in the responder’s presence; if heads, they split 5,000 won each; if tails, 8,000 won to the proposer and 2,000 won to the responder.In [Experiment 2], just like [Experiment 1], the proposer selects one of the three options. However, if the Coin Option is selected, the experimenter tosses the coin without the responder’s knowledge; if heads, informs the responder the 5-5 Option is being offered; if tails, informs the responder of the 8-2 Option. Everything else proceeds as in [Experiment 1].For example, when the responder is offered the 8-2 Option, they do not know if the proposer chose it directly or if it was the result of a coin toss. The proposer also knows that the responder cannot distinguish the source of the offer. <choices> Explanation:(a) In [Experiment 1], if the responder is offered the 8-2 Option, their expected payoff is 0 won if they reject and 2,000 won if they accept. According to (Hypothesis 1), which states people act to maximize expected payoff, the responder should accept the 8-2 offer. Therefore, if a majority—60% of responders—reject the offer, (Hypothesis 1) is weakened. Thus, (a) is an appropriate evaluation.(b) In [Experiment 1], if a proposer believes the responder will accept the 5-5, 8-2, and Coin Options with probabilities 100%, 20%, and 80%, respectively, the expected payoffs for each are:5-5 Option: 5,000 × 1.00 = 5,000 won8-2 Option: 8,000 × 0.20 = 1,600 wonCoin Option: {(5,000 × 0.5) + (8,000 × 0.5)} × 0.8 = (2,500 + 4,000) × 0.8 = 6,500 × 0.8 = 5,200 wonIf the proposer chooses the Coin Option, which yields the highest expected payoff, this aligns with (Hypothesis 1)—the principle of maximizing expected payoff. So (b) is an appropriate evaluation.(c) In [Experiment 1], the responder knows which option the proposer chose. In [Experiment 2], however, when offered the 8-2 Option, the responder cannot know if it was chosen directly by the proposer or resulted from the coin toss. Therefore, in [Experiment 2], the proposer can obscure the fact that they offered the 8-2 Option directly. That is, the proposer can believe that their unfair action (offering the 8-2 Option) is less likely to be detected by the other party. In [Experiment 1], such belief is not possible. Thus, if the rate of proposers choosing the 8-2 Option is higher in [Experiment 2] than in [Experiment 1], (Hypothesis 2) is strengthened. So (c) is also an appropriate evaluation.All of (a), (b), and (c) are appropriate evaluations, so the correct answer is ⑤."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_35",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "35",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to judge whether a hypothetical experimental result weakens a theory about what a concept is.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "<Theory> The concept of A consists of the characteristics that define A, that is, the characteristics that constitute the necessary and sufficient conditions for something to be A. For example, if the necessary and sufficient condition for an entity to be a “bachelor” is to be an unmarried man, then for an entity to be a bachelor, he must be both unmarried and male, and all entities who are both unmarried and male are bachelors. In this case, the concept of bachelor is composed of the characteristics of being unmarried and being male. If someone possesses the concept of A, they would use the concept of A to determine whether a specific entity belongs to category A or not. The time it takes to determine, using the concept of A, whether an entity falls under A is the sum of the time required to check whether that entity possesses each of the defining characteristics of A. <Experiment> Scientists presented participants with various kinds of animals, and asked them to perform a task to judge whether each animal was a bird. After posing questions like “Is x a bird?” they measured the time taken for participants to answer. The results showed that the average response time to say that a sparrow is a bird was 0.4 seconds, while for a penguin, it was 1.4 seconds on average. <question> Which of the following, as found among <statements>, is an appropriate evaluation of <Theory>? <statements> (a) If participants did not possess the concept of bird and answered based on the feel or impression of the words “sparrow” and “penguin,” then the results of <Experiment> do not weaken <Theory>. (b) If the time taken to confirm whether a sparrow and a penguin possess each characteristic that constitutes the concept of bird differs, then the results of <Experiment> weaken <Theory>. (c) If people who think that the concept of human is defined as “rational animal” take less time to judge whether an entity is a human than to judge whether the same entity is an animal, <Theory> is weakened. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If participants did not possess the concept of bird and answered based on the feel or impression of the words “sparrow” and “penguin,” then the results of <Experiment> do not weaken <Theory>.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If the time taken to confirm whether a sparrow and a penguin possess each characteristic that constitutes the concept of bird differs, then the results of <Experiment> weaken <Theory>.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If people who think that the concept of human is defined as “rational animal” take less time to judge whether an entity is a human than to judge whether the same entity is an animal, <Theory> is weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "According to <Theory>, a concept is, in effect, equivalent to a definition: the concept of A consists of the characteristics that serve as the necessary and sufficient conditions for something to be A. A person who possesses the concept of A will use it to determine whether a particular entity belongs to A. Therefore, by measuring the time taken to categorize using the concept, <Theory> can be evaluated. The <Experiment> presents, in a simplified manner, a psychological experiment that demonstrates the so-called “typicality effect.”Explanation for <choices>: (a) If the participants did not possess the concept of bird, then they did not use the concept of bird in the categorization task. <Experiment> can only be used to evaluate <Theory> if the participants answered using the concept of bird. Therefore, if participants answered based on the impression the language gave, rather than using the concept, the results of <Experiment> do not weaken <Theory>. (a) is an appropriate evaluation. (b) Suppose the concept of bird consists of characteristic X and characteristic Y. The results of <Experiment> show that answering whether a sparrow is a bird is faster than answering whether a penguin is a bird. Thus, only if the time it takes to check whether a sparrow and a penguin possess X and Y is the same, or shorter for the penguin, would <Experiment> weaken <Theory>. If the time taken to check each characteristic differs, and the time is shorter for the sparrow, then <Theory> is still compatible with the results of <Experiment>. Therefore, the results of <Experiment> do not weaken <Theory>. (b) is not an appropriate evaluation. (c) People who think the concept of human is defined as a rational animal would need to check whether an entity is rational and whether it is an animal to judge it as human. Therefore, the time required to judge whether something is human cannot be shorter than the time required to judge whether it is an animal. If the opposite were observed, <Theory> would be weakened. (c) is an appropriate evaluation. Therefore, among the <choices>, only (a) and (c) are appropriate evaluations. The correct answer is ③."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_36",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "36",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand two competing hypotheses regarding the origin of the tiger chameleon living in the Seychelles Islands and to find evidence that strengthens or weakens each hypothesis.",
    "domain": null,
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "In the Seychelles of the Western Indian Ocean lives an endemic species known as the ‘tiger chameleon.’ However, the Seychelles is a remote location, approximately 1,100 km northeast of Madagascar—a large island off the southeastern coast of Africa—and about 2,800 km west of India. How did such a small animal, unable to fly nor particularly skilled at swimming, come to inhabit this place? Two explanations have been presented regarding this question. One is that ⓐ ‘the ancestors of the tiger chameleon originally lived in their current location, but became isolated on islands as the continents separated and drifted.’ The Seychelles was originally part of the supercontinent Gondwana together with Africa, India, and Madagascar; as India-Madagascar and Africa separated, followed by the split between India and Madagascar, and finally the split between India and the Seychelles, the islands reached their current position. According to this explanation, the ancestor of the tiger chameleon evolved independently after the Seychelles separated from other regions. The other explanation, ⓑ, is that ‘the ancestor of the tiger chameleon reached the Seychelles by rafting on floating branches or similar debris from rivers or coasts on Madagascar or Africa.’ According to this, the ancestor originally lived in Africa or Madagascar, and after events such as flooding near its habitat washed it out to sea, it migrated to the Seychelles on floating debris, and then evolved independently. <question> Which of the following <statements> correctly assess ⓐ and ⓑ? <statements> (a) The fact that there are chameleon species that inhabit only the Comoros—a remote island formed by undersea volcanic activity and never connected to a continent—supports ⓐ.(b) If there is research showing that since the Seychelles split from India, the ocean currents in the Western Indian Ocean have flowed from west to east, this would weaken ⓑ.(c) If there is research showing that the most recent common ancestor of East African chameleons and tiger chameleons appeared later than the most recent common ancestor of Madagascan chameleons and tiger chameleons, this would weaken ⓐ but not weaken ⓑ. <choices>① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) The fact that there are chameleon species that inhabit only the Comoros—a remote island formed by undersea volcanic activity and never connected to a continent—supports ⓐ.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If there is research showing that since the Seychelles split from India, the ocean currents in the Western Indian Ocean have flowed from west to east, this would weaken ⓑ.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If there is research showing that the most recent common ancestor of East African chameleons and tiger chameleons appeared later than the most recent common ancestor of Madagascan chameleons and tiger chameleons, this would weaken ⓐ but not weaken ⓑ."
    },
    "original_rationale": "According to ⓐ, the separation of continents influenced the evolution of the tiger chameleon. The order in which the continents separated from the Seychelles was ‘Africa → Madagascar → India’, so the order of divergence of chameleons living in these regions and the tiger chameleon should be the same. However, according to ⓑ, the tiger chameleon came to inhabit the Seychelles independently of continental drift, so the divergence order need not match that of ⓐ. In addition, ⓑ includes the claim that even animals not adept at swimming can occasionally colonize remote islands by chance. <choices> Commentary(a) If there are chameleon species inhabiting only a remote island, such as the Comoros, which was formed by undersea volcanic eruptions and was never connected to a continent, those species must have migrated there from elsewhere. This strongly suggests that long-distance dispersal of chameleons is possible. Therefore, (a) actually strengthens ⓑ—the claim that the Seychelles tiger chameleon arrived from outside—but does not strengthen ⓐ. Thus, (a) is not a proper assessment.(b) According to ⓑ, the ancestors of the tiger chameleon living in Africa or Madagascar would have to move eastward to the Seychelles on floating debris. Thus, if the ocean currents flowed from west to east, it would make such a journey easier (see the figure above). Therefore, such research would not weaken ⓑ but rather strengthen it. Thus, (b) is also not a proper assessment.(c) According to ⓐ, since Africa separated from the Seychelles before Madagascar did, chameleons in East Africa would have diverged earlier and evolved independently. Therefore, the most recent common ancestor of the Seychelles tiger chameleon and Madagascar chameleons should have emerged later than that of the tiger chameleon and East African chameleons. Thus, if research showed the reverse, ⓐ would be weakened. In ⓑ, the claim is that the ancestor immigrated after the Seychelles had settled as an island, regardless of the order of continental separation. Thus, if East African chameleons migrated to the Seychelles by rafting, the most recent common ancestor of the tiger chameleon and East African chameleons would have appeared after that of the tiger chameleon and Madagascar chameleons. Such results actually strengthen ⓑ but, at the very least, do not weaken it. Thus, (c) is a proper assessment.Of the <choices>, only (c) is a proper assessment, so the correct answer is ②."
  },
  {
    "id": "2021_37",
    "year": "2021",
    "problem_idx": "37",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to determine whether empirical evidence strengthens or weakens Lavoisier's proposed hypothesis.",
    "domain": null,
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "At the end of the 18th century, the French chemist Lavoisier argued that the combustion of a substance was a process in which the substance combined with another substance he named “oxygen.” However, this claim met with opposing arguments that it could not explain why heat was generated when a substance combined with oxygen. In response, he made the following assumptions: First, heat is actually a massless substance called “caloric,” and the generation of heat is a process by which caloric, which had been combined with a substance, is released. Second, gases contain far more caloric than solids or liquids. The reason why water turns into steam when an enormous amount of heat is supplied is because water and a large amount of caloric combine together. Similarly, gaseous oxygen is also a compound of oxygen and caloric. Based on these two assumptions, Lavoisier claimed that ‘ⓐ in the process of combustion, the oxygen in gaseous oxygen combines with the burning substance to form a compound, but the caloric in gaseous oxygen does not combine with the substance and escapes into the air, thus generating heat.’<question> Which of the following from <statements> are appropriate evaluations of ⓐ?<statements> (a) The fact that when many solid substances combust, heat is generated and gas is produced at the same time, strengthens ⓐ.(b) The fact that gunpowder, which contains compounds of oxygen, can combust explosively and release a massive amount of heat even without gaseous oxygen, weakens ⓐ.(c) The fact that, no matter how much heat generated during the combustion process is released into the air, the mass of air does not increase, weakens ⓐ. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) The fact that when many solid substances combust, heat is generated and gas is produced at the same time, strengthens ⓐ.",
      "statement_2": "(b) The fact that gunpowder, which contains compounds of oxygen, can combust explosively and release a massive amount of heat even without gaseous oxygen, weakens ⓐ.",
      "statement_3": "(c) The fact that, no matter how much heat generated during the combustion process is released into the air, the mass of air does not increase, weakens ⓐ."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Lavoisier’s theory of combustion was accepted because of its strong explanatory power concerning the change in mass during the process of combustion. However, there were several weaknesses in his theory, one of which was the difficulty in explaining why heat is generated in the process of combustion. He proposed theory ⓐ, in which gaseous oxygen contains caloric, and during combustion, caloric escapes into the atmosphere and thus causes heat to be released. Even at the time, his theory was subject to criticism. According to ⓐ, the reason heat is generated in the process in which gaseous oxygen combines with a substance is that the caloric within the gaseous oxygen escapes into the air. Note that Lavoisier’s concept of caloric is not equivalent to the modern scientific concept of energy. Caloric was considered a type of material that could combine with other substances (e.g., oxygen) to form a compound; a gas, in this view, was itself a compound resulting from a sufficient quantity of caloric binding to a material. Thus, unlike in modern science, for Lavoisier a gas was a type of compound. <choices> Explanation (a) In Lavoisier’s theory of combustion, in the process of combustion, a substance combines only with oxygen. In this process, the caloric contained in gaseous oxygen escapes into the air, generating heat. This may be represented as: Substance + gaseous oxygen (oxygen + caloric) → oxide (substance + oxygen) + released caloric However, let us consider that a solid substance such as coal combusts and produces a gaseous compound. This is a process in which a solid substance containing little caloric is converted into a gaseous compound containing much more caloric, so it would have to combine with both oxygen and caloric. This process can be represented as: solid substance + gaseous oxygen (oxygen + caloric) → gaseous oxide (substance + oxygen + caloric) or solid substance + gaseous oxygen (oxygen + caloric) → gaseous oxide (substance + oxygen + caloric) + a small amount of remaining caloric This would result in little or no caloric escaping to the outside, so little or no heat should be generated in the combustion process. Therefore, the fact that heat is generated and gas is produced when a solid substance combusts does not strengthen ⓐ. (a) is not an appropriate evaluation.(b) ⓐ assumes that the source of heat generated during combustion is the caloric originally contained in gaseous oxygen. However, gunpowder can combust and release large amounts of heat even without gaseous oxygen because it contains oxygen compounds. These compounds exist as solids within the gunpowder and contain little caloric. Thus, the explanation in ⓐ—that heat is generated by the caloric escaping from gaseous oxygen during combustion—is weakened. (b) is an appropriate evaluation.(c) Lavoisier regarded caloric as a massless substance; therefore, even if caloric is released into the air during combustion, the mass of the air does not increase. Thus, the fact that the mass of air does not increase even when heat is released into it does not weaken ⓐ, which seeks the source of generated heat in the caloric combined in gaseous oxygen during combustion. (c) is not an appropriate evaluation.Only (b) is an appropriate evaluation in <choices>, so the correct answer is ②."
  },
  {
    "id": "2022_01",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "1",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to read a given text containing a specific viewpoint on the implications of advancements in neuroscience for law, and to determine what neuroscience findings would strengthen or weaken this viewpoint.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "Some people believe that in the not-so-distant future, if neuroscience is able to find the cause of all behavior within the brain, the practice of holding people legally responsible and punishing them will fundamentally change. Their view is that if a person’s criminal behavior is determined by causes in the brain, rather than stemming from free will, then it is not possible to hold that person responsible and punish them. However, this is a misconception arising from a misunderstanding of the law. The law assumes that people generally have the ability to make rational choices. There is general agreement that in order for someone to be exempt from legal responsibility, it must be proven that \"the defendant lacks the capacity for rational action.\" The capacity for rational action here refers to the ability to act in ways that achieve one’s desires based on one’s own beliefs. Neuroscience may be able to help determine whether a person who committed a crime was rational at the time of the crime. However, unless neuroscience shows that people in general do not meet this minimum standard of rationality, it cannot justify a fundamental change in the way the law approaches responsibility. The law is not concerned with whether people possess metaphysical free will or not. The only concern of the law is whether people meet the minimum standard of rationality. <question> Which of the following statements in <statements> is correct as an evaluation of the above passage?<statements> (a) If neuroscience reveals that things like human beliefs or desires play no role in causing behavior, the argument of this passage would be weakened.(b) If neuroscience reveals that the very capacity for rational action in humans itself arises from the biological properties of brains evolved in a certain way, the argument of this passage would be weakened.(c) If neuroscience reveals that a large proportion of those who have committed crimes share common neural mechanisms that cause criminal behavior, the argument of this passage would be strengthened. <choices>① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b)④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If neuroscience reveals that things like human beliefs or desires play no role in causing behavior, the argument of this passage would be weakened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If neuroscience reveals that the very capacity for rational action in humans itself arises from the biological properties of brains evolved in a certain way, the argument of this passage would be weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If neuroscience reveals that a large proportion of those who have committed crimes share common neural mechanisms that cause criminal behavior, the argument of this passage would be strengthened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The passage discusses what impact neuroscience could have on the practice of legal punishment if, in the future, it can fully elucidate all causes of behavior. According to the passage, even if neuroscience completely identifies all causes of behavior within the brain, it would have no effect on the practice of holding people legally responsible and implementing punishment. The reason is that the law assumes not that people have metaphysical free will, but that people have at least the minimum capacity for rational action. The minimum capacity for rational action here refers to the ability to act in ways that achieve one's desires, based on one’s beliefs. The passage argues that neuroscience cannot change the practice of legal punishment because it is unlikely that neuroscience will show that people generally lack this ability. <choices> Explanations (a): According to the passage, the law sees it as sufficient for punishment if the person who committed the crime had the capacity for rational action at the time. The capacity for rational action here means the ability to act in ways that achieve one’s desires based on one’s beliefs. However, if neuroscience shows that beliefs or desires play no role in causing behavior, this effectively shows that humans do not have the capacity for rational action. Therefore, the argument of the passage—that neuroscience cannot change the practice of legal punishment—would be weakened. Thus, (a) is a correct evaluation.(b): According to the passage, the only way neuroscience could change the practice of legal punishment is by showing that humans lack the capacity for rational action. Demonstrating that the capacity for rational action itself arises from biological properties of the brain that evolved in a particular way merely reveals its cause, not that people lack such capacity. Therefore, even if neuroscience shows that the human capacity for rational action is rooted in biological properties of the brain, the argument of this passage is not weakened. Hence, (b) is not a correct evaluation.(c): Suppose that a large proportion of people who committed crimes share common neural mechanisms that cause criminal behavior. This may enhance the argument that many offenders lack the capacity for rational action. Therefore, this does not strengthen the position that neuroscience cannot change the practice of legal punishment. (c) is not a correct evaluation.Since only (a) is a correct evaluation among the <choices>, the answer is ①."
  },
  {
    "id": "2022_03",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "3",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to properly understand the differences among various views regarding the grounds for judgments on the unconstitutionality of laws, and to apply them to <situations> to make correct judgments.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "The Constitution is the highest law, establishing the fundamental values of the nation; if a statute violates the Constitution, that law becomes null and void. The question here is which aspect of a statute provides grounds for judging its unconstitutionality. One might say that the literal meaning of the legal text is the core aspect that serves as the basis for unconstitutionality, but in reality, while the Constitution prohibits discrimination, it is rare for a statute to explicitly contain words or sentences that say \"discriminate.\" Fundamentally, the aspect of a law that is judged as unconstitutional is ⓐ ‘the direct consequence that is expected when the legal sentence representing the statute is applied to a specific case.’ For example, if Legal Sentence A contains content punishing those who commit adultery, the deciding aspect for the constitutionality of the law represented by A is the punishment imposed on those who commit adultery as a result of applying A. Some argue that we must examine ⓑ 'the impact that the enforcement of the statute has on the entire society.' For instance, in considering whether a statute giving extra points to a certain group in employment is unconstitutional due to discrimination, it is said that one must also observe the impact such granting of extra points has on others in the society. On the other hand, some still seek the decisive aspect for judgment of unconstitutionality in the meaning of the legal sentence, yet claim that the meaning of the legal sentence is ⓒ 'the contextual meaning that the legal sentence conveys within the context of the society’s history.' Whether a law represented by a legal sentence establishing a women-only educational institution violates the constitutional prohibition on discrimination depends on whether the establishment of such an institution aims to uplift women's status in the given country or is grounded in a historical context of separation and discrimination against women. <Situation> In Country X, after experiencing numerous wars, the national flag has become a symbol of the nation’s very existence, and flag burning is considered a criminal act that violates constitutional order, as it is regarded as an act undermining the authority of the state. However, when Country X’s parliament legislated Law L, represented by Legal Sentence R, to punish those who burn the national flag in order to protect the dignity and authority of the flag, acts of flag burning—which had almost never occurred previously—became frequent as opponents of the law protested, and sympathizers with the act of flag burning also grew in number. <question> From the following <statements>, which ones correctly evaluate the <situation>? <statements> (a) If ⓐ is considered the core aspect providing grounds for judgment of unconstitutionality, then Law L in Country X is unconstitutional.(b) The aspect ⓑ of Law L does not align with the legislative purpose of L as represented by R.(c) If ⓒ is considered the core aspect providing grounds for judgment of unconstitutionality, then Law L in Country X is unconstitutional. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If ⓐ is considered the core aspect providing grounds for judgment of unconstitutionality, then Law L in Country X is unconstitutional.",
      "statement_2": "(b) The aspect ⓑ of Law L does not align with the legislative purpose of L as represented by R.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If ⓒ is considered the core aspect providing grounds for judgment of unconstitutionality, then Law L in Country X is unconstitutional."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The literal meaning of the legal sentence, the direct result of applying the sentence in specific cases, the broad social impact when the law is enforced in society, and the historical context that the legal sentence has within the society—all these provide grounds for determining whether a law is unconstitutional. In the <situation>, a statute was enacted to punish acts that, under Country X’s constitutional order, are considered crimes; however, the social impact of the law’s enforcement actually runs counter to the original legislative intent.Explanation of <choices> (a) The direct result of applying R is punishing those who commit the act of burning the flag. Since there is social consensus in Country X’s constitutional order that burning the flag is a crime, if ⓐ is considered the core aspect for judging unconstitutionality, Law L would be judged not to be unconstitutional. Thus (a) is not a correct evaluation.(b) The aspect ⓑ of Law L refers to the impact of L’s enforcement on the entire society. Here, the enforcement of L has led to an increase in acts of flag burning—which were previously rare—and greater support for such acts, thus running counter to L’s original legislative purpose of protecting the dignity and authority of the flag. Thus (b) is a correct evaluation.(c) The viewpoint that sees ⓒ as the core aspect looks at the historical context of R in Country X. Given that, through repeated wars, Country X’s flag has come to symbolize national authority and dignity, flag burning is undoubtedly an anti-state, anti-constitutional act. Therefore, a law punishing it cannot be considered unconstitutional. Thus (c) is not a correct evaluation.Thus, only (b) is a correct assessment, and the answer is ②."
  },
