    "problem_idx": "8",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the content of regulations concerning child abuse crimes and the opinions regarding them, and to use provided research results as arguments for each opinion.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "[Regulation] Article 1 (Definition) “Child” refers to a minor. Article 2 (Physical Child Abuse) Anyone who commits an act of physical abuse by assaulting a child or causing harm to his or her physical health and development shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than 5 years. Article 3 (Sexual Child Abuse) Anyone who commits an act of sexual abuse causing sexual humiliation to a child shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than 6 years. <Review Opinions> Alice: Crimes of child abuse are distinct from general violent crimes in that the guardian, who has a duty of care, inflicts harm upon the person to be protected. Therefore, the child, as the person to be protected, should be excluded from being the subject of the act in Articles 2 and 3, and the subject should be limited to “adults” who are the guardians. Bob: The [Regulation] aims to thoroughly punish the perpetrators of abuse and thereby provide strong protection for children, who are the victims of various abusive acts. Therefore, the subject of the acts in Articles 2 and 3 should be retained as “anyone” as in the current regulation. Charlie: In relation to sexual acts, child victims cannot be treated in the same way as adult victims who possess sexual self-determination. Therefore, it is reasonable to delete the phrase “causing sexual humiliation” from Article 3. <question> Which of the following in <statements> correctly evaluates the <Review Opinions> regarding the [Regulation]? <statements> (a). The research finding that “recently, more minors are entering social relationships in which one minor is the guardian or supervisor of another minor” supports Alice’s opinion. (b). The research finding that “a significant number of perpetrators of child abuse were themselves victims of child abuse as children, so it is impossible to dichotomously distinguish between victims and perpetrators of child abuse” supports Bob’s opinion. (c). The research finding that “recently, cases where minors make sexual requests to other minors, involving the filming of videos, are increasing. Experiences of responding to such requests without any sense of shame or discomfort critically influence the later development of negative self-identity or distorted sexual awareness. Therefore, the need to punish sexual requests between minors as acts of abuse is great”—this research finding supports both Bob and Charlie’s opinions. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) . The research finding that “recently, more minors are entering social relationships in which one minor is the guardian or supervisor of another minor” supports Alice’s opinion.",
      "statement_2": "(b) . The research finding that “a significant number of perpetrators of child abuse were themselves victims of child abuse as children, so it is impossible to dichotomously distinguish between victims and perpetrators of child abuse” supports Bob’s opinion.",
      "statement_3": "(c) . The research finding that “recently, cases where minors make sexual requests to other minors, involving the filming of videos, are increasing. Experiences of responding to such requests without any sense of shame or discomfort critically influence the later development of negative self-identity or distorted sexual awareness. Therefore, the need to punish sexual requests between minors as acts of abuse is great”—this research finding supports both Bob and Charlie’s opinions."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The [Regulation] stipulates “anyone” as the subject of the act, without special restriction, whereas Alice argues that it should be limited to “adults” only. Bob argues that it should remain as is (including minors). Alice bases her argument on the characteristic of the crime that the perpetrator is the guardian with a duty to protect, while Bob uses the purpose of the regulation, which is to provide broad protection to abused children, as his basis. Regarding sexual child abuse, the [Regulation] defines it as “sexual abuse causing sexual humiliation,” but Charlie argues that the expression “causing sexual humiliation” should be deleted. Charlie bases this on the characteristic that children do not possess the same sexual self-determination as adults. Explanation of <choices>: (a). The presented research shows an increase in relationships where the guardian is a minor and the person to be protected is also a minor. Therefore, Alice’s opinion—which presupposes the guardian is an adult and the person to be protected is a minor, and thus proposes excluding minors from being subjects of child abuse—is not supported by this research. (a) is not a correct evaluation. (b). The presented research states that, from a macroscopic perspective, the distinction between perpetrator and victim of child abuse is not always clear. Therefore, Bob’s opinion, which clearly distinguishes perpetrators from victims on the narrow, case-by-case level of specific crimes, is not supported by this research. (b) is not a correct evaluation. (c). The presented research findings can be summarized as follows: ① Even if a sexual request does not cause sexual humiliation, it can still harm the sexual development of minors. ② Sexual requests between minors also need to be punished as abuse. First, Charlie’s opinion—that the phrase “causing sexual humiliation” is unnecessary in cases of sexual abuse against children, who lack full sexual self-determination—is supported by point ①. In addition, Bob’s opinion—that there should be no restriction on the subject of the act in order to thoroughly punish perpetrators, including minors—is supported by point ②. Therefore, (c) is a correct evaluation. Since only (c) is a correct evaluation among the <choices>, the answer is ②."
  },
