    "problem_idx": "12",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the arguments and reasoning of A, B, and C in the debate surrounding the concept of property under X country's criminal law, and based on this, to determine whether a specific object constitutes property.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "Country X’s Criminal Act punishes those who steal another person's property as the crime of theft. Regarding the meaning of “property” under the Criminal Act, Alice, Bob, and Charlie are debating as follows.Alice: I think “property” refers to an “object with economic value,” and here, “economic value” means pure economic value, that is, monetary value. Therefore, under the Criminal Act, property is irrelevant to whether the ownership and transfer of the object are lawful.Bob: I agree with Alice that property does not necessarily have to be lawfully owned or lawfully traded. However, since “economic value,” which is a conceptual element of property, is subjectively attached by the owner, I think that as long as the owner’s intention to possess is expressed—regardless of whether there is any monetary exchange value—such an object should be seen as property under the Criminal Act.Charlie: For \"economic value,” a conceptual element of property, to be recognized, there must be monetary exchange value. But I believe this is a necessary, not a sufficient, condition. In order for something to be property under the Criminal Act, not only must it have monetary exchange value, but its ownership and transfer must also be lawful. <question> Which of the following analyses regarding the above debate is/are correct? Select all correct options from <statements>.<statements> (a) Alice regards narcotics illegally owned by a drug dealer—which are prohibited by law from being owned—as property under the Criminal Act.(b) Bob regards both the narcotics illegally owned by a drug dealer and a fan letter cherished by a celebrity but not subject to transaction as property under the Criminal Act.(c) Charlie regards a fan letter cherished by a celebrity but not subject to transaction as property under the Criminal Act, but does not regard narcotics illegally owned by a drug dealer as property under the Criminal Act. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Alice regards narcotics illegally owned by a drug dealer—which are prohibited by law from being owned—as property under the Criminal Act.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Bob regards both the narcotics illegally owned by a drug dealer and a fan letter cherished by a celebrity but not subject to transaction as property under the Criminal Act.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Charlie regards a fan letter cherished by a celebrity but not subject to transaction as property under the Criminal Act, but does not regard narcotics illegally owned by a drug dealer as property under the Criminal Act."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Alice, Bob, and Charlie agree that, under the Criminal Act, “property” means “an object with economic value.” However, they are debating what exactly constitutes “economic value.” Alice’s position is that economic value means pure economic value, i.e., monetary (exchange) value, and therefore, legitimate ownership is not required for property under the Criminal Act. Bob’s position is that if the owner subjectively attaches value (expressed intention to possess), the object should be regarded as property under the Criminal Act, regardless of whether it has monetary exchange value. Charlie’s position is that, besides monetary exchange value, lawful ownership and transfer must also be permitted. <choices> Commentary:(a) Alice argues that for something to be regarded as property under the Criminal Act, lawful ownership is not necessary and only monetary (exchange) value is required, so she would regard a drug dealer’s narcotics as property under the law. (a) is a correct analysis.(b) Bob’s position is that as long as there is subjective value to the owner, regardless of monetary exchange value, the item is regarded as property under the Criminal Act—so both a drug dealer’s narcotics and a fan letter cherished by a celebrity would be regarded as property. (b) is a correct analysis.(c) Charlie’s view is that property under the Criminal Act requires not just monetary exchange value but also lawful ownership and transfer. Therefore, a fan letter that cannot be traded lacks exchange value and is thus not property; narcotics prohibited by law also lack lawful ownership, so they are also not property. (c) is not a correct analysis."
  },
  {
    "id": "2022_16",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "16",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to read Socrates' argument concerning the impossibility of false judgment and to evaluate it correctly.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "Socrates: Regarding an object, isn’t it that we either know it or do not know it, one of the two? Then, necessarily, a person making a judgment must be judging about something they know or about something they do not know, correct?Theaetetus: That is necessary.Socrates: And it is impossible for someone to both know and not know an object at the same time, or to not know and know at the same time.Theaetetus: That is so.Socrates: Then, if someone who makes a false judgment is someone who knows the object of their judgment, does that mean that he considers something he knows not as itself, but as something else that he knows? So, even though he knows both, does he end up not knowing both again?Theaetetus: That is impossible.Socrates: If someone who makes a false judgment does not know the object of their judgment, does that mean he thinks of what he does not know as some other thing he does not know? So, is it possible for someone who does not know either you or me to come to the idea that “Socrates is Theaetetus” or “Theaetetus is Socrates”?Theaetetus: How could that be possible?Socrates: Indeed, there is never a case where someone considers what they know to be something they do not know, nor is there a case where someone considers what they do not know to be something they know. So then, how could one make a false judgment? Because we either know an object or we do not know it, and in either case, making a false judgment seems impossible. <question> Which of the following analyses of the dialogue above are correct, as stated in the <statements>? <statements> (a) According to Socrates, even if one knows only 'a' and does not know 'b', one can still make a true judgment such as “a is b.”(b) According to Socrates, if one knows neither 'a' nor 'b', one cannot even make a false judgment such as “a is b.”(c) If it is actually possible to make a false judgment such as “a is b” while knowing both 'a' and 'b', then Socrates’ argument loses its persuasiveness. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) According to Socrates, even if one knows only 'a' and does not know 'b', one can still make a true judgment such as “a is b.”",
      "statement_2": "(b) According to Socrates, if one knows neither 'a' nor 'b', one cannot even make a false judgment such as “a is b.”",
      "statement_3": "(c) If it is actually possible to make a false judgment such as “a is b” while knowing both 'a' and 'b', then Socrates’ argument loses its persuasiveness."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The concept of knowledge at issue in Socrates’ statement “one must know that one does not know” or “know thyself” is not incomplete knowledge but perfect knowledge. The discussion in “Theaetetus” examines Socrates’ concept of ‘perfect knowledge,’ and here, Socrates presents an argument that false judgment is impossible.The structure of the argument Socrates puts forward is as follows:① We either know or do not know objects. (Socrates’ first statement)② If we know all objects, we cannot make a false judgment. (Socrates’ third statement)③ If we do not know any of the objects, we cannot make a false judgment. (Socrates’ fourth statement)④ Therefore, we cannot make a false judgment. (Socrates’ fifth statement)From this, it can be seen that making a false judgment of “a is b” is impossible in cases where one knows both 'a' and 'b', or knows neither 'a' nor 'b'. <choices> Explanation(a): From the given passage, we can infer that making a true judgment is possible when one knows both 'a' and 'b', but we cannot infer that a true judgment can be made when one knows only one of them. If one knows 'a' but does not know 'b', then, for the same reason as in the case of knowing neither, that is, because one cannot make a judgment at all about what one does not know, one cannot make a true judgment such as “a is b.” Therefore, (a) is not a correct analysis.(b): In Socrates’ fourth statement, he says that if one does not know either 'a' or 'b', it is impossible to reach a judgment such as “a is b.” That is, he claims one cannot make such a judgment at all. Therefore, (b) is the correct analysis.(c): In Socrates’ third statement, he asserts that it is impossible to make a false judgment such as “a is b” while knowing both 'a' and 'b'. Therefore, if it were actually possible to do so, Socrates’ argument would not be maintained. Thus, (c) is a correct analysis.Since only (b) and (c) are correct, the answer is ④."
  },
  {
    "id": "2022_17",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "17",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to read texts that understand evil as an independent entity and texts that understand evil as a mere lack, and to grasp what their arguments are.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "A: There are people who claim that evil is not a real existence but merely a privation. However, when it comes to privation, we cannot speak of \"more\" or \"less.\" This is because the statement \"this is lacking\" and the statement \"this is not lacking\" are in a contradictory relationship. In a contradiction, no middle ground is allowed. On the other hand, with respect to existence, we can speak of \"more\" or \"less,\" since there can be degrees of perfection in existence. Then what about evil? Among evil things, some are more evil than others.B: When we say that something is more evil or less evil than another, we are referring to how far removed it is from the good. In this sense, even for concepts that involve privation, such as “inequality” or “dissimilarity,” we can speak of “more” or “less.” That is, we say something is “more unequal” when it is farther from equality, and “more dissimilar” when it is farther from similarity. Therefore, something that is more lacking in goodness, as if it were farther from the good, can be described as “more evil.” A privation is not a property that exists in itself, but only increases or decreases according to the increase or decrease in the cause that produces it. Darkness does not exist or become intensified on its own; rather, the more light is blocked, the darker it becomes, and the farther it is removed from brightness. <question> Which of the following <statements> is correct regarding the evaluations of A and B? <statements> (a) Unlike A, B argues that evil is a privation. (b) A acknowledges the degree of evil, and B agrees with this. (c) The view that good can exist without evil, but evil cannot exist without good, is better supported by B than by A. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Unlike A, B argues that evil is a privation.",
      "statement_2": "(b) A acknowledges the degree of evil, and B agrees with this.",
      "statement_3": "(c) The view that good can exist without evil, but evil cannot exist without good, is better supported by B than by A."
    },
    "original_rationale": "A is an argument that refutes the perspective that evil is not a real existence but merely a privation, while B is an argument that, in order to maintain the privation view, refutes A. The issue at stake in both arguments is the ambiguity of the concept of privation. A understands the relationship of privation with respect to existence simply as the negation of a statement, and holds that, since affirmative and negative statements are contradictory, there can be no “more” or “less” in negation or privation. That is, A claims that in the contradictory statements “it exists” and “it does not exist (is lacking),” there is no room for an intermediate, that is, for “more” or “less.” Nevertheless, the existence of “more evil” and “less evil” is commonly accepted as an empirical fact or in ordinary language, and therefore, A concludes that evil cannot be a mere privation. In contrast, B does not simply understand the relationship of privation with respect to existence as a negation of a statement, but as a state where an essence or property is removed or diminished due to a particular cause. In this sense, degrees are naturally accepted in privation. <choices> Explanation (a) A claims that privation does not accept degrees, but existence does, and since evil accepts degrees, it must be a kind of existence. In contrast, B defends the concept of evil as privation by interpreting privation as something that can accept degrees, opposing A. (a) is a correct evaluation. (b) The fact that evil can be more or less is a key premise in A’s argument. B also agrees with this premise. What B rejects is A’s claim that privation does not accept degrees. Therefore, (b) is a correct evaluation. (c) According to B, privation is a partial negation of existence (or a deleted part of existence), and thus, is a concept dependent on existence. Therefore, B’s view, which sees evil as privation, better supports the idea that good can exist without evil, but evil cannot exist without good. On the other hand, A’s view, which sees evil as a kind of existence, tends to regard good and evil as ontologically equal, thus implying that evil can also exist independently of good. Therefore, (c) is correct. Since all of (a), (b), and (c) are correct, the right answer is ⑤."
  },
  {
    "id": "2022_18",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "18",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to criticize arguments that appear in debates and the ability to determine the necessary and sufficient conditions for each premise to be true.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "Alice: My child, the exam is tomorrow. Why aren't you studying? Bob: Mother, that’s a good question. I have chosen not to study. Alice: Could you give a convincing explanation as to why you’ve made such a surprising choice? Bob: The exam I am taking is designed to rank all test-takers from first to last place. I found out that other test-takers are happy even if their rank goes up just a little. But I do not feel any joy when my rank goes up. And I want more people to experience happiness. So, wouldn't my not studying make other test-takers happy? If I don't study, more students will move up in the rankings. Therefore, not studying is justified. Alice: You’re saying that just by not studying, you can somehow cause others to be happy? It seems to me you’re making a remarkable claim that you can do nothing and yet make others happy. If others are happy because of their own rank, isn't that because they studied? It has nothing to do with you not doing anything. Bob: That's not true, Mother. If I were to study, more people would get a score lower than mine, compared to if I did not study. In that case, wouldn’t my effort take away their chance to experience happiness? <question> Which of the following analyses of this dispute is/are correct according to the <statements>?<statements> (a) If not every means of attaining what one wants is justified just because one desires it, then Bob’s argument is weakened. (b) If it is true that Bob’s score goes up when he studies as compared to not studying, then the premise that more test-takers move up the rankings if Bob does not study is also true. (c) For Alice’s claim that not studying cannot be the cause of others’ happiness to be true, it must be assumed that not doing something cannot be the cause of anything else. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If not every means of attaining what one wants is justified just because one desires it, then Bob’s argument is weakened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If it is true that Bob’s score goes up when he studies as compared to not studying, then the premise that more test-takers move up the rankings if Bob does not study is also true.",
      "statement_3": "(c) For Alice’s claim that not studying cannot be the cause of others’ happiness to be true, it must be assumed that not doing something cannot be the cause of anything else."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Bob’s first argument is as follows: [Premise 1] If I do not study, more test-takers will move up in the rankings. [Premise 2] Test-takers are happy when their rank goes up. [Premise 3] I want more people to experience happiness. [Conclusion] Therefore, not studying is justified. Bob’s second argument is as follows: [Further Premise 1] If I study, more people get a lower score than I do. [Further Premise 2] If people get a lower score than me, they lose a chance to feel happy. [Hidden Conclusion] Therefore, if I study, more people lose the chance to feel happy. Alice’s argument is as follows: [Premise 1] Not studying cannot be the cause of others’ happiness. [Premise 2] The cause of others’ happiness is that they studied. [Hidden Conclusion] Thus, the claim that Bob should not study is unjustified. <choices> Explanation (a) From [Premise 1] and [Premise 2] of Bob’s first argument, we can derive “If I do not study, more people will be happy.” This shows that not studying is taken as a means for Bob to achieve what he wants, namely more people’s happiness. In addition, [Premise 3] is that Bob wants more people to be happy. Therefore, Bob draws the [Conclusion] that the means of not studying is justified in order to achieve his desired end. However, if not every means of attaining what one wants is justified simply by the desire for it, the inference from more people’s happiness (as an end) to not studying (as a means) being justified is weakened. So, (a) is a correct analysis. (b) The relationship between Bob’s increase in score and other test-takers’ changes in rank is logically independent. For example, if Bob is in last place with a very low score, even if he studies and his score rises, there may be no change in other test-takers’ ranks. In this case, “Bob’s score goes up if he studies” may be true, but “If Bob does not study, more test-takers’ ranks go up” would be false. Thus, (b) is not a correct analysis. (c) If the proposition “Not doing something cannot be the cause of anything else” is true, then the proposition “Not studying cannot be the cause of others’ happiness” would also be true. However, the fact that the latter logically follows from the former does not mean that the latter can only be true if the former is true. Even if it is true that not studying cannot be the cause of others’ happiness, it is nevertheless possible that not doing a particular thing can be the cause of some result. So, (c) is not a correct analysis. Therefore, only (a) is the correct analysis, and the answer is ①."
  },
