    "id": "2022_19",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "19",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the given research data and determine whether new evidence from r strengthens or weakens a hypothesis.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "The research team surveyed a group of philosophers and a group of laypeople regarding their agreement with the following three statements.(Statement A) If a claim is true for someone, it is true for everyone.(Statement B) If everyone agrees with a claim, then the claim is true.(Statement C) If a claim is true, it represents a fact.In both groups, the proportion of respondents who agreed with (C) exceeded 80%. For (B), the proportion of those who disagreed was much larger in both groups, but the agreement rate was higher among philosophers. What is interesting is (A): 83% of philosophers agreed with (A), whereas only slightly over 40% of laypeople did, and in fact, a higher proportion of laypeople responded that they disagreed. Where does this difference regarding (A) originate? According to the research team, (A) can be interpreted in one of two ways:[Interpretation 1] If it has been determined that a claim is true, its truth is objective.[Interpretation 2] If someone thinks a claim is true, everyone will agree with them.Saying that the truth of a claim is objective means that its truth is not relative to each individual’s perspective. The research team states, \"ⓐ The reason the proportion of agreement with (A) among laypeople was significantly lower than among philosophers is that philosophers tend to read (A) as [Interpretation 1], while laypeople tend to read it as [Interpretation 2].\" Despite this difference, the research team also believes that \"ⓑ Regarding the objectivity of truth, the opinions of laypeople and philosophers are in accord.\" This is because (A) and (C) are statements that affirm the objectivity of truth, while (B) denies it, and the proportion of agreement with (C) was similarly high among both laypeople and philosophers, while the proportion who disagreed with (B) was also similarly high in both groups. <question> Which of the following evaluations, as given in <statements>, is/are correct regarding the above passage? <statements> (a) If additional research revealed that the vast majority of philosophers responded \"disagree\" to [Interpretation 2], ⓐ would be strengthened.(b) If additional research revealed that the vast majority of laypeople responded \"agree\" to [Interpretation 1], ⓑ would be strengthened.(c) If it were found that the difference in agreement rates with (B) between laypeople and philosophers was due to some philosophers who actually disagreed with (B) mistakenly responding \"agree,\" then ⓑ would be strengthened. <choices>① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If additional research revealed that the vast majority of philosophers responded \"disagree\" to [Interpretation 2], ⓐ would be strengthened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If additional research revealed that the vast majority of laypeople responded \"agree\" to [Interpretation 1], ⓑ would be strengthened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If it were found that the difference in agreement rates with",
      "statement_4": "(B) between laypeople and philosophers was due to some philosophers who actually disagreed with",
      "statement_5": "(B) mistakenly responding \"agree,\" then ⓑ would be strengthened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Presenting statements that either affirm (A, C) or deny (B) the objectivity of truth to philosophers and laypeople, and surveying their agreement, allows one to infer from the results that philosophers and laypeople generally have similar intuitions about truth. However, opinions diverged on (A), and the main content of this passage is to explore why. The passage’s main claim is the hypothesis ⓐ to explain this difference, and ultimately, the claim that philosophers and laypeople agree on the objectivity of truth (ⓑ).(a). The experimental results can be summarized as follows.- Philosophers generally agree with original statement (A), with no mention of Interpretations 1 or 2, disagree with (B), and agree with (C).- Laypeople generally disagree with the original (A), with no mention of Interpretations 1 or 2, disagree with (B), and agree with (C).Furthermore, according to ⓐ, based on the passage’s information, the responses are as follows:- Philosophers agree with original (A), agree with Interpretation 1 of (A), do not mention Interpretation 2, disagree with (B), and agree with (C).- Laypeople do not mention original (A), agree with Interpretation 1 (b), disagree with Interpretation 2, disagree with (B), and agree with (C).ⓐ is the hypothesis that \"laypeople presented negative opinions on (A), not because their views differ from philosophers regarding (A) itself, but because their interpretation differs.\" Therefore, if in the above response table the philosophers and laypeople match (i.e., if a is \"disagree,\" b is \"agree\"), then ⓐ is further strengthened. Thus, if the evidence in (a) is obtained and a becomes \"disagree,\" ⓐ is strengthened. Thus, (a) is a valid evaluation.(b). According to the passage, the evidence supporting ⓑ is that for (C), which affirms the objectivity of truth, the agreement rate among philosophers and laypeople was similarly high, and for (B), which denies it, the disagreement rate was similarly high in both groups. Meanwhile, [Interpretation 1] explicitly affirms the objectivity of truth. Therefore, if laypeople—who had a high rate of disagreement with (A)—are found to agree with [Interpretation 1], it provides further evidence that laypeople, like philosophers, agree with statements affirming the objectivity of truth. Thus, ⓑ is strengthened. (b) is a correct evaluation.(c). According to the passage, for (B), the majority of both philosophers and laypeople disagreed, but the agreement rate was higher among philosophers. However, if it is discovered that, as described in (c), some philosophers who actually disagreed accidentally responded \"agree,\" then the agreement and disagreement rates for (B) among the two groups would become even more similar, thus strengthening ⓑ. (c) is also a correct evaluation.Therefore, since (a), (b), and (c) are all valid evaluations, the answer is ⑤."
  },
