    "id": "2022_21",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "21",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to correctly analyze the argument presented in the statement that names used in all fictional works do not refer to real people.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "When we use the name “Napoleon,” which is the name of a historical figure, in everyday life, this name refers to the real person, Napoleon. However, in fictional works such as the novel War and Peace, in which Napoleon appears as a character, does the name “Napoleon” used there also refer to the real person Napoleon? We naturally have the intuition that it does.But let us imagine an extreme fictional work in which Napoleon appears as an Americano and goes on adventures with coffee friends. Since the Napoleon appearing here bears no resemblance whatsoever to the real person Napoleon, we can conclude that the name “Napoleon” used in this work simply refers to a character in fiction, not the real historical figure.Thus, if we accept the claim that at least in certain works of fiction, the name “Napoleon” does not refer to the actual person, we must accept one of the following two:⑴ In some works of fiction, the name “Napoleon” does not refer to the real person, but in other works of fiction, the name “Napoleon” does refer to the real person.⑵ In all works of fiction, the name “Napoleon” does not refer to the real person.Now, considering theoretical simplicity and unity, unless there is a serious problem with the view in ⑵, we should adopt ⑵ over ⑴. One might think that the intuition that the “Napoleon” used in War and Peace refers to the real Napoleon is problematic and clashes with ⑵, but this can be explained as follows: The “Napoleon” used in War and Peace also refers to a character within the fiction, and because this fictional character Napoleon has features similar to the real historical figure Napoleon, we mistakenly have the intuition that the name refers to the real person. <question> Which of the following analyses of the above passage is/are correct? Choose all that apply from <statements>.<statements>(a) According to this passage, if a name “N” used in someone’s writing refers to a real person, then that writing is not a work of fiction.(b) If there is no problem at all with the view that every instance of “Napoleon” used in any fictional work refers to the real person, then the argument in this passage is weakened.(c) The argument in this passage assumes that, “If a character’s name used in a work of fiction does not refer to a real person, then that character and the real person share no similarities whatsoever.”<choices>① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) According to this passage, if a name “N” used in someone’s writing refers to a real person, then that writing is not a work of fiction.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If there is no problem at all with the view that every instance of “Napoleon” used in any fictional work refers to the real person, then the argument in this passage is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) The argument in this passage assumes that, “If a character’s name used in a work of fiction does not refer to a real person, then that character and the real person share no similarities whatsoever.”"
    },
    "original_rationale": "The passage first considers the case where the Napoleon appearing in a work bears no resemblance to the real person Napoleon, and argues that in such extreme fictional works, it is clear that the name “Napoleon” does not refer to the real Napoleon. Then, if we accept this conclusion, it is argued that the theory claiming that the name “Napoleon” used in all works of fiction does not refer to the real person is simpler and more unified than the competing theory, so we should adopt the former. The passage also explains why, under such a theory, people nevertheless have the mistaken intuition that the name “Napoleon” in a work of fiction refers to the real Napoleon. <choices> Commentary:(a): The passage maintains that any name for a real person does not refer to the actual person as long as it is used in a work of fiction, so from this conclusion it follows that if a name used in some writing refers to a real person, then the writing is not a work of fiction. Thus, (a) is a correct analysis.(b): If there is no problem at all with the view that every instance of “Napoleon” used in any fictional work refers to the real person, contrary to the passage’s argument in the beginning, it means that even in extremely fictional works the name can refer to the real person without any issue. This option would therefore allow us to adopt a position as simple and unified as that of (2) (“In all works of fiction, ‘Napoleon’ does not refer to the real person.”), thereby weakening the passage's argument for (2) based on simplicity and unity. Thus, (b) is a correct analysis.(c): The claim, “If a character’s name used in a work of fiction does not refer to a real person, then that character and the real person share no similarities whatsoever,” is, according to the passage, false. This is evident since the passage claims that although the Napoleon in War and Peace is similar to the real person, the name “Napoleon” used in War and Peace still does not refer to the real person. Thus, (c) is not a correct analysis.Therefore, only (a) and (b) are correct, so the answer is ③."
