    "id": "2022_26",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "26",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand three perspectives on acceptable actions and to analyze specific cases according to these perspectives.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "Suppose a person P has the ability to either perform or not perform the act of eating meat (Act A) and the act of donating to an animal protection organization (Act B), and for convenience, assume there are no other possible acts. If we disregard any mutual influence between performing A and B and only consider the outcome of each act individually, performing A leads to a bad outcome (－80), and performing B leads to a good outcome (+100). If neither A nor B is performed, the outcome is 0 for each. In this case, there will be four 'action combinations' consisting of acts that P may or may not perform. Each combination also has its own outcome value, which is the sum of the outcomes of the acts comprising the combination. For instance, if P performs A but does not perform B, the outcome value of that action combination is the lowest among the four combinations, －80. If certain conditions are met, all acts belonging to that action combination are permitted, so even A, which independently carries a negative outcome value, could be permissible. Regarding the condition under which acts belonging to an action combination are permitted, Alice, Bob, and Charlie respectively assert the following:Alice: A person's act is permissible only if it belongs to the combination among the possible action combinations, as determined by their abilities, that yields the maximum outcome value, and only in that case.Bob: A person's act is permissible only if it belongs to the combination among those the person is actually inclined to carry out in reality that yields the maximum outcome value, and only in that case. However, although P can in fact choose whether or not to perform A and whether or not to perform B, the combination where P does not perform A but performs B is never a combination that P would choose in reality.Charlie: A person's act is permissible only if it belongs to any of the combinations, among those possible based on their abilities, whose outcome value is 0 or positive, and only in that case. <question> Which of the following analyses about the above debate are appropriate? Choose only those that are correct as they appear in <statements>. <statements>(a) According to Alice and Bob, P’s A can never be permitted in any case. (b) According to Charlie, P’s A can be permitted. (c) According to Charlie, there are two action combinations of P that can be permitted. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) According to Alice and Bob, P’s A can never be permitted in any case.",
      "statement_2": "(b) According to Charlie, P’s A can be permitted.",
      "statement_3": "(c) According to Charlie, there are two action combinations of P that can be permitted."
    },
    "original_rationale": "In the passage, we can see that for P, who can either perform or not perform eating meat (Act A) and donating to an animal protection organization (Act B), there are four possible action combinations and we know the outcome value of each. This can be summarized as follows in <Table 1>.<Table 1>- Action Combination 1 | A: Performed | B: Performed | Outcome value: 20 (＝－80＋100)- Action Combination 2 | A: Performed | B: Not performed | Outcome value: －80 (＝－80＋0)- Action Combination 3 | A: Not performed | B: Performed | Outcome value: 100 (＝0＋100)- Action Combination 4 | A: Not performed | B: Not performed | Outcome value: 0 (＝0＋0)The claims of Alice, Bob, and Charlie about the conditions under which acts belonging to an action combination are permissible are as follows:Alice:• A person's act is permissible only if it belongs to the combination, among those possible given the person's abilities, that yields the maximum outcome value.• Action Combination 3 yields the maximum outcome value.Bob:• A person's act is permissible only if it belongs to the combination, among the options the person is actually inclined to choose in reality, that yields the maximum outcome value.• However, Action Combination 3 is not a combination that P would actually choose in reality.• Therefore, if no other combination is further denied in reality, among the combinations P would actually be inclined to choose, the one that yields the maximum outcome value is Combination 1.Charlie:• A person's act is permissible only if it belongs to any of the possible action combinations, as determined by their abilities, whose outcome value is 0 or positive, and only in that case.• Action Combinations 1, 3, and 4 all have outcome values that are 0 or positive. <choices> Commentary (a) Among the four action combinations, Action Combination 3 is the one with the maximum outcome. Therefore, according to Alice, \"not performing A and performing B\" is permissible, and other acts are not permissible. Thus, according to Alice, performing A is not a permitted act. However, according to Bob, Action Combination 3 is not one that P would actually choose in reality, so unless another combination is denied in reality, among the combinations P would actually consider, the one yielding the maximum value is Combination 1. In this case, according to Bob, it is permissible for P to perform A. Thus, the part of (a) stating “according to Bob, P’s A can never be permitted” is incorrect. Therefore, (a) is not an appropriate analysis.(b) Action combinations with outcome values of 0 or positive are Combinations 1, 3, and 4; of these, Combination 1 includes P performing both A and B. Therefore, according to Charlie, P’s A could be permitted. (b) is an appropriate analysis.(c) According to Charlie, among the possible action combinations, those with an outcome value of 0 or positive are considered permissible. Since Combinations 1, 3, and 4 have values of 0 or positive—a total of 3 combinations—according to Charlie, there are 3 permissible action combinations for P. Thus, (c) is not an appropriate analysis.Therefore, since only (b) among the statements is appropriate, the answer is ②."
