    "original_question": "The Victim Impact Statement (VIS) system provides victims with an opportunity to express the impact they have suffered from a crime during the sentencing phase of a trial. There is a tendency for sentences to be heavier when a VIS is submitted compared to when it is not, and two views have been suggested regarding the reasons for this phenomenon. According to View A, it is not the presence of the VIS itself but the severity of the harm described in the VIS that leads to heavier sentences. According to this view, the more severe the harm, the heavier the sentence, as victims who have suffered more serious harm are more likely to submit a VIS in order to highlight the details of the harm described in the indictment, whereas victims who have not suffered serious harm tend not to submit a VIS. Therefore, it appears as though there is a meaningful relationship between VIS and sentencing. According to View B, not only are judges or jurors influenced by the harm described in the VIS, but they are also influenced by the strong emotions expressed by the victim through the VIS; as a result, the VIS itself induces a heavier sentence. Two research methods, P and Q, have been devised to test the validity of each view.P: Mock jurors, randomly selected, are divided into three groups and provided with objective information about a case.[Group 1] receives a VIS describing emotional injury that is much more serious than generally expected; [Group 2] receives a VIS describing emotional injury that is less serious than generally expected; [Group 3] receives no VIS. The average sentence given by each group is then compared.Q: Mock jurors, randomly selected, are divided into three groups and provided with objective information about a case.[Group 1] is presented with a video of a trial in which the victim reads a serious VIS in a highly emotional manner; [Group 2] is presented with a video of a trial in which the victim reads the same VIS in a calm manner; [Group 3] is presented with a video in which the victim calmly reads a VIS that is less serious than the previous one. The average sentence given by each group is then compared. <question> Which of the statements in <statements> below correctly evaluate the above text? <statements> (a) If, in P, the average sentence of [Group 1] is significantly higher than that of [Group 2], and the average sentence of [Group 2] is significantly higher than that of [Group 3], View A is strengthened.(b) If, in Q, the average sentence of [Group 1] is significantly higher than that of [Group 2], and the average sentence of [Group 2] is significantly higher than that of [Group 3], View B is strengthened.(c) If, in Q, only [Group 1] and [Group 2] are compared as a modified research method, and there is no significant difference in the average sentence between the two groups, View A is weakened. <choices>① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If, in P, the average sentence of [Group 1] is significantly higher than that of [Group 2], and the average sentence of [Group 2] is significantly higher than that of [Group 3], View A is strengthened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If, in Q, the average sentence of [Group 1] is significantly higher than that of [Group 2], and the average sentence of [Group 2] is significantly higher than that of [Group 3], View B is strengthened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If, in Q, only [Group 1] and [Group 2] are compared as a modified research method, and there is no significant difference in the average sentence between the two groups, View A is weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "View A holds that the reason sentences tend to be heavier when a Victim Impact Statement (VIS) is present is not because the VIS itself is presented, but because of the information about the severity of the harm contained within the VIS. According to View A, if the harm is not severe, even if a VIS is submitted, there will be no significant difference in sentencing compared to when no VIS is submitted. Conversely, if the harm is severe, even if a VIS is not submitted, the sentence will not differ significantly from cases where a VIS describing the same harm is submitted. In other words, sentences are influenced by the severity of the harm, regardless of the presence of the VIS. View B holds that judges or jurors are influenced not only by the harm described in the VIS but also by the strong emotions expressed by the victim through the VIS.The P research method is designed to test the validity of View A. It is important to determine that, based on the generally expected level of emotional injury, the severity of the harm each group is exposed to is in the order of [Group 1], [Group 3], and [Group 2]. The Q research method is designed to verify the validity of View B, and seeing how the results differ between [Group 1] and [Group 2] reveals whether the degree of emotional expression by the victim affects sentencing, while comparing [Group 2] and [Group 3] clarifies whether the severity of the harm influences sentencing. <choices> Explanation(a) View A holds that sentencing is influenced by the severity of the harm, not by the presence of the VIS. In P, [Group 1] is exposed—through the VIS—to information indicating the victim suffered much more serious harm than generally expected; [Group 2] is exposed to information showing the victim suffered less harm than generally expected. In [Group 3], since no VIS is provided, the mock jurors rely on the objective information about the case and are likely to assume a harm at the generally expected level. Therefore, the severity of the harm each group is exposed to is [Group 1], [Group 3], [Group 2], in that order. If the severity of the harm influences sentencing, then the average sentence of [Group 1] should be higher than [Group 2], and the average sentence of [Group 2] should be lower than [Group 3]. Thus, if the average sentence of [Group 2] is significantly higher than that of [Group 3], as in (a), it does not support View A. Therefore, (a) is not a correct evaluation.(b) View B holds that not only the harm described in the VIS, but also the strong emotions expressed when delivering the VIS, influence sentencing. If View B is valid, when the VIS content is identical, a strongly emotional delivery will have a greater effect on sentencing than a calm delivery. Therefore, if in Q, the average sentence of [Group 1] (strongly emotional delivery) is significantly higher than that of [Group 2] (same content, calm delivery), it shows that the victim’s emotional expression influences sentencing. [Group 2] and [Group 3] both receive a calmly delivered VIS, so the degree of emotional expression is the same for both groups. Nonetheless, if [Group 2]’s average sentence is significantly higher than [Group 3]’s, it shows that the content of the VIS (the severity of the harm) also influences sentencing. Thus, the result described in (b) shows that both the content and the emotional expression by the victim affect mock jurors’ sentencing decisions, supporting View B. Therefore, (b) is a correct evaluation.(c) View A argues that sentencing is influenced by the severity of the harm, regardless of whether a VIS is presented. Thus, according to View A, if the content of the VIS is identical, the sentencing judgments by jurors should likewise be identical. Therefore, if there is no significant difference in average sentence between [Group 1] and [Group 2], both of whom receive the same content in different emotional deliveries, this supports View A and does not weaken it. Therefore, (c) is not a correct evaluation.Since only (b) is a correct evaluation, the answer is ②."
  },
