    "problem_idx": "29",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to determine whether empirical facts strengthen or weaken a presented theoretical claim.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "Violent and property crimes, which had surged explosively in the United States since the 1960s, entered a sharp declining trend from the early 1990s onwards. Between 1991 and 2012, violent crime decreased by 49% and property crime by 44%. Moreover, this decline was observed in all regions and across all population groups, and the trend has continued up until 2020. In this context, there is the claim ⓐ, ‘that the decline in crime in the United States is closely related to lead exposure.’ According to this claim, from the end of World War II until the early 1970s, the increase in lead emissions from cars was followed by a rise in violent crime. However, after lead began to be removed from gasoline in the 1970s, violent crime subsequently decreased. Tetraethyl lead was developed in the 1920s to prevent engine knocking in gasoline engines, and its use exploded in the postwar period with the popularity of automobiles. Rates of violent and property crime are highest in the late teens to early twenties; unlike adolescents or adults, however, for children, exposure to lead affects brain development and future potential for criminal behavior. In particular, lead is known to induce increased aggression and impulsivity. <question> Which of the following evaluations of the above passage is correct? Select all that apply from <statements>.<statements> (a) The fact that the average blood lead levels of American children aged 1–5 in 2000 had dropped to half the level of 1990 strengthens claim ⓐ. (b) The fact that the sharp decline in violent crime in the US began in the 1990s rather than the 1970s weakens claim ⓐ. (c) The research finding that adolescents in the United States who committed crimes had four times the bone lead content of those who did not strengthens claim ⓐ. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) The fact that the average blood lead levels of American children aged 1–5 in 2000 had dropped to half the level of 1990 strengthens claim ⓐ.",
      "statement_2": "(b) The fact that the sharp decline in violent crime in the US began in the 1990s rather than the 1970s weakens claim ⓐ.",
      "statement_3": "(c) The research finding that adolescents in the United States who committed crimes had four times the bone lead content of those who did not strengthens claim ⓐ."
    },
    "original_rationale": "In the passage, the statement “rates of violent and property crime are highest in the late teens to early twenties; unlike adolescents or adults, for children, exposure to lead affects brain development and future potential for criminal behavior. In particular, lead is known to induce increased aggression and impulsivity” serves as a key clue for solving the problem. From this, we can infer that lead exposure affects the likelihood of criminal behavior in childhood, but its effects emerge roughly 20 years later, when the affected children reach their late teens or early twenties. <choices> Commentary (a) Suppose it is true that the average blood lead level among American children aged 1–5 in 2000 was half the level of a decade earlier in 1990. If claim ⓐ is true, and there is a positive correlation between lead poisoning and criminal behavior, this implies a reduction in the relative size of the population at risk for future crime. Children aged 1–5 in 1990 would likely express potential criminal behavior around 2005–2010, and those aged 1–5 in 2000 would do so around 2015–2020. The passage states that the decline in American crime rates has continued from the early 1990s until 2020. Therefore, the fact that average blood lead levels among 1–5 year-olds in 2000 fell to half the 1990 level strengthens claim ⓐ. Thus, (a) is a correct evaluation.(b) According to the reasoning for ⓐ, lead negatively impacts brain development in children, thus affecting the probability of criminal behavior when they later become adolescents or adults; that is, there should be a time lag between exposure to lead and the manifestation of criminal behavior—about 20 years, until children reach their late teens or early twenties. Therefore, the effect of reducing lead in gasoline in the 1970s should appear some 20 years later, i.e., in the 1990s. Thus, the fact that crime rates started dropping in the 1990s rather than the 1970s is actually consistent with ⓐ, and does not weaken it. Thus, (b) is not a correct evaluation.(c) The claim that the reduction in American crime is closely linked to lead means that there is a positive correlation between lead poisoning and criminal behavior. The research showing that adolescent offenders in the US have much higher bone lead levels than non-offenders supports this correlation and thus strengthens claim ⓐ. Therefore, (c) is a correct evaluation.Among the <choices>, only (a) and (c) are correct, so the answer is ③."
  },
