    "id": "2022_30",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "30",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand arguments for and against the basic income system and to determine whether given economic data strengthens or weakens each of those arguments.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "A: Due to future technological changes such as digital transformation, opportunities to earn income through jobs may decrease. In order to prepare for this, it is necessary to introduce a basic income system which pays the same amount unconditionally to every citizen without any individual conditions. Even if welfare benefits are concentrated on those who are selected as being in social risk, there may still be blind spots, and there is also considerable friction caused by the selection process. Universal provision can alleviate these problems and provide practical help to everyone without any blind spots.B: Although basic income appears to solve poverty by providing a certain amount to everyone, if the basic income is paid only within the limits permitted by the government’s fiscal situation, the benefit level will be too low to effectively address the blind spots.C: If existing welfare systems are reorganized and the public sector is reformed, it would be possible to secure the financial resources for basic income. If everyone receives a certain benefit, polarization will be alleviated. Accordingly, tax resistance will decrease, public support for redistributive policies will increase, and a virtuous cycle is expected in which overall welfare funding will also expand.D: Strengthening the existing social safety net, such as the Basic Livelihood Security System for supporting the living expenses of the poor or employment insurance to compensate for income loss from unemployment, is a more effective alternative for addressing polarization than basic income. <question> Which of the following evaluations regarding the above debate is correct? Choose as it is from the <statements>.<statements> (a) Research findings that more jobs will disappear than be newly created due to the spread of AI with the development of the Fourth Industrial Revolution weaken Alice’s argument.(b) If there is a survey result that emergency disaster relief funds temporarily provided to all citizens to support those suffering from national disasters did not affect the business closure rate among self-employed people, then Bob’s argument is weakened.(c) If, when basic income is provided with funds obtained by integrating existing welfare systems, the income share of the highest income decile significantly decreases compared to the lowest income decile, then Charlie's argument is strengthened and Dave’s is weakened. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Research findings that more jobs will disappear than be newly created due to the spread of AI with the development of the Fourth Industrial Revolution weaken Alice’s argument.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If there is a survey result that emergency disaster relief funds temporarily provided to all citizens to support those suffering from national disasters did not affect the business closure rate among self-employed people, then Bob’s argument is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If, when basic income is provided with funds obtained by integrating existing welfare systems, the income share of the highest income decile significantly decreases compared to the lowest income decile, then Charlie's argument is strengthened and Dave’s is weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Alice and Charlie support the basic income system. Alice argues that because technological changes reduce jobs and prevent people from earning a livelihood, basic income is needed, and that selective welfare benefits fail to help those in the blind spots. Charlie argues that basic income helps alleviate polarization and thus brings about a virtuous cycle in the welfare sector. On the other hand, Bob and Dave oppose basic income. Bob argues that, due to fiscal constraints, the size of basic income is small and thus ineffective in addressing blind spots. Dave argues that targeted welfare systems are more effective at alleviating polarization than basic income. <choices> Explanation (a): Research that finds more jobs disappear than are newly created means that jobs overall will decrease; such results actually strengthen, not weaken, Alice’s argument. So (a) is not a correct evaluation.(b): Temporary national disaster relief payments are not a basic income due to their lack of permanence. Even if such funds share some functions of basic income, the fact that the emergency funds did not affect the business closure rate among self-employed people means they did not have a practical effect on those facing closure. Therefore, such findings do not weaken Bob’s argument that basic income is ineffective at addressing blind spots. (b) is not a correct evaluation.(c): If consolidating existing welfare programs into a basic income reduces the income share gap between the highest and lowest income deciles, this means polarization is being alleviated. Thus, Charlie’s claim (that basic income helps reduce polarization) is strengthened, and Dave’s claim (that basic income is less effective than existing welfare at reducing polarization) is weakened. (c) is a correct evaluation.As only (c) in <choices> is a correct evaluation, the answer is ②."
