    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "ⓐ People often treat robots as if they were human, but there are differences between East and West in such phenomena, and these differences appear to be the result of evolution through culture or cultural factors—in other words, through cultural selection. ⓑ According to one study, when participants were shown an Aibo robot dog wagging its tail and spinning around in response to a person’s actions, Korean participants were more likely than Western participants to answer that people and robots could become friends. ⓒ When participants were shown a scene in which a child tries to break Aibo’s tail and were asked whether they would morally instruct the child not to bully Aibo, Korean participants again gave a much more positive response than their Western counterparts. ⓓ This suggests that the phenomenon of treating robots as if they were human is stronger among Koreans than among Westerners. ⓔ According to the Mohist school, emotions like friendship can only arise when one judges that the object will bring real benefit to oneself. ⓕ According to the Confucianist school, the basis for moral judgment lies in the emotional relationship with the object rather than in some inherent principle within the judging subject. ⓖ If we apply Mohist and Confucianist theory to the relationship between people and robots, people can consider Aibo a friend when they judge that Aibo brings them joy, and can treat Aibo as a subject of moral consideration when they feel sympathy for Aibo. ⓗ There are research findings suggesting that, across Korean society, cultural selection has taken place through the traditions of Mohism and Confucianism, and as a result, the social aspects of general Korean emotions and morality have been partially determined. <question> Which of the following most appropriately analyzes the structure of the above argument? <choices> (in DOT) ① digraph G1 { b -> d; c -> d; e -> g; f -> g; d -> a; g -> a; h -> a; } ② digraph G2 { b -> d; c -> d; e -> g; f -> g; d -> h; g -> h; a -> h; } ③ digraph G3 { b -> d; c -> d; e -> g; f -> g; d -> a; g -> h; h -> a; } ④ digraph G4 { b -> d; c -> d; e -> g; f -> g; g -> a; d -> h; a -> h; } ⑤ digraph G5 { b -> h; c -> h; d -> h; e -> h; f -> h; g -> h; h -> a; }",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "① digraph G1 { b -> d; c -> d; e -> g; f -> g; d -> a; g -> a; h -> a; }",
