    "original_rationale": "This question deals with the phenomenon that Koreans are more likely than Westerners to regard robots as living beings. According to the passage, the reason Koreans are more likely than Westerners to treat robots as if they were living creatures is as follows. Koreans have undergone a process of cultural selection with the traditions of Mohism and Confucianism as selection pressures. Under such traditions, people naturally come to treat robots as if they were human when a certain kind of relationship is established between humans and robots.What you need to pay attention to when solving this question is that the main argument in the passage is composed of two sub-arguments. The first sub-argument is that there is a difference between Koreans and Westerners in treating robots as if they were human. The second is a sub-argument explaining this phenomenon, which is particularly characteristic of Koreans, using theories from Eastern philosophy. Another important point is to identify the relationship between the sentences about Mohism and Confucianism, namely ⓔ, ⓕ, ⓖ, and ⓗ. ⓗ is a claim about cultural selection, whereas ⓖ is a claim that presupposes ⓔ and ⓕ. More specifically, ⓗ is the proposition that the traditions of Mohism and Confucianism have permeated social aspects of Korean culture and emotion, and ⓖ is a proposition regarding Mohist and Confucianist theories. ⓗ and ⓖ are independent of each other; that is, ⓖ can be true even if ⓗ is false, and vice versa.Correct Answer Explanation ① ⓐ corresponds to the main claim running throughout the entire passage. The statements that directly support this claim are ⓓ, ⓖ, and ⓗ. Both ⓓ and ⓖ have their own sub-arguments. The support for ⓓ comes from ⓑ—the claim that Koreans are more likely than Westerners to feel emotional attachment to Aibo—and ⓒ—the claim that Koreans, more than Westerners, treat Aibo as an object of moral judgment. ⓖ is derived from ⓔ and ⓕ. ⓗ has no separate premise.Incorrect Answer Explanation ② ⓗ is a proposition about a particular research finding and is not the main claim running throughout the passage. ③ As explained above, ⓗ and ⓖ are independent. Therefore, one cannot derive ⓗ from ⓖ. ④ ⓗ is a proposition about a particular research finding and is not the main claim running throughout the passage. ⑤ ⓗ cannot be derived from any of ⓑ through ⓖ."
