      "statement_2": "(b) If IL-17 is produced when X1's DC is cultured with Y2's T H 17, but not when Y1's DC is cultured with Y2's T H 17, then ⓐ is reinforced.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If the offspring born from X1 show autistic tendencies and the offspring born from Y2 do not, then ⓐ is reinforced."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Abnormal maternal immune activation consists of three steps. Step 1 is the process where DCs in the gut are activated by a certain viral infection. Step 2 is the process where the activated DC activates the T H 17 immune cells in the gut. Step 3 is the process where these T H 17 cells secrete the IL-17 protein, which ultimately interferes with fetal brain development. Therefore, experimental results showing the production of IL-17 or the phenomenon of offspring mice displaying autistic traits both indicate that both DCs and T H 17 immune cells have been activated, while the opposite results indicate that either the DC or T H 17 immune cells were not activated.The passage presents the hypothesis that gut bacteria are involved in this abnormal immune activation. That is, when the mother harbors certain specific gut bacteria, this process occurs, but when these specific gut bacteria are absent, immune activation does not occur even if infection is present. <choices> Commentary(a) Here, the DC from X1 is the same, but only the T H 17 cells differ. X1 mice were infected with a virus, so their DCs would be activated. If the activated DC activates X2's T H 17 but not Y2's T H 17, it means that X2's and Y2's T H 17 cells differ in their state. The only difference between X2 and Y2 is the presence of specific gut bacteria, so we can infer that X2's T H 17 cells were influenced by the specific gut bacteria prior to isolation. Thus, this result strengthens ⓐ. Therefore, (a) is an appropriate evaluation.(b) Here, the T H 17 from Y2 is the same, but the DCs differ. Both X1 and Y1 were infected with the virus, so their DCs would be activated. In this case, the DCs from these mice should be able to activate Y2's T H 17. If only X1's DC can activate Y2's T H 17 but Y1's DC cannot, it means that X1's and Y1's DCs are somehow different. The only difference is the presence of specific gut bacteria, so we can infer that X1's DCs were influenced by the specific gut bacteria prior to isolation. Thus, this result supports ⓐ. Therefore, (b) is an appropriate evaluation.In (a), it can be inferred that specific gut bacteria affect T H 17, while in (b), specific gut bacteria affect DCs. The experimental results in (a) and (b) are incompatible, but note that either result still strengthens ⓐ.(c) X1 mice have specific commensal bacteria and are infected with a virus, while Y2 mice lack specific commensal bacteria and are not infected with a virus. If immune activation occurs in X1 mice but not in Y2, it is uncertain whether X1's immune activation is due to the existence of specific gut bacteria or some other factor. This is because X1 and Y2 differ both in terms of the presence of specific gut bacteria and viral infection. Therefore, this phenomenon does not strengthen ⓐ. (c) is not an appropriate evaluation.Only (a) and (b) are appropriate evaluations, so the answer is ③."
  },
  {
    "id": "2022_39",
    "year": "2022",
    "problem_idx": "39",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the 'anti-incretin hypothesis' regarding why blood sugar improves after bariatric surgery, and to judge whether given information strengthens or weakens it.",
    "domain": null,
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Problem Solving",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "In the 1970s, American researchers discovered that a surgical procedure, which creates a bypass from the stomach directly to the small intestine, resulted not only in weight loss but also in improved blood sugar control. The research team performed this surgery (bariatric surgery) on 608 severely obese patients and observed that, among those with both severe obesity and diabetes, 83% showed improved blood sugar levels. Furthermore, this improvement in blood sugar occurred within a few days after surgery, rather than as a secondary effect following weight loss.To understand how this mechanism works, it is necessary to understand the function of incretin. Incretin is a substance secreted by the small intestine when food is consumed, which signals the pancreas to secrete insulin. Therefore, when incretin is properly secreted after a meal, blood sugar is well regulated by insulin.Rubino proposed the hypothesis that “ⓐ The improvement in blood sugar regulation after bariatric surgery is due to the existence of a substance in the body that interferes with the effect of incretin.” Ingested food passes sequentially through three parts of the small intestine—the duodenum, jejunum, and ileum—before entering the large intestine. Using experimental mice, Rubino performed bariatric surgery that connected the stomach directly to the jejunum, and observed an improvement in blood sugar without reduced body weight or food intake. Based on this, he argued that bypassing the duodenum may be effective in treating diabetes and inferred the possible existence of “anti-incretin” that interferes with the effect of incretin. <question> Which of the following statements from <statements> is/are correct as an evaluation of the above passage? <statements> (a) If a substance secreted in the duodenum decreases insulin secretion induced by incretin, then ⓐ is strengthened.(b) If a surgery where the stomach is removed and the esophagus is directly connected to the duodenum results in improved blood sugar, then ⓐ is strengthened.(c) If after Rubino's bariatric surgery, a second surgery is performed so that food passing into the jejunum is rerouted back to the duodenum, and the effect of blood sugar improvement disappears, then ⓐ is weakened. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If a substance secreted in the duodenum decreases insulin secretion induced by incretin, then ⓐ is strengthened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If a surgery where the stomach is removed and the esophagus is directly connected to the duodenum results in improved blood sugar, then ⓐ is strengthened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If after Rubino's bariatric surgery, a second surgery is performed so that food passing into the jejunum is rerouted back to the duodenum, and the effect of blood sugar improvement disappears, then ⓐ is weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The digestive tract is connected in the order: esophagus → stomach → small intestine (in the order of duodenum, jejunum, ileum) → large intestine → rectum. Rubino performed a gastric bypass surgery in which the end of the stomach is separated and connected to the jejunum instead of the duodenum, and as described in the passage, observed improvement in blood sugar. In particular, the fact that improvement in blood sugar was observed before weight loss is important, as it suggests that the surgery directly affected blood sugar via a certain mechanism, and not secondarily through weight loss. To understand why such an effect appears, it is necessary to understand the function of incretin. Incretin is secreted by the small intestine when food is eaten, which signals the pancreas to secrete insulin, leading to lower blood sugar after eating.Rubino hypothesized that since his procedure bypasses only the duodenum, some substance secreted in the duodenum must act in opposition to incretin. In other words, in cases of diabetes with high blood sugar, when food is prevented from entering the duodenum, the action of incretin is increased, resulting in improved blood sugar—because this hypothetical “substance in the duodenum” is not secreted. Rubino called this the “anti-incretin” or “Rubino factor,” and argued for this hypothesis.To summarize Rubino’s hypothesis: when food enters the duodenum, anti-incretin is secreted, which balances the incretin that is mainly secreted by the jejunum and ileum. If food does not enter the duodenum, anti-incretin is not secreted, so the relative effect of incretin becomes very large, resulting in better blood sugar control. <choices> Explanation(a) If a substance secreted in the duodenum decreases insulin secretion induced by incretin, that substance would be the one present inside the body interfering with incretin’s effect, so ⓐ is strengthened. Thus, (a) is a correct evaluation.(b) According to the first paragraph, bariatric surgery is a “procedure that creates a bypass from the stomach to the small intestine.” From this, it can be seen that bariatric surgery is a surgery that does not remove the stomach. However, in a surgery where the stomach is removed and the esophagus is directly connected to the duodenum, the stomach is removed. Therefore, the fact that blood sugar is improved by such a surgery is unrelated to the rationale given for improved blood sugar regulation after a non-stomach-removing bariatric surgery (ⓐ), and it neither strengthens nor weakens ⓐ. Thus, (b) is not a correct evaluation.(c) Rubino’s surgery is one that bypasses the duodenum and connects the stomach directly to the jejunum. According to the passage, the result of this surgery is blood sugar improvement without weight loss or decreased food intake. If, after this surgery, a second surgery reroutes food back into the duodenum and the effect of blood sugar improvement disappears, this would strengthen the claim that some substance from the duodenum interferes with incretin’s effect. Therefore, the assertion that blood sugar improvement after bariatric surgery is due to the presence of a substance in the body that interferes with incretin (ⓐ) is strengthened. Thus, (c) is not a correct evaluation.Since only (a) among the choices is a correct evaluation, the answer is ①."
  },
  {
    "id": "2023_02",
    "year": "2023",
    "problem_idx": "2",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand a presented argument and to identify appropriate counter-arguments to it.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "[Law A] Article 1: The Supreme Court is responsible for handling appeals, which are the final instance in the three-tier court system. Article 2: The Supreme Court may dismiss an appeal by judgment without holding a trial if it considers the grounds for the appeal to be inappropriate. Article 3: In a judgment dismissing the appeal pursuant to Article 2, the reasons for such dismissal may be omitted. <Argument> Article 2 of Law A is a provision designed to prevent abuse of the appeal process at the Supreme Court and to faithfully guarantee the right to trial for parties with proper grounds for appeal, through swift handling of cases. In light of the legislative intent and content of the regulation, it is sufficiently reasonable. Article 3 of Law A is a procedural provision required to realize Article 2. That is, requiring reasons to be stated in a judgment of dismissal would only impose unnecessary burdens on the Supreme Court and waste time that should be spent on cases that truly need a trial, so the intent of Article 3 is also justified. Generally, the purpose of requiring reasons in judgments is to allow parties to understand the court’s reasoning and to seek remedies if dissatisfied, but just as the reasons for judgment may be omitted in minor cases such as small claims for the sake of speedy processing, the stating of reasons is not an essential element of a judgment, but is something the court may choose at its discretion. Furthermore, the existence of the Supreme Court does not mean that every case must be guaranteed a trial by the Supreme Court. Therefore, the detailed content of Supreme Court procedures, including whether to state reasons in its judgments, falls within the Court’s discretion. <question> Among the <statements> below, which can serve as counterarguments to the <Argument>? <statements> (a) The right to a trial is the right to demand a judicial act by the state, and the right of claim necessarily involves a corresponding duty on the other party, which includes both the obligation to respond to the claim and the obligation to answer faithfully. (b) The right to a trial is characterized primarily as a right to guarantee access to procedures and procedural fairness, and the legitimacy of a court’s judgment depends on the presentation of grounds for that judgment. (c) The Supreme Court’s judgments serve as the de facto standard for interpreting similar cases and making normative evaluations among the public, and not only the conclusions of judgments but also their reasoning processes perform this function. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c).",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) The right to a trial is the right to demand a judicial act by the state, and the right of claim necessarily involves a corresponding duty on the other party, which includes both the obligation to respond to the claim and the obligation to answer faithfully.",
      "statement_2": "(b) The right to a trial is characterized primarily as a right to guarantee access to procedures and procedural fairness, and the legitimacy of a court’s judgment depends on the presentation of grounds for that judgment.",
      "statement_3": "(c) The Supreme Court’s judgments serve as the de facto standard for interpreting similar cases and making normative evaluations among the public, and not only the conclusions of judgments but also their reasoning processes perform this function."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The <Argument> is in favor of the non-hearing dismissal system for appeals at the Supreme Court and the system of omitting reasons in such judgments. The <Argument> points out that appeals to the Supreme Court can be abused, which could result in situations where the parties who truly need a Supreme Court trial cannot adequately receive one, and asserts that in order to maximize the efficient use of the Supreme Court’s resources, it should be permitted to conclude less significant cases without stating reasons. In particular, it cites the existence of summary cases where omitting the reasons for judgment is already allowed, arguing that stating reasons is not an essential element of a judgment. The <Argument> also maintains that it is not necessary to guarantee every party the opportunity to have a trial at the Supreme Court.Explanation for <statements> (a): The right to trial being a right of claim means there is a corresponding duty for the court, including the obligation to hold a trial (response to the claim) and, even in cases of dismissing an appeal, the obligation to inform the parties of the grounds for dismissal (the duty to answer faithfully). (a) can serve as a counterargument to the <Argument>. (b): If the court does not hold a trial, then the main content of the right to trial—guaranteed access to judicial procedures—cannot be realized. Furthermore, legitimate judgments require the presentation of reasons behind them. (b) can serve as a counterargument to the <Argument>. (c): The Supreme Court’s conclusions and reasoning serve as de facto standards for the interpretation and normative assessment of similar cases by the public, but if the Court omits its reasoning, the public cannot know the reasoning process, which in turn prevents that reasoning from guiding public judgments. (c) can serve as a counterargument to the <Argument>.Since all of (a), (b), and (c) can serve as counterarguments to the <Argument>, the correct answer is ⑤."
  },
  {
    "id": "2023_03",
    "year": "2023",
    "problem_idx": "3",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to appropriately analyze the debate among Gap, Eul, and Byeong regarding the concept of truth to be pursued in criminal procedure and the role a judge should play to discover such truth.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "Alice: The truth that should be pursued in criminal procedure is the substance of the case, that is, the “objective truth.” Moreover, in order to discover the objective truth, the judge’s active involvement and investigative activities are necessary, no less than those of the parties to the case (defendant, prosecutor). Therefore, if it is necessary for discovering the truth and there is no significant procedural violation, the judge can also directly collect or investigate evidence without being restricted by the claims or requests of the parties. Bob: The “substance of the case” or “objective truth” can only be known by God (or an absolute being). Even the conclusion reached by the judge based on the facts and evidence presented by the parties is, strictly speaking, no more than the judge’s subjective truth. The reason why the judge’s subjective truth is trusted and given normative force under the name of a “judgment” is because it is not merely an individual’s subjective truth, but a conclusion derived through a fair criminal procedure. Therefore, what should be pursued in criminal procedure is the “truth through procedure,” and, to that end, the parties must be guaranteed a fair opportunity to contest the truth in court. At this time, the judge’s role should be to interpret, apply, and observe procedure fairly and strictly in order to ensure the truth. In other words, the judge should perform the role of an adjudicator from the neutral position of a third party, making decisions based on the arguments and proof presented by the parties within the prescribed procedure. Charlie: Objective truth exists, and criminal procedure is a process established to approach such objective truth as closely as possible. Accordingly, I basically agree that criminal procedure should pursue objective truth by clearly revealing the facts of the case. However, the discovery of objective truth should be entrusted entirely to the parties’ submission and proof of evidence, and it is undesirable for the judge to intervene directly and actively in this process of discovering the truth. Therefore, as a rule, the judge should perform the role of a neutral adjudicator as a third party; however, since objective truth obtained through human rights violations cannot acquire legitimacy, the judge also has the role and duty to supervise the criminal procedure so that human rights violations do not occur in its course and to rectify them if they do occur. <question> Which of the following analyses concerning the debate above is correct? Choose as listed in <statements>. <statements> (a) Alice and Charlie would support the proposed revision of the law to remove the limit on the number of times the detention period could be extended for the purpose of investigating a crime. (b) Regarding the principle of law that \"evidence collected by violating the legitimate procedures prescribed by law, even if it is the only and clear proof of guilt, cannot be used as evidence of guilt without exception,\" Bob agrees, but Alice would disagree. (c) As for the legal principle that \"if the defendant does not appear in court, unless special rules apply, the trial cannot proceed,\" Bob and Charlie would agree. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Alice and Charlie would support the proposed revision of the law to remove the limit on the number of times the detention period could be extended for the purpose of investigating a crime.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Regarding the principle of law that \"evidence collected by violating the legitimate procedures prescribed by law, even if it is the only and clear proof of guilt, cannot be used as evidence of guilt without exception,\" Bob agrees, but Alice would disagree.",
      "statement_3": "(c) As for the legal principle that \"if the defendant does not appear in court, unless special rules apply, the trial cannot proceed,\" Bob and Charlie would agree."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Alice believes that the truth to be pursued in criminal procedure is the “objective truth,” and that the judge should actively participate in the discovery of truth, independently of the parties (defendant and prosecutor). Bob, on the other hand, believes that pursuing objective truth is impossible, so the truth to be sought in criminal procedure is “truth through procedure.” He also asserts that the judge’s role should be to ensure compliance with fair procedures and to act as a neutral adjudicator. Charlie agrees with the pursuit of objective truth in criminal procedure, but holds that the responsibility for discovering the truth lies with the parties; the judge must act neutrally to protect the defendant’s human rights.<Explanation of the options> (a) Regarding the proposed revision to remove the limit on the number of times the detention period can be extended for investigating crimes, Alice, who emphasizes the discovery of objective truth, would support it. However, Charlie, who claims that although the pursuit of objective truth is important, objective truth obtained through human rights violations cannot acquire legitimacy, would oppose it. Therefore, (a) is not a correct analysis. (b) Regarding the legal principle that evidence collected by violating legal procedures cannot be used as evidence under any circumstance, Bob, who emphasizes truth through procedure and procedural strictness, would agree. On the other hand, Alice, who emphasizes the discovery of objective truth, would disagree unless the violation of procedure is significant. Therefore, (b) is a correct analysis. (c) Regarding the legal principle that the defendant’s appearance is a necessary condition for the trial to proceed, both Bob and Charlie, who see the parties as the subjects of truth-finding and the judge as a neutral third party, would agree."
  },
