    "id": "2023_06",
    "year": "2023",
    "problem_idx": "6",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to judge whether each argument concerning the interpretation of key terms or the scope of the [school regulations] constitutes a rationale for or against disciplinary action.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "[School Regulations] Article 1 (Disciplinary Actions for Students)1. If a student, while at school, engages in behavior that damages the dignity of a student or tarnishes the reputation of the school, the principal may discipline the student for educational purposes.2. When the principal intends to discipline a student, teachers must be involved in the process, and appropriate procedures such as giving the student or their guardian an opportunity to present their opinion must be ensured.<Situation>While receiving a real-time online class at home, a middle school student, Alice, posted information about a corporal punishment incident under investigation at her school on social media to protect the public’s right to know. This sparked a social controversy. In response, P Middle School intends to discipline Alice in accordance with the [School Regulations]. <question> Which of the following choices correctly state(s) the appropriate judgment regarding the <Situation>? Select all that apply from the <statements>.<statements>(a) The claim that the “school” specified in the [School Regulations] should be regarded solely as a physical space becomes an argument against disciplinary action.(b) The claim that a student's freedom of expression for public interest should be guaranteed without limitation becomes an argument against disciplinary action.(c) The claim that all student activities during class hours should be regarded as activities within the school becomes an argument in favor of disciplinary action. <choices>① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) The claim that the “school” specified in the [School Regulations] should be regarded solely as a physical space becomes an argument against disciplinary action.",
      "statement_2": "(b) The claim that a student's freedom of expression for public interest should be guaranteed without limitation becomes an argument against disciplinary action.",
      "statement_3": "(c) The claim that all student activities during class hours should be regarded as activities within the school becomes an argument in favor of disciplinary action."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Although Alice’s posting about the corporal punishment incident at P Middle School was not done at school, it took place during a real-time online class, which counts as class hours, and it had a public interest purpose of protecting the citizens’ right to know.<Explanation of Choices>(a) In the <Situation>, Alice posted on social media from her home. Therefore, the argument that the “school” in the [School Regulations] should be regarded solely as a physical space is an argument against disciplining Alice. (a) is a valid judgment.(b) In the <Situation>, Alice’s posting on social media about the corporal punishment incident currently under investigation at her school was done out of concern for the public’s right to know. Thus, the argument that a student's freedom of expression for public interest should be guaranteed without limitation is an argument against disciplining Alice. (b) is a valid judgment.(c) In the <Situation>, Alice’s act of posting on social media occurred during class hours. Therefore, the argument that all student activities during class hours should be regarded as school activities is an argument in favor of disciplinary action. (c) is a valid judgment.Since (a), (b), and (c) are all correct judgments, the answer is ⑤."
  },
