    "id": "2023_08",
    "year": "2023",
    "problem_idx": "8",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to find a rule that satisfies all the candies mentioned by Gap, Eul, and Byung.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "\"Mediation\" refers to facilitating convenience between a person and their counterpart by brokering certain matters. Article A of Country X’s \"Criminal Law\" punishes specific acts of mediation.Alice: Even people without the status of public officials can use personal influence such as alumni or regional ties to affect the duties of public officials, so Article A punishes mediation by such people as well.Bob: Because protecting public trust in the execution of public officials' duties is important, Article A punishes those who pursue their own interests under the guise of mediation concerning a public official’s duty, regardless of whether they actually performed mediation.Charlie: There is no need to prohibit bona fide mediation acts, so Article A prohibits mediation concerning a public official’s duty undertaken for one’s own interests. In this case, for preventive effect, Article A also compels those involved in mediation not to retain any property acquired in connection with the mediation. <question> Which of the following most appropriately describes the content of Article A, satisfying all the matters mentioned by Alice, Bob, and Charlie? <statements>(1) Anyone who receives or promises to receive money or benefits in connection with mediation regarding matters pertaining to a public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years or a fine not exceeding 10 million won.(2) Anyone who receives or promises to receive money or benefits and mediates regarding matters pertaining to a public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years, and any property acquired thereby shall be confiscated.(3) Any public official who, by using their position, receives or promises to receive money or benefits in connection with mediation regarding matters pertaining to another public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years or a fine not exceeding 10 million won.(4) Anyone who receives or promises to receive money or benefits in connection with mediation regarding matters pertaining to a public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years or a fine not exceeding 10 million won, and any property acquired thereby shall be confiscated.(5) Anyone who provides or expresses the intention to provide money or benefits in connection with mediation regarding matters pertaining to a public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years or disqualification for not more than seven years, and any property acquired thereby shall be confiscated. <choices> ①(1) ②(2) ③(3) ④(4) ⑤(5)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(1) Anyone who receives or promises to receive money or benefits in connection with mediation regarding matters pertaining to a public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years or a fine not exceeding 10 million won.",
      "statement_2": "(2) Anyone who receives or promises to receive money or benefits and mediates regarding matters pertaining to a public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years, and any property acquired thereby shall be confiscated.",
      "statement_3": "(3) Any public official who, by using their position, receives or promises to receive money or benefits in connection with mediation regarding matters pertaining to another public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years or a fine not exceeding 10 million won.",
      "statement_4": "(4) Anyone who receives or promises to receive money or benefits in connection with mediation regarding matters pertaining to a public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years or a fine not exceeding 10 million won, and any property acquired thereby shall be confiscated.",
      "statement_5": "(5) Anyone who provides or expresses the intention to provide money or benefits in connection with mediation regarding matters pertaining to a public official’s duties shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years or disqualification for not more than seven years, and any property acquired thereby shall be confiscated."
    },
    "original_rationale": "According to Alice, Article A punishes not only the mediation acts of public officials but also those by people who are not public officials.According to Bob, Article A punishes not only actual mediation but also acts where one pursues their own interests under the guise of mediation with respect to a public official’s duty.According to Charlie, Article A prohibits mediation acts undertaken to obtain personal gain and does not allow retention of any property acquired in connection with mediation.Answer Explanation: ④ Since it does not require public official status, it satisfies Alice’s point; it punishes anyone who pursues personal gain by receiving or promising to receive money or benefits without requiring actual mediation, matching Bob’s point; and, since it punishes those who pursue personal gain through mediation and confiscates acquired property, it fulfills Charlie’s point. Thus, ④ most appropriately describes Article A, satisfying all matters mentioned by Alice, Bob, and Charlie.Explanation of incorrect answers:① Only imprisonment or fines are possible, and there is no provision for confiscation of property, so it does not meet Charlie’s requirement. Although, in practice, a fine may function as a de facto confiscation, since the upper limit is set at 10 million won, it may not recover all property acquired through mediation, and if one is sentenced only to imprisonment, they may retain the property acquired through mediation. Thus, ① is not appropriate.② Only punishes actual acts of mediation, so it does not satisfy Bob’s point, and thus is not appropriate.③ Only applies to public officials, so it does not meet Alice’s requirement, and as there is no provision for confiscation of property, it does not meet Charlie’s point. Although, in practice, a fine may serve as a de facto confiscation, since the upper limit is set at 10 million won, it may not recover all property, and property may be retained if sentenced to imprisonment. Thus, ③ is also inappropriate.⑤ This punishes persons who provide or express the intent to provide benefits to those who are asked to mediate, rather than punishing those who act under the pretense of mediation to pursue personal gain, and so it does not meet Bob or Charlie’s criteria. ⑤ is not appropriate as the content of Article A."
