    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to evaluate whether each viewpoint interpreting a case based on regulations is strengthened or weakened by additional information such as separate regulations or legislative intent.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "[Regulations] Article 1 (Definition): The term “pharmacist” refers to matters related to the manufacturing, compounding, storage, import, sale (including delivery), and other pharmaceutical techniques of drugs and quasi-drugs. Article 2 (Sale of Drugs): Unless you are a pharmacy founder, you cannot sell or acquire drugs for the purpose of sale. However, this does not apply if a person who has obtained a manufacturing license sells the drugs they manufactured to a person who has obtained a license for manufacturing or selling drugs. <Case> Company P has obtained licenses for both drug manufacturing and drug sales and thus simultaneously holds the status of both a drug manufacturer and a drug wholesaler. Company P was subject to a suspension of drug sales in its capacity as a manufacturer due to a violation of drug handling methods. With regard to this, there are competing views as to whether Company P shipping drugs from its manufacturer status and receiving them as a wholesaler constitutes a “sale” under these regulations.<Opinions>View 1: Article 2 is intended to strictly manage and prevent the abnormal distribution of drugs. Even if a pharmaceutical company obtains both a manufacturing license and a wholesaler license, if drugs are moved from the manufacturer side to the wholesaler side, it can be regarded as a transaction between entities with separate statuses, thus constituting a “sale.\"View 2: Generally, “sale\" means transferring goods to another person in exchange for a price, presupposing a giver and a recipient. Even if a pharmaceutical company has both manufacturing and wholesaler licenses, when receiving and managing drugs manufactured under one’s manufacturing status within the same company as a wholesaler, it is merely an internal transfer and not a transaction with an independent third party; thus, it does not constitute a “sale.\" <question> Which of the following in <statements> is/are correct as assessments of the <opinions>? <statements> (a) If there are separate regulations stating that a person intending to be a drug wholesaler must obtain permission from the mayor, county governor, or district head, while a person intending to be a manufacturer must obtain permission from the Food and Drug Administration’s head, then View 1 is weakened.(b) If the concept of “delivery” included in “sale” under Article 1 encompasses the transfer of a thing itself irrespective of the transaction counterparty, then View 2 is strengthened.(c) If, according to the purpose of Article 2, the concept of sale is to mean distribution of drugs to the general public, then View 2 is strengthened. <choices>① (b) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (a), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
