      "statement_2": "(b) If the concept of “delivery” included in “sale” under Article 1 encompasses the transfer of a thing itself irrespective of the transaction counterparty, then View 2 is strengthened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If, according to the purpose of Article 2, the concept of sale is to mean distribution of drugs to the general public, then View 2 is strengthened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "[Regulations] under the Pharmaceutical Affairs Act limit those who may sell drugs to pharmacy founders and those licensed as manufacturers or vendors. In the <Case>, Company P is both a licensed manufacturer and vendor, and shipments and receipts of drugs occurred within Company P after it was subject to a sales suspension as a manufacturer. There are competing views as to whether this internal shipment and receipt of drugs by Company P constitute a “sale\" under the [Regulations].View 1 holds that Company P, having two independent statuses as manufacturer and vendor, means that even internal transfers within the same company can be regarded as transactions and thus as “sales.”View 2 argues that, even if Company P holds both licenses, in order for something to be a sale, there must be an independent third party, and that the situation described in the <Case> is merely an internal transfer within the same company and does not constitute a “sale.”<Explanations>(a): It is unclear whether the fact that drug wholesalers and manufacturers have different licensing authorities can directly justify that Company P has separate statuses and thus the transfer constitutes a “sale.” Therefore, it is difficult to say that this directly strengthens or weakens View 1 or View 2. In fact, if one argues that having two separate authorities means the statuses are separated, and thus transactions between such statuses should be recognized as “sales,” then View 1 would actually be strengthened, not weakened. Therefore, (a) is not a correct assessment.(b): If “delivery,” as included in “sale” under Article 1, means the transfer of goods regardless of the presence of a counterpart, then, even if transfer occurs within the same company, this would strengthen View 1, which sees such transfer as a “sale,” and weaken View 2, which requires an independent counterparty. Thus, (b) is not a correct assessment.(c): Receiving drugs into Company P is not the same as distributing them to the general public; Company P is a wholesaler, not a retailer, and did not acquire drugs for the purpose of general public distribution. If the purpose of Article 2 is to regulate sales as distribution to the public, then internal transfers within Company P would not be a regulated “sale,” and this would strengthen View 2. Therefore, (c) is a correct assessment.Of the given statements, only (c) is correct, so the answer is ②."
  },
