    "id": "2023_11",
    "year": "2023",
    "problem_idx": "11",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the differences that arise between aggregated taxation and individual taxation due to varying tax rates based on real estate price ranges, to grasp the main points of each perspective, and to judge individual cases.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "[Real Estate Holding Tax Rate under Country X's Tax Law]Real estate price: up to 500 million won, tax rate: 0.5%Real estate price: more than 500 million won up to 1 billion won, tax rate: 1.5%Real estate price: more than 1 billion won up to 2 billion won, tax rate: 2.5%Real estate price: over 2 billion won, tax rate: 3.5%<Situation>Company Alice and Company Bob belong to Group P, while Company Charlie and Company Diane are run by the Q family. Group P is registered as a group in the corporate registry, whereas Q is not registered as a group. According to the current tax law of Country X, real estate held by each company is taxed individually. (Neither P nor Q itself owns any real estate.)<Viewpoints>Viewpoint 1: Taxation should be carried out based on the unit of the economic community. Companies within a single group registered in the corporate registry can be viewed as an economic community. For example, under the current law, if only Alice in Group P owns real estate worth 1 billion won, the total tax amount is different from the case where Alice and Bob each own real estate worth 500 million won. Since this does not reflect their status as an economic community, it is unjust. Taxation should be based on the total value of all real estate held by the companies in Group P, regardless of the individual real estate values owned by each company. In other words, an aggregated taxation should be imposed on the real estate holdings of the companies within Group P.Viewpoint 2: While it is desirable for taxation to be based on the unit of the economic community, if aggregate taxation of real estate holdings is imposed only on groups registered in the corporate registry, certain problems arise. For example, since Company Charlie and Company Diane, run by the Q family, are not registered as a group in the corporate registry, their real estate holdings will not be aggregated for tax purposes. When the combined real estate value of companies belonging to P and Q is identical, both have the characteristics of an economic community, yet P will end up paying more taxes than Q, leading to an unfair outcome. Therefore, it would be better to tax each company individually according to the current tax law, regardless of group registration status. <question> Which of the analyzes below is/are correct according to the information above? Choose all that apply from the <statements>.<statements>(a) If the total real estate value of the companies in P does not exceed 500 million won, the total tax amount will not differ whether taxation is according to Viewpoint 1 or Viewpoint 2.(b) If the total real estate value of the companies in P exceeds 2 billion won, there is no situation in which the total tax amount is the same when taxation is according to Viewpoint 1 and when it is according to Viewpoint 2.(c) If the tax law is revised to treat substantive economic entities like Q as groups registered in the corporate registry, Viewpoint 2 would not object to aggregate real estate holding tax on P. <choices>① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b),(c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If the total real estate value of the companies in P does not exceed 500 million won, the total tax amount will not differ whether taxation is according to Viewpoint 1 or Viewpoint",
      "statement_2": "2. ",
      "statement_3": "(b) If the total real estate value of the companies in P exceeds 2 billion won, there is no situation in which the total tax amount is the same when taxation is according to Viewpoint 1 and when it is according to Viewpoint",
      "statement_4": "2. ",
      "statement_5": "(c) If the tax law is revised to treat substantive economic entities like Q as groups registered in the corporate registry, Viewpoint 2 would not object to aggregate real estate holding tax on P."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The [Real Estate Holding Tax Rate under Country X's Tax Law] takes a progressive structure, where the higher the real estate value, the higher the tax rate imposed. According to this, if a single economic entity owns multiple pieces of real estate, aggregating them for taxation leads to a higher total tax than taxing them individually. In this system, if several companies belonging to one group are each taxed individually on their real estate, the total tax will be less than if all their real estate values were combined for taxation. Based on this issue, Viewpoint 1 argues that tax on real estate holdings should be aggregated for companies within a group, reflecting their status as an economic community. On the other hand, while Viewpoint 2 fundamentally agrees with aggregate taxation for economic communities, it points out that, since companies run by the Q family (which in reality is also an economic community) are forced to be taxed individually due to lack of group registration, companies in P end up paying more tax than those in Q. Therefore, Viewpoint 2 advocates for both P and Q to be taxed individually in fairness, according to the current law.<Explanations>(a): If the total real estate value does not exceed 500 million won, whether aggregate taxation according to Viewpoint 1 or individual taxation according to Viewpoint 2 is applied, the 0.5% tax rate is applied, and thus the total tax amount is the same. Thus, (a) is a correct analysis.(b): If each company belonging to P owns real estate worth more than 2 billion won, whether aggregate taxation according to Viewpoint 1 or individual taxation according to Viewpoint 2 is applied, the 3.5% tax rate is applied in either case, so the total tax amount is the same. Therefore, (b) is not a correct analysis.(c): Viewpoint 2 fundamentally agrees on aggregate taxation for a single economic community. However, since it would be unfair to apply aggregate taxation only to P and not to Q (which, in reality, is also an economic community), Viewpoint 2 argues for individual taxation for both P and Q. If a legal reform allows substantive economic communities like Q to be treated as registered groups (thus addressing the fairness issue), Viewpoint 2 would not object to aggregate real estate holding tax on P. Therefore, (c) is a correct analysis.Since only (a) and (c) are correct analyses, the answer is ③."
  },
