    "problem_idx": "18",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand and analyze the debate between Gap and Eul regarding whether implicit truths exist in fictional works in addition to explicit truths.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "Alice: In the novel \"A Study in Scarlet,\" the statement \"Holmes is a detective\" appears explicitly, so the proposition <Holmes is a detective> is explicitly true in this novel. However, nowhere in \"A Study in Scarlet\" is there any explicit statement about the number of Holmes’s nostrils. Nevertheless, it is common knowledge that Holmes is a human within the work, and humans generally have two nostrils, so a proposition such as <Holmes has two nostrils> would also be true in \"A Study in Scarlet.\" In fact, although not expressed explicitly, there are many propositions that are implicitly true in \"A Study in Scarlet,\" such as <The earth is round> and <All humans die>. Bob: Accepting that there are propositions that are implicitly true in fiction leads to unreasonable consequences. First, let’s note that sequels to fictional works can exist. Sequels have the power to determine the truth of things not made explicit in the original work. For example, in the novel \"The Hobbit,\" it is not specified what kind of ring Bilbo possesses, but in its sequels, \"The Lord of the Rings\" series, it is made explicit that the ring is the One Ring. In this case, it is reasonable to regard the proposition that Bilbo’s ring is the One Ring as true even in \"The Hobbit.\" Now, suppose the following. Conan Doyle writes a sequel to \"A Study in Scarlet\" titled \"A Study in Red,\" and in that novel there is an explicit statement: \"In fact, Holmes, who had had three nostrils since birth, was able to smell very well.\" Then it would also be reasonable to see the proposition <Holmes has three nostrils> as explicitly true not only in \"A Study in Red\" but also in \"A Study in Scarlet.\" However, if <Holmes has two nostrils> is implicitly true in \"A Study in Scarlet,\" then Holmes must have both two and three nostrils at the same time in \"A Study in Scarlet.\" This is clearly an unreasonable consequence. Therefore, one can conclude that there is no such thing as implicit truth in fiction in addition to explicit truth. <question> Which of the following analyses of the above debate is/are correct? Choose from the <statements> below as appropriate.<statements>(a) Alice presupposes that any proposition must be either true or false in a particular fiction.(b) According to Bob, the proposition <Holmes has two nostrils> could be true in \"A Study in Scarlet\" and later become false.(c) According to Bob, even if the statement \"The earth is round\" does not appear explicitly in \"A Study in Scarlet,\" there may be situations where the proposition <The earth is round> is true in \"A Study in Scarlet.\"<choices>① (a)② (c)③ (a), (b)④ (b), (c)⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Alice presupposes that any proposition must be either true or false in a particular fiction.",
      "statement_2": "(b) According to Bob, the proposition <Holmes has two nostrils> could be true in \"A Study in Scarlet\" and later become false.",
      "statement_3": "(c) According to Bob, even if the statement \"The earth is round\" does not appear explicitly in \"A Study in Scarlet,\" there may be situations where the proposition <The earth is round> is true in \"A Study in Scarlet.\""
    },
    "original_rationale": "Alice argues that, in addition to propositions that become true through explicit statements in fiction, there are also propositions that are implicitly true. For example, propositions such as <Holmes has two nostrils>, <The earth is round>, and <All humans die> are implicitly true in \"A Study in Scarlet.\"On the other hand, Bob argues that sequels have the power to determine the truth of things not made explicit in the original work, and through an argument that unreasonable results appear when implicit truth is accepted—such as when a sequel contains an explicit statement that contradicts what was previously considered an implicit truth—he concludes that there is no such thing as implicit truth in fiction.<Analysis of statements>(a) Alice's claim is only that there is implicit truth in addition to explicit truth, and in the original text, she limits this to propositions that align with common sense. Therefore, Alice’s position is compatible with the view that some propositions in a fictional work are neither explicitly nor implicitly true or false. For example, Alice’s claim does not entail that a proposition like <Holmes has an odd number of hairs> must be either true or false in \"A Study in Scarlet.\" It is compatible with Alice’s view that such a proposition is neither true nor false, whether explicitly or implicitly. Therefore, Alice does not presuppose that any proposition must be either true or false in a particular fiction. Thus, (a) is not a correct analysis.(b) Bob’s position is not that the proposition <Holmes has two nostrils>, which was true in \"A Study in Scarlet,\" could later become false if Conan Doyle were to write a sequel, \"A Study in Red.\" Nowhere in Bob’s argument does he claim that the truth value of a proposition can change. Rather, Bob's claim is simply that <Holmes has two nostrils> was never implicitly true in \"A Study in Scarlet\" to begin with. Whether a sequel can change the explicit truth of an original work is not discussed in the text. Thus, (b) is not a correct analysis.(c) Bob’s position is that there is no implicit truth, so <The earth is round> cannot be implicitly true in \"A Study in Scarlet.\" However, taking into account Bob's statement, “In that case, it would be appropriate to consider the proposition <Holmes has three nostrils> as explicitly true not only in 'A Study in Red' but also in 'A Study in Scarlet',” it follows that if in the sequel \"A Study in Red\" there is an explicit statement \"The earth is round,\" then <The earth is round> would become explicitly true in \"A Study in Scarlet\" as well according to Bob. Thus, (c) is a correct analysis.Only (c) is a correct analysis, so the answer is ②."
  },
