    "original_rationale": "The logical structure of the argument presented can be analyzed as follows.[1] “ⓜSelf-consciousness is not useful at all.” follows from the following three statements:ⓐ If self-consciousness, which has been treated as an important problem in philosophy, is useful, then it is either useful in itself or gives rise to something else useful.ⓑ Upon closer examination, self-consciousness is not at all useful in itself.ⓛ Self-consciousness does not give rise to anything else useful.[2] ⓒFollows ⓑ and ends with “…because,” showing that ⓒ serves as the basis for ⓑ—that is, ⓑ follows from ⓒ.[3] “ⓛSelf-consciousness does not give rise to anything else useful.” follows from the following three statements:ⓓ If self-consciousness gives rise to something else useful, the useful thing that self-consciousness brings about exists either inside the mind or outside the mind.ⓔ Self-consciousness cannot bring about anything useful outside the mind.ⓗ There is nothing useful within the mind that self-consciousness produces.[4] “ⓔSelf-consciousness cannot bring about anything useful outside the mind.” follows from the following two statements:ⓕ If self-consciousness could bring about something outside the mind, then there would have to be something outside the mind that self-consciousness could causally influence.ⓖ Everything that self-consciousness can causally influence exists within the mind.(Additional explanation: From ⓕ and ⓖ, we infer that “self-consciousness cannot bring about anything outside the mind”; from this statement, ⓔ is inferred.)[5] The argument whose conclusion is “ⓗThere is nothing useful within the mind that self-consciousness produces” is as follows:ⓘ What is useful within the mind ultimately does not differ from a good state of mind.ⓙ For such states to arise, self-consciousness is not necessary.ⓚ If something can arise without the need for self-consciousness, then it is not produced by self-consciousness.(Additional explanation: From ⓙ and ⓚ, we infer “these states (that is, good states of mind) are not produced by self-consciousness.” Combining this statement with ⓘ, we can infer “what is useful within the mind is not brought about by self-consciousness.” From this statement, ⓗ is inferred.)Answer Explanation: ③ The diagram that satisfies all the logical analyses described in [1] to [5] above is ③."
