    "id": "2023_26",
    "year": "2023",
    "problem_idx": "26",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to properly understand the logic of the methods of selecting target polling stations to acquire samples for exit polls and to distinguish their differences.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "An election exit poll is a method of increasing the accuracy of predicting election results by surveying actual voters instead of eligible voters. In exit polls, it is important how to select the polling stations (within an electoral district) that will be surveyed. Once the polling stations are selected, the surveys are conducted at the polling places that belong to those polling stations. There are three exit poll methods: A, B, and C.A: Compare the overall vote tally of the district and the individual results from each polling station in the previous election, then select the polling place of the station where the difference is smallest as the target for the survey. B: Group together polling stations that showed similar party-specific results in the previous election into several strata, and select a certain number of polling stations randomly from each stratum according to the proportion of voters, then survey the polling places corresponding to those stations. C: Rather than pre-selecting polling stations and conducting surveys within the voting hours only at those places, travel to all polling stations in the district, conducting surveys at each by staying for a certain period of time before moving to the next. In this way, surveyors travel between polling stations, surveying for a set amount of time at each. The sample size for each polling station is determined in proportion to its number of eligible voters. <question> Which of the following analyses about the text above is/are correct? Select the correct options from <statements> as they are given. <statements> (a) If there has been significant change in the population’s social characteristics in a polling station since the last election, method A is difficult to apply. (b) Method B assumes that polling stations within the same district are generally homogeneous in terms of voters’ political orientation. (c) In method C, data from the previous election about vote counts per polling station is essential. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If there has been significant change in the population’s social characteristics in a polling station since the last election, method A is difficult to apply.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Method B assumes that polling stations within the same district are generally homogeneous in terms of voters’ political orientation.",
      "statement_3": "(c) In method C, data from the previous election about vote counts per polling station is essential."
    },
    "original_rationale": "As with other surveys, ensuring the representativeness of the sample is key in election exit polls. Method A is an approach seeking representativeness by selecting the polling station that, based on results from the previous election, had the most similar results to the district as a whole. Method B first stratifies all polling stations by grouping those with similar results in the previous election, then selects a certain number of polling stations from each stratum. This method seeks representativeness by ensuring that polling stations with diverse characteristics are evenly included in the sample. Method C is a method where all polling stations are visited in sequence, and a small number of voters are surveyed at each, aiming to ensure that voters from every polling station are included in the sample.(a): Method A assumes that voting behavior at a particular polling station will be similar to that in the previous election. If there has been a significant change in the population or social characteristics of a polling station since the last election, voting behavior may differ considerably from the past, making method A difficult to apply. Therefore, (a) is a correct analysis.(b): Method B assumes that polling stations within the same district are heterogeneous, which is why it first groups homogeneous polling stations into strata, then selects a certain number of polling stations from each stratum. While polling stations within the same stratum are homogeneous, polling stations in different strata are heterogeneous. By this approach, polling stations with various characteristics are evenly surveyed, allowing for better prediction of the district's overall voting results. If polling stations’ political inclinations were homogeneous, there would be no need to divide them into strata and select polling stations from each. Therefore, (b) is an incorrect analysis.(c): Both A and B require data from the previous election's polling station results in order to pre-select representative stations; however, C surveys all polling stations anyway, so previous vote count data is not necessary. Therefore, (c) is an incorrect analysis.Thus, only (a) is a correct analysis, so the answer is ①."
  },
