    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the argument that the birth rate will decrease due to COVID-19, and to correctly judge whether hypothetical data strengthens or weakens that argument.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "There is a claim that the birth rate will decrease due to COVID-19, which began spreading in January 2020. The grounds for this claim are as follows. First, strong social distancing measures have made it relatively difficult for people to freely meet and date. Because of significant restrictions on using public facilities and traveling abroad, many people are postponing or giving up on marriage. Second, especially among low-income groups and young people—who generally have higher birth rates—unemployment rates have risen and income has decreased, leading to increased economic hardship. Since the economic burden of childbirth and childrearing is high, a decrease in income will result in a decrease in births. Third, as remote work and telecommuting have become widespread, the boundary between work and home has become blurred, causing many workers to complain of stress. Furthermore, with childcare facilities such as schools, kindergartens, and daycare centers being closed or partially operated, raising children has become even more difficult. Because of these childcare and childrearing challenges, not only families with young children but also those without children are likely to postpone or give up on having children. <question> Which of the following evaluations of the above argument are correct? Select all correct answers from the <statements> as they are. <statements> (a) If the total number of infants and young children decreased from July 2019 to July 2022, but there was no difference in the population under one year old, the argument is strengthened. (b) If the per capita Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in 2019 was 31,929,000 KRW and in 2020 it was 31,637,000 KRW, showing little difference, the argument is weakened. (c) If in August 2019, the percentage of women—both economically active and inactive—who reported being currently pregnant was 10% for both groups, and this percentage showed almost no change in the same survey conducted in August 2021, the argument is weakened. <choices> ① (b) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (a), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If the total number of infants and young children decreased from July 2019 to July 2022, but there was no difference in the population under one year old, the argument is strengthened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If the per capita Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in 2019 was 31,929,000 KRW and in 2020 it was 31,637,000 KRW, showing little difference, the argument is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If in August 2019, the percentage of women—both economically active and inactive—who reported being currently pregnant was 10% for both groups, and this percentage showed almost no change in the same survey conducted in August 2021, the argument is weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Three main points are offered as grounds for the claim that the birth rate will decline due to COVID-19:First, strong social distancing measures have made meetings and romantic relationships relatively difficult, resulting in many people postponing or giving up on marriage.Second, in low-income groups and young people—demographics with relatively high birth rates—income has decreased, which is anticipated to lead to a decline in births.Third, families both with and without children may postpone or give up on plans for childbirth due to problems with childcare and childrearing.<Explanation of each statement>(a) If there is no difference in the population under one year old between July 2019 and July 2022, this suggests there was little change in the birth rate during that period. (Even if the total number of infants and young children decreased, this might be due to other reasons, such as a higher mortality rate among children over one year old.) Therefore, the fact that there was no difference in the population under one year old does not strengthen the argument that the birth rate fell due to COVID-19. Evaluation (a) is incorrect.(b) If the income of low-income groups and young people did not decrease, that would undermine the argument. However, the fact that per capita GDP remained almost the same does not necessarily weaken the argument, since even if incomes among low-income groups and young people decreased, the per capita GDP might be unchanged if the income of the middle or upper income groups increased. Thus, evaluation (b) is incorrect.(c) The argument claims that worsening conditions for childcare and childrearing due to COVID-19 will lead families to delay or forgo childbirth. If the percentage of both economically active and inactive women who reported being currently pregnant did not change from the 2019 to the 2021 survey, this undermines the grounds for the argument, thus weakening the argument. Evaluation (c) is correct.Only (c) is a correct evaluation, so the correct answer is ②."
  },
