    "problem_idx": "37",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the argument that the meaning of words can be extended when a specific mathematical model is applied, and to determine whether new information strengthens or weakens that argument.",
    "domain": null,
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "It is doubtful whether the intuition that the word ‘eat up’ (잡아먹다) should only be used for animals that have mouths and digestive organs is a good basis for determining the meaning of this word. There is scientific evidence that this word can also be used for entities that have neither a mouth nor digestive organs. The following mathematical model M explains this evidence.(1) dP/dt = b(aV)P - mP(2) dV/dt = rV - (aV)PA mathematical model can only be meaningful when properly applied to reality. M was created to predict the relationship in population size changes between sharks and cod living in a certain region, and in fact, this prediction was successful. Equation (1) represents the change in the shark population over time, and equation (2) represents the change in the cod population over time. In (1), the term b(aV)P is interpreted as “an increase in the shark population proportional to the number of cod eaten by sharks.” Recently, botanists have successfully used M to predict the relationship in population size changes between the parasitic plant mistletoe and oak trees. If so, the interpretation of the relationship between sharks and cod should be applied consistently to the relationship between mistletoe and oak trees as well. When applying M to the relationship between mistletoe and oak, b(aV)P means “an increase in the mistletoe population proportional to the number of oak trees eaten by mistletoe.” The fact that the application of M is extended from the shark case to the mistletoe case is scientific evidence that the meaning of the word ‘eat up’ (잡아먹다) can be extended. <question> Which of the following judgments about the above argument is correct? Choose from among the <statements>.<statements>(a) The fact that the word ‘eat up’ is rarely used in everyday language to describe the behavior of organisms that absorb food into their bodies without a mouth weakens this argument.(b) The fact that the expression ‘eat up’ is commonly used in everyday language for carnivorous plants, which have structures similar to the mouths and digestive organs of animals, weakens this argument.(c) If model M is well applied to the relationship between disease-causing bacteria and humans, and the statement “small bacteria eat up humans” comes to be generally used among biologists, then this argument is strengthened. <choices>① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) The fact that the word ‘eat up’ is rarely used in everyday language to describe the behavior of organisms that absorb food into their bodies without a mouth weakens this argument.",
      "statement_2": "(b) The fact that the expression ‘eat up’ is commonly used in everyday language for carnivorous plants, which have structures similar to the mouths and digestive organs of animals, weakens this argument.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If model M is well applied to the relationship between disease-causing bacteria and humans, and the statement “small bacteria eat up humans” comes to be generally used among biologists, then this argument is strengthened."
