    "original_rationale": "This argument addresses the claim that the meaning of the word ‘eat up’ (잡아먹다) can be expanded in a counter-intuitive way by appealing to scientific evidence. The mathematical model M was created to predict the population size change relationship between sharks and cod in a certain region, and in fact, this prediction was successful.Therefore, M can be seen as a model about the phenomenon of sharks eating cod. However, it has been shown that the mathematical model M not only predicts the population size change relationship between sharks and cod, but also successfully predicts the population size change relationship between parasitic mistletoe and oak trees.If so, the interpretation regarding the relationship between sharks and cod should be consistently applied to the relationship between mistletoe and oak. The fact that the application of M is extended from the shark case to the mistletoe case provides scientific grounds for extending the meaning of the word ‘eat up’ even to mistletoe, which has neither a mouth nor digestive organs.<Explanations> for Choices(a) According to the passage, intuition is not considered an appropriate semantic basis for determining word meanings. If one presents a reason why intuition is a better semantic basis than scientific evidence in the passage, then this argument could be weakened. However, “the fact that the word ‘eat up’ is rarely used in everyday language to explain the behavior of organisms that absorb food into their bodies without a mouth” does not provide a reason why intuition is a better semantic basis than scientific evidence."
