    "id": "2024_01",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "1",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand two perspectives on the nature of torts and the objectives of tort law, among other things, and to determine whether court judgments strengthen or weaken these perspectives.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "<Opinion> A: A tort is an act that destroys the originally just or equitable state of affairs. Therefore, the law of torts is a system designed to restore the original state that was destroyed by a tort and to remedy the victim. The aim of restoration in tort law is a demand based on justice or ethics, not because it contributes to the promotion of social utility or is functionally useful. Furthermore, unless the victim is completely restored to the state prior to the tort from the victim's perspective, rather than from the viewpoint of the perpetrator or a third party (including the social community), true remedy for the victim has failed. B: The essence of a tort lies in the fact that it is an unlawful act committed intentionally or negligently by a person. Therefore, the law of torts should aim not only at restoring the loss caused by a tort but also at preventing tortious conduct. Tort law should provide behavioral guidelines for members of society and give incentives to promote desirable behavior. Preventive messages should be addressed not only to the perpetrator, but to all members of the community, including the perpetrator. When deciding what kind of message to deliver, it is necessary to seriously consider what constitutes the greatest good for the community. <question> Which of the following in <statements> is correct as an assessment of the <Opinion>? <statements> (a) In a case where damages involved the destruction of property and the cost of repair exceeded the replacement value of the item, if a court in country X ruled that the perpetrator must compensate the victim for the full repair cost, this would weaken A. (b) In a case where an employee transferred company C’s trade secrets to a competitor for profit, but the company suffered no actual damage, if a court in country X ruled that the illicit gains should nonetheless be compensated to the company as damages, this would strengthen B. (c) In a case where someone repeatedly used demeaning expressions to defame another, but the victim forgave the offender, if a court in country X ruled compensation should be paid not to the victim but to a third party on the grounds that tolerating such demeaning expressions would undermine free debate in society, this would weaken A and strengthen B. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) In a case where damages involved the destruction of property and the cost of repair exceeded the replacement value of the item, if a court in country X ruled that the perpetrator must compensate the victim for the full repair cost, this would weaken A.",
      "statement_2": "(b) In a case where an employee transferred company C’s trade secrets to a competitor for profit, but the company suffered no actual damage, if a court in country X ruled that the illicit gains should nonetheless be compensated to the company as damages, this would strengthen B.",
      "statement_3": "(c) In a case where someone repeatedly used demeaning expressions to defame another, but the victim forgave the offender, if a court in country X ruled compensation should be paid not to the victim but to a third party on the grounds that tolerating such demeaning expressions would undermine free debate in society, this would weaken A and strengthen B."
    },
    "original_rationale": "There is a conflict between two opinions regarding whether a judge in a tort case should focus solely on adjusting the interests of the parties, or resolve what appears to be a private dispute in a way that is best for the interests of the community as a whole. Opinion A emphasizes restoration of loss, while Opinion B focuses on prevention of tortious acts. The key points of A and B are as follows:A: Tort law should prioritize restoring the interests harmed by the tort to their original state, without considering any further social utility or usefulness. Compensation should be such that, from the perspective of the victim, a complete restoration to the pre-tort condition is possible.B: Tort law should provide behavioral guidelines to members of society so that torts can be prevented. In this context, the preventive message should be sent not only to the perpetrator but to all members of the community as pertaining to the greatest good.<Explanations> (a): In cases where property is damaged by a tort, there can be situations in which the repair cost for the damaged part exceeds the replacement value of the object. In such cases, the only way to truly restore the item to its original state is through repair. Therefore, if a ruling requires the perpetrator to pay for the repair rather than just the replacement value, this strengthens A, which emphasizes restoration from the victim’s perspective. Thus, (a) is not a correct assessment.(b): In cases where an employee transfers company trade secrets to a competitor and gains benefit, but the company's loss is negligible or virtually nonexistent, a ruling that the perpetrator must pay over all illicit profits to the company as damages reflects a preventive, rather than restorative, approach. Such a decision signals to potential wrongdoers and the community that such conduct is wrong and is intended to prevent similar actions. Thus, this strengthens B, making (b) a correct assessment.(c): If there is a ruling that compensation should be paid not to the victim but to a third party, with the reason being that tolerating repeated demeaning expressions undermines free debate in society, this weakens A, which emphasizes the importance of restoration to the victim, ignoring social utility or functionality. On the other hand, it strengthens B, as the court is sending a message about the greater good and regulating harmful conduct in society. Thus, (c) is a correct assessment.Of the above, only (b) and (c) are correct, so the answer is ④."
  },
