    "id": "2024_05",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "5",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the views regarding when the autonomy of contracting parties can be restricted, and to accurately judge the conclusions based on each of those views.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "A contract is established by the autonomous agreement of the parties. In light of the nature and function of contracts, contract law must not only recognize the autonomy of the parties but also be a normative system that maximally implements and strengthens such autonomy. In what cases can the autonomy of the parties be restricted? There are three views regarding this question. A: Autonomy should be protected because the value lies in autonomy itself rather than the consequences it brings. Since the intention of the parties is inherently worthy of respect, even if the intention displayed by one party differs from what the party originally intended and the other party relies on the displayed intention, the originally intended will should be respected over what was expressed. State intervention is justified only when the exercise of autonomy so fundamentally infringes upon autonomy itself. B: Autonomy should be protected by focusing on the utility it brings to the parties, rather than the value of autonomy itself. A restriction on autonomy is justified if the absolute value of the cost (-) to the parties caused by restricting autonomy is less than the absolute value of the utility (+) gained by the parties. The mere fact that restriction of autonomy increases the utility of a third party (including the State or society) does not justify restricting autonomy. C: Autonomy should be protected by focusing on the utility it brings to society as a whole, rather than its value in itself. This view focuses on the utility to society as a whole rather than to the parties when making evaluations. However, if the absolute value of the cost (-) to the parties caused by restricting autonomy is greater than the absolute value of the utility (+) to the parties, restriction of autonomy is only permissible if the difference is compensated by the State, etc. To the extent of such compensation, the utility of the parties is considered to have increased. <question> Which of the following is NOT a reasonable inference from the above? <choices> ① According to A, even if one party unintentionally expresses intention ⓑ instead of the intended will ⓐ and the other party recognizes ⓑ as the intention, the originally intended will ⓐ should be respected. ② According to B, when restricting the parties’ autonomy is justified, the sum of the cost (-) and utility (+) to the parties is always positive (+). ③ According to C, when restricting the parties’ autonomy, there are cases where the sum of the cost (-) and utility (+) to the parties is negative (-). ④ According to both A and C, even if the sum of the cost (-) and utility (+) to the parties caused by restricting the parties’ autonomy is positive (+), there are cases when the parties’ autonomy cannot be restricted. ⑤ If the Basic Regulatory Act of Country X provides that “the parties’ autonomy may only be restricted if the total utility produced for society as a whole exceeds the costs generated by restricting autonomy,” then this is based on C rather than B.",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "① According to A, even if one party unintentionally expresses intention ⓑ instead of the intended will ⓐ and the other party recognizes ⓑ as the intention, the originally intended will ⓐ should be respected.",
      "statement_2": "② According to B, when restricting the parties’ autonomy is justified, the sum of the cost (-) and utility (+) to the parties is always positive (+).",
      "statement_3": "③ According to C, when restricting the parties’ autonomy, there are cases where the sum of the cost (-) and utility (+) to the parties is negative (-).",
      "statement_4": "④ According to both A and C, even if the sum of the cost (-) and utility (+) to the parties caused by restricting the parties’ autonomy is positive (+), there are cases when the parties’ autonomy cannot be restricted.",
      "statement_5": "⑤ If the Basic Regulatory Act of Country X provides that “the parties’ autonomy may only be restricted if the total utility produced for society as a whole exceeds the costs generated by restricting autonomy,” then this is based on C rather than B."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Because the parties’ autonomy in contracts must be maximally implemented and strengthened, in principle, the State etc. cannot restrict it. There are three views regarding exceptional cases in which autonomy can be restricted. A argues that restriction of autonomy is justified only when the exercise of autonomy so fundamentally infringes upon autonomy itself. B argues that restriction of autonomy is justified only when the absolute value of the cost (-) to the parties caused by restricting autonomy is less than the absolute value of the utility (+) brought to the parties. C argues that restriction of autonomy is justified only when the absolute value of the cost (-) to society as a whole caused by restricting autonomy is less than the absolute value of the utility (+) brought to society as a whole. According to (③), under C, when the absolute value of the cost (-) to the parties caused by restricting autonomy is greater than the absolute value of the utility (+) to the parties, restriction of autonomy is only allowed if the State, etc. compensates the difference. In this case, the utility of the parties is considered to increase by the amount compensated, so the absolute value of the cost (-) to the parties and the absolute value of the utility (+) to the parties become equal; thus, the sum of the cost (-) and the utility (+) is zero. Therefore, according to C, there is no case where the sum of the cost (-) and utility (+) to the parties is negative (−) when restricting autonomy: it is always positive (+) or zero. Statement (③) is not a correct inference. Explanation of Incorrect Answers ① According to A, even if one party’s intention is expressed differently and the other party relies on the expressed will, the originally intended will should be respected. Accordingly, if one party’s intended will is ⓐ, but by mistake it is expressed as ⓑ and the other party recognizes it as ⓑ, the party’s will is regarded as ⓐ. Thus, ① is a correct inference. ② According to B, the justification for restricting autonomy is that the absolute value of the cost (−) to the parties caused by restriction is smaller than the absolute value of the utility (+) to the parties. In this case, the sum of the cost (−) and utility (+) to the parties is positive (+). Therefore, restricting the parties’ autonomy in a justified manner always results in a positive (+) sum of cost (−) and utility (+). Thus, ② is correct. ④ A does not focus on the utility to the parties caused by restriction but argues that autonomy itself should be protected due to its inherent value. Thus, under A, even if the sum of the cost (−) and utility (+) to the parties becomes positive (+) through restriction, restriction of autonomy is not allowed unless the exercise of autonomy fundamentally infringes upon autonomy itself. According to C, even if the sum of the cost (−) and utility (+) to the parties is positive (+), if the sum of the cost (−) and utility (+) to society as a whole is negative (−), restriction is not allowed. Thus, ④ is correct. ⑤ B focuses on the utility to the parties rather than to society as a whole, whereas C focuses on the utility to society as a whole rather than to the parties. Since the Basic Regulatory Act of Country X focuses on the utility to society as a whole, it is justified based on C rather than B. Thus, ⑤ is correct."
  },
  {
    "id": "2024_06",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "6",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to comprehend the reasoning behind viewpoints and to judge whether new information reinforces or undermines them.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "An incident occurred in Country X where a drone was used to film the interior of a high-rise apartment living room without permission, raising the issue of whether \"ⓐ the act of photographing the interior of another person's residence from outside without authorization\" can be punished under [the Regulation]. [Regulation] Article 1 (Crime of Secret Surveillance): Anyone who records or listens to others’ undisclosed residence or building interiors by means such as recording or listening shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than five years. Article 2 (Crime of Illegal Search): Anyone who searches another person’s residence or building without authority shall be punished by imprisonment for not more than three years. <Opinions> A: ⓐ falls under the crime of secret surveillance. 'Surveillance' means ascertaining information about the interior of a residence, thereby infringing on the sense of security regarding privacy enjoyed by the resident; and 'by means such as recording or listening' should not necessarily be restricted to only auditory or acoustic methods but can include visual methods such as video recording or viewing. B: ⓐ falls under the crime of illegal search. 'Search' refers to examining a certain place in order to discover a person or object. Although the existing interpretation of illegal search crimes punished those who, having lawfully entered a residence or building, conducted a search without authority, the text of the illegal search crime itself is not limited only to when someone has entered the residence or building. Therefore, illegal search crimes should also cover cases where a person unlawfully enters or, even from outside, searches the interior without authority; thus, a person who conducts such a search from outside the residence or building can also be punished. <question> Considering the above <Opinions>, which of the following from <statements> are correct? <statements> (a). If the Country X court has ruled that merely peeking into another’s residence through the window from the outside with the naked eye does not constitute 'surveillance' under the crime of secret surveillance, then A is weakened. (b). If the legislative intent behind prescribing different penalties in Article 1 and Article 2 is that unlawfully entering another’s residence to obtain information is more wrongful than obtaining information by lawful entry, then B is strengthened. (c). If the Country X court has ruled that an act where the police, to find the wanted person, film Bob’s residence from outside using a drone without a warrant does not infringe on the sense of privacy but does constitute an unlawful “search,” then A is weakened and B is strengthened. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) . If the Country X court has ruled that merely peeking into another’s residence through the window from the outside with the naked eye does not constitute 'surveillance' under the crime of secret surveillance, then A is weakened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) . If the legislative intent behind prescribing different penalties in Article 1 and Article 2 is that unlawfully entering another’s residence to obtain information is more wrongful than obtaining information by lawful entry, then B is strengthened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) . If the Country X court has ruled that an act where the police, to find the wanted person, film Bob’s residence from outside using a drone without a warrant does not infringe on the sense of privacy but does constitute an unlawful “search,” then A is weakened and B is strengthened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Regarding whether it is possible to punish the act of filming the interior of a high-rise apartment from outside using a drone without authorization, Opinion A applies Article 1 to argue that one can be punished for the crime of secret surveillance, while Opinion B applies Article 2 to argue that one can be punished for the crime of illegal search. The reasoning of A and B is as follows. A: First, A relies on the definition of 'surveillance' as ‘ascertaining information about the interior of a residence, thereby infringing on the sense of security regarding privacy enjoyed by the resident.’ A regards the act of filming the interior of a residence using a drone as infringing on a resident’s sense of security. Second, A is based on the fact that Article 1 punishes the act of ascertaining information about the interior of a residence \"by means such as recording or listening.\" The term \"such as\" allows for expansive interpretation, thereby including visual methods like video recording or viewing. In other words, A claims that visual methods, such as filming by drone, can also fall under \"means such as recording or listening.\"B: According to the conventional interpretation in Country X, the crime of illegal search was limited to cases where a person who had lawfully entered a residence or building conducted a search without authority. However, Article 2 does not specifically state that the crime is limited to cases where someone has entered the residence or building. Based on this, B argues that those who unlawfully enter a residence or building and conduct an unauthorized search, as well as those who search the interior without entering, can be punished for illegal search. Therefore, filming with a drone constitutes an unauthorized search of the interior from outside the residence or building, and can be punished accordingly.Explanation for <statements>:(a). Looking into a residence through a window from outside with the naked eye is considered \"viewing,\" which is a visual method that A claims is included within the meaning of \"surveillance.\" However, if the Country X court rules that viewing does not constitute \"surveillance\" under the crime of secret surveillance, there is a high likelihood that recording, like viewing, does not constitute \"surveillance\" either, as both are visual methods. This decision thus weakens A's argument that \"surveillance\" includes visual as well as auditory methods. Therefore, (a) is a correct evaluation.(b). Article 1 (Crime of Secret Surveillance) and Article 2 (Crime of Illegal Search) have penalties of not more than five years and not more than three years, respectively. If the legislative intent of prescribing different penalties is that unlawfully entering another’s residence to obtain information is more wrongful than lawfully obtaining information by entry, this supposes that secret surveillance means unlawfully entering to obtain information, while illegal search refers to obtaining information after lawful entry. That is, both articles presuppose \"entering the residence,\" differing only on the legality of entry. Therefore, based on legislative intent about sentencing, the traditional interpretation that illegal search is limited to cases of lawful entry is strengthened. However, B argues against this conventional interpretation, insisting that the crime of illegal search can be applied even to those who search from outside. Thus, B’s argument is not strengthened. (b) is therefore an incorrect evaluation.(c). If the Country X court found that the police’s filming from outside by drone without a warrant did not infringe on the sense of privacy but nonetheless constituted an unlawful “search,” then, since the act does not infringe on the sense of privacy, A (who defines “surveillance” as infringing the sense of privacy) is weakened. On the other hand, the finding that this action constitutes an unlawful \"search\" strengthens B's argument that such conduct falls under the crime of illegal search. Therefore, (c) is a correct evaluation.Since only (a) and (c) are correct evaluations, the answer is ③."
  },
  {
    "id": "2024_13",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "13",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to correctly infer from two different positions concerning the theory required to construct moral principles for evaluating the moral responsibility of killing in war.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "According to our intuitions, murder cannot be morally justified, and the murderer is morally responsible. Let us consider the following two situations. (Situation 1) Alice, the head of a mafia organization planning a bank robbery, instructs Bob, a member of the organization, to kill the bank's security officer. Bob, following Alice's instructions, shoots and kills the security officer. (Situation 2) During a fierce battle with the enemy, commander Charlie orders his subordinate Dave to shoot and kill an enemy sniper. Dave, following Charlie's orders, kills the enemy sniper. Concerning the principles for assessing moral responsibility for Bob's and Dave's actions in the two situations above, there are the following two viewpoints. <Viewpoints> A: There is no difference between (Situation 1) and (Situation 2) in that an act of killing has occurred. Therefore, there is no reason that the principle for evaluating moral responsibility for murder should be different between (Situation 1) and (Situation 2). Let us define principle P for evaluating moral responsibility as follows: \"Any killing, command to kill, or execution of a killing that is not self-defense is morally impermissible, and there is moral responsibility for such an act.\" When evaluating the moral responsibility for the killings committed by Bob in (Situation 1) and Dave in (Situation 2), principle P should be equally applicable. B: Violence in war and violence in everyday life are clearly different; therefore, a special moral principle, distinct from the principle used to assess moral responsibility for murder in daily life, is required in war. Thus, in order to assess the moral responsibility for the actions of Bob in (Situation 1) and Dave in (Situation 2), at least two principles are necessary. To properly assess moral responsibility for killing in war, one should be able to apply a different moral principle than the one used in daily life. <question> Which of the following, among the analysis of the <Viewpoints>, are correct as they are stated in the <statements>? <statements> (a) If, according to P, Bob is morally responsible but Dave is not, viewpoint A is weakened. (b) According to A, in order to argue that Dave bears moral responsibility for the killing in (Situation 2) under P, it must be proven that Dave’s action does not count as self-defense. (c) According to B, the conclusion that both Bob and Dave are morally responsible cannot be reached. <choices> ① (b) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (a), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If, according to P, Bob is morally responsible but Dave is not, viewpoint A is weakened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) According to A, in order to argue that Dave bears moral responsibility for the killing in (Situation 2) under P, it must be proven that Dave’s action does not count as self-defense.",
      "statement_3": "(c) According to B, the conclusion that both Bob and Dave are morally responsible cannot be reached."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Viewpoint A represents reductionism: if there is a principle that can properly assess moral responsibility for killing in war, it must also be capable of properly assessing moral responsibility for killing in everyday life. Viewpoint B, in contrast, is non-reductionist: the moral principles used to justify killing in war are separate from those applied in daily life. This position arises from the view that the specific characteristics of violence or killing in war cannot be reduced to those of everyday violence.<Explanation of the statements> (a) If P leads to the conclusion that Bob is morally responsible but Dave is not, then this means that principle P has been applied equally to both Bob in (Situation 1) and Dave in (Situation 2), so this does not weaken A, which claims that the same principle P should be applied equally to both when evaluating moral responsibility for killing. Thus, (a) is not the correct analysis. (b) A asserts that principle P should be applied equally in both cases when assessing moral responsibility for killing. According to P, if Dave’s act of killing the enemy sniper by Charlie’s order in (Situation 2) is not self-defense, then Dave is morally responsible. Thus, in order to claim that Dave’s act of killing is morally blameworthy under P, it must be shown that Dave's action does not constitute self-defense. Therefore, (b) is the correct analysis. (c) B argues that violence in war and violence in everyday life are clearly different, and therefore, a special moral principle, distinct from that used in daily life, is needed for war. This means that different moral principles must be applied to Bob in (Situation 1) and Dave in (Situation 2). If different moral principles are applied, whether Bob and Dave bear moral responsibility depends on which moral principle is applied to each situation. Therefore, according to Viewpoint B, it is possible that the conclusion that both Bob and Dave are morally responsible can be reached, depending on which principles are applied. Therefore, (c) is not the correct analysis. Only (b) is the correct analysis, so the answer is ①."
  },
  {
    "id": "2024_14",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "14",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to appropriately analyze and evaluate arguments supporting the claim that exceptions to the attribution of responsibility exist, within the problem of responsibility attribution related to the post-truth phenomenon.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "In the process of public opinion formation, it is increasingly common for personal beliefs or emotions to wield greater influence than the truth. A typical example is when posts on social networking platforms—written based on personal feelings yet differing from the facts—still exert significant social influence. These phenomena manifest in various ways, one of which is when people claim something as true without verification, even though it is possible to check the authenticity of the information. We may tend to think simply that, in such cases, the speaker is to be held responsible. However, according to A, \"ⓐEven in such cases, responsibility does not always lie with the speaker.” For example, suppose that under normal observation conditions, Alice looks down from the rooftop of a tall building and sees what appears to be a crowd of people gathered in the plaza next to the building. Alice then claims, \"There are many people gathered in the plaza.\" However, in reality, what was in the plaza were not people, but human-shaped mannequins installed for an event. Since Alice's observation felt clear to her, she did not take the simple step of going down to the ground floor to check the facts. Had Alice herself felt suspicious of her evidence or had someone else requested verification, she would have checked, but she was so confident in her experience that she did not feel the need. According to A, even if Alice's claim is not true in this case, it is difficult to assign responsibility to Alice. A accepts the premise that responsibility is assigned to the agent only in cases where the act itself is subject to blame. According to A, in the above example, Alice’s act of claiming \"there are many people gathered in the plaza\" is, in itself, not blameworthy. Alice's assertion is merely a cognitive error. Therefore, responsibility is not assigned to Alice. A states that in cases of believing or asserting something untrue as the truth, what is crucial is not a permissible level of negligence or cognitive error, as in the above example, but rather an active attitude of intentionally avoiding or refusing to acquire information. Responsibility is, of course, assigned to an agent with such an attitude. It is clear that someone who intentionally refuses even a very simple verification process and spreads fake news warrants responsibility. <question> Which is the correct evaluation of ⓐ? <choices> ① If an act that is not, in itself, subject to blame is not cognitive error, then ⓐ is weakened. ② If it is not always the case that responsibility is assigned to someone who believes in and spreads fake news, then ⓐ is weakened. ③ If there are cases where responsibility is not assigned to the agent of an act that is not, in itself, subject to blame, then ⓐ is weakened. ④ If all false assertions made under normal observation conditions always stem from an active avoidance attitude, then ⓐ is strengthened. ⑤ If in situations where it is impossible to check the truth, acts that are merely cognitive errors cannot occur, then ⓐ is strengthened.",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "① If an act that is not, in itself, subject to blame is not cognitive error, then ⓐ is weakened.",
      "statement_2": "② If it is not always the case that responsibility is assigned to someone who believes in and spreads fake news, then ⓐ is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "③ If there are cases where responsibility is not assigned to the agent of an act that is not, in itself, subject to blame, then ⓐ is weakened.",
      "statement_4": "④ If all false assertions made under normal observation conditions always stem from an active avoidance attitude, then ⓐ is strengthened.",
      "statement_5": "⑤ If in situations where it is impossible to check the truth, acts that are merely cognitive errors cannot occur, then ⓐ is strengthened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The argument that A presents to support ⓐ is as follows: [Premise 1] If responsibility is assigned to the agent, then the act itself is subject to blame. (\"Responsibility is assigned to the agent only in cases where the act itself is subject to blame…\") [Premise 2] Alice's case is merely a cognitive error. [Premise 3] An act that is merely a cognitive error is not, in itself, blameworthy. [Conclusion 1] Therefore, Alice’s case is not one where responsibility is assigned to the agent. [Premise 4] Alice's case is one where she asserts something as true without checking the facts, even though it was possible to verify the authenticity of the information. [Conclusion 2] Therefore, not all cases where someone asserts something as true without verification (even though verification is possible) warrant assigning responsibility to the speaker. Correct answer explanation ① If you convert the first part of ① into its contrapositive, it means that all acts that are cognitive errors are, in themselves, subject to blame. This would make [Premise 3] false, thereby weakening A’s argument. Therefore, ① is a correct evaluation. Incorrect answers explanation ② The claim in ⓐ is that not all cases where someone asserts a falsehood without checking the facts (even though they could check) are cases where responsibility is assigned to the speaker. Believing in and spreading fake news is an example of such a \"case\" as confirmed at the end of the passage. If it is not always the case that responsibility is assigned to someone who believes in and spreads fake news, this actually aligns with ⓐ and therefore strengthens it, not weakens it. For this reason, ② is not a correct evaluation. ③ The example of Alice cited by A is precisely a case where \"responsibility is not assigned to the agent of an act that is not, in itself, subject to blame.\" Thus, ③ is consistent with the example A uses to support their claim and therefore strengthens ⓐ, making it incorrect as an evaluation. ④ If, even under normal observation conditions—in other words, even when it is possible to confirm the truth—all false assertions always stem not from cognitive error but from an active avoidance attitude, then the scope of assigning responsibility to the speaker expands to include all such cases under normal observation. In other words, ⓐ’s claim that there are cases where the speaker is not to blame is weakened. Therefore, ④ is not a correct evaluation. ⑤ A’s argument is limited to situations where it is possible to determine the truth. A contrasts cases of “permissible levels of negligence or cognitive error” (where fact-checking is possible but not done) with cases of “actively avoiding or refusing to acquire information,” assigning responsibility only in the latter. Thus, we cannot know what stance A would take if it were impossible to verify the truth. Even if such situations were included in A’s argument, if acts that are merely cognitive errors cannot occur in those situations, the scope of responsibility exemption that A proposes is thereby reduced. Thus, ⑤ is not a correct evaluation."
  },
