    "problem_idx": "17",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to accurately understand the definitions concerning various dimensions of lines and to analyze their differences.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "Goodness (善), that is, goodness, has two dimensions. \"ⓐPrimary goodness\" refers to the essential perfection that a being possesses. This is an essential goodness in the sense that if any being lacks it, it can no longer be that being. In this sense, primary goodness signifies, in an active sense, the negation of privation. If a human lacks humanity, they are no longer human. As long as a human exists as a human, regardless of the differences in physical abilities or virtues among individuals, the assertion that someone is \"more human\" than others does not stand. Secondary goodness refers to the relationship between a subject and the accidental properties it possesses, as the property of \"upright walking\" pertains to being human. This kind of goodness is not what constitutes \"being,\" but rather accompanies \"being.\" Secondary goodness is subdivided into two. \"ⓑThe first type of secondary goodness\" refers to the suitability in which a property, in and of itself, contributes to the perfection of the being it belongs to. Health is not a primary goodness to a human, but a secondary one, because even a sick person is still human. And if health is good for a human, then health itself is a good property for humans. \"ⓒThe second type of secondary goodness\" refers to the goodness that is found in a being when a certain property belongs to it. In this sense of goodness, it is not the particular property itself that is good, but the overall goodness possessed by the being. For example, when we say a particular food is delicious, it is because its salinity, acidity, texture, and so on are well-harmonized; it is difficult to claim, by isolating just one element, that it alone is delicious. <question> Which of the following analyses of the above passage is/are correct? <statements> (a) If evil is the privation of goodness, then evil is ⓐ. (b) In the statement, \"If an object is beautiful, its beauty is the harmonious totality of size, shape, color, etc. that the object possesses,\" beauty is ⓒ. (c) If something is always good for someone, then it is ⓐ, and if not, it is ⓑ or ⓒ. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If evil is the privation of goodness, then evil is ⓐ.",
      "statement_2": "(b) In the statement, \"If an object is beautiful, its beauty is the harmonious totality of size, shape, color, etc. that the object possesses,\" beauty is ⓒ.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If something is always good for someone, then it is ⓐ, and if not, it is ⓑ or ⓒ."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The passage provides an explanation of Duns Scotus’s analysis on the concept of ‘goodness,’ stating that there are two dimensions to goodness. That is, goodness exists both on the metaphysical level, as in the statement “all humans are good,” and on the natural level, as in everyday situations where we call an individual better than another. In the passage, these are distinguished as primary goodness and secondary goodness. Primary goodness is the essential kind of goodness, whose absence would mean the being ceases to be what it is; secondary goodness is a kind of goodness based on the relation of a property to the subject it belongs to. Furthermore, secondary goodness is divided into two senses: one refers to properties in themselves, and the other refers to the goodness found in the subject that possesses those properties. If a property, in itself, contributes to the perfection of the subject to which it belongs, it is the first type of secondary goodness; if the property, when possessed by a being, results in overall goodness found in that being, it is the second type of secondary goodness.<view> Explanation:(a) If evil is defined as the privation of goodness, evil can never be primary goodness, for primary goodness actively implies the negation of privation. Thus, (a) is not an appropriate analysis.(b) The second type of secondary goodness is the goodness found in a being when a certain property belongs to it, and in this sense, it is goodness applicable to the overall subject, not to an individual property. The example in the passage is that when a food is delicious, it is not because of the saltiness, acidity, or texture in themselves, but because these elements harmonize to make the dish tasty overall. Similarly, in (b), “beauty” as the harmonious totality of size, shape, color, etc., constitutes the second type of secondary goodness. Thus, (b) is an appropriate analysis.(c) Primary goodness is essential goodness in the sense that, without it, a being cannot be what it is—a necessary condition. However, even if something is always good for a person, it does not necessarily mean it is required for a person to be what they are. For example, while it can be said that health is always good for humans, a sick person is still human, so health is not primary goodness. On the other hand, if something is not always good, it could be a kind of goodness or not be goodness at all. Thus, (c) is not an appropriate analysis.Only (b) is the appropriate analysis, so the answer is ②."
  },
