    "id": "2024_18",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "18",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to appropriately analyze the debate between Eul, who presents a causal theory regarding the intentionality of thought content, and Gab, who presents a counterargument to it.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "Alice1: The symbol 'dog' written on paper is about dogs. Likewise, our thought-of-dog in our heads is also about dogs. But just as it's tricky to explain why the arbitrary symbol 'dog' is about dogs, it's also tricky to explain how the thought-of-dog is about dogs. Bob1: That’s simple to explain. If object X causally triggers a certain thought, and if that thought is causally triggered only when X exists, then the thought is about X. Think about something like the elevator indicator. The 7th-floor indicator turns on when, and only when, the elevator reaches the 7th floor. In the same way that the 7th-floor indicator is about the 7th floor, the thought-of-dog is about dogs.Alice2: Your view isn’t satisfactory. For example, suppose Charlie sees a dog. The causal chain from the dog to Charlie’s thought-of-dog is very long. Light reflects off the dog’s fur and enters Charlie’s retina. The retina is activated in a specific pattern, and that information is delivered through the optic nerve to the brain. Finally, the thought-of-dog is formed deep in Charlie’s brain. Let’s call “pattern of activation on Charlie’s retina” ‘d-pattern.' Then we could say that it is the d-pattern—not the dog itself—that causally triggers, and only triggers, Charlie’s thought-of-dog. Bob2: But if you trace back the causal chain leading to that d-pattern, at the very end there is always the dog itself. So Charlie’s thought-of-dog is still about the dog; nothing changes. Alice3: Then let’s say on a foggy evening Charlie mistakes a sheep for a dog and thinks, “There’s a dog beyond that fog.” Now Charlie’s thought-of-dog has been triggered by a sheep, whereas in a normal situation, it would have been triggered by an actual dog, not a sheep. The thought-of-dog can be caused either by the sheep or by the dog. So you’d have to say the thought-of-dog is triggered by a dog-or-sheep. Therefore, if your view is correct, Charlie’s thought-of-dog would be about not the dog, but the object dog-or-sheep. <question> Which of the following analyses of the debate are correct? Choose all that apply from the <statements> below.<statements>(a) Even if the starting point of the causal chain leading up to ⓐ is not the whole dog but just a part of the dog, Alice2’s conclusion would still follow.(b) In Bob2’s argument, he presupposes the principle that, for objects a, b, and c, if a causally triggers b and b causally triggers c, then a causally triggers c.(c) The arguments presented in Alice2 and Alice3 show that, if one accepts Bob1’s view, Charlie’s thought-of-dog could be about something other than a dog. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Even if the starting point of the causal chain leading up to ⓐ is not the whole dog but just a part of the dog, Alice2’s conclusion would still follow.",
      "statement_2": "(b) In Bob2’s argument, he presupposes the principle that, for objects a, b, and c, if a causally triggers b and b causally triggers c, then a causally triggers c.",
      "statement_3": "(c) The arguments presented in Alice2 and Alice3 show that, if one accepts Bob1’s view, Charlie’s thought-of-dog could be about something other than a dog."
    },
    "original_rationale": "A summary of the passage is as follows: • Bob1’s theory: If object X causally triggers thought C and if C is triggered only when X exists, then thought C is about X.• Alice2’s rebuttal: If we accept Bob's theory, then Charlie’s thought-of-dog is not about a dog, but rather about the d-pattern.• Bob2’s counter-rebuttal: If we trace the causal chain from the d-pattern all the way back, we always end up at the dog itself. That is, “the dog causally triggers Charlie’s thought-of-dog and only when the dog is present is the thought-of-dog triggered.” This maintains that, under his theory, Charlie’s thought-of-dog is still about the dog.• Alice3’s further rebuttal: If we accept Bob's theory, Charlie’s thought-of-dog would be about not the dog itself, but rather the disjunctive object dog-or-sheep.<Explanation of Statements> (a): Even if the starting point of the causal chain leading to the particular activation on Charlie’s retina is not the whole dog but a part of the dog, the contention in Alice2—that “it is the d-pattern, and only the d-pattern, that causally triggers Charlie’s thought-of-dog”—still holds. Therefore, if we accept Bob's theory, Alice2’s conclusion that Charlie’s thought-of-dog is about the d-pattern rather than the dog itself still follows. Thus, (a) is a correct analysis.(b): Bob2 concludes that “if we trace the causal chain that leads to the d-pattern back, we ultimately always find the dog,” and from there, he infers that “Charlie’s thought-of-dog is still about the dog itself.” For this conclusion to be justified, it must be the case that “the dog causally triggers Charlie’s thought-of-dog.” For this to be true, Bob2 must presuppose the principle that for objects a, b, and c, if a causally triggers b and b causally triggers c, then a causally triggers c.Therefore, (b) is a correct analysis.(c): As explained above, both Alice2 and Alice3 show that, if Bob1’s theory is accepted, then Charlie’s thought-of-dog could be about the d-pattern (in Alice2) or about the object dog-or-sheep (in Alice3), i.e., something other than the dog itself. Thus, (c) is a correct analysis.Since all of (a), (b), and (c) are correct analyses, the answer is ⑤."
  },
  {
    "id": "2024_19",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "19",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to appropriately analyze and evaluate Gap's claim regarding the compatibility of his theory, 'Naive Truth Pluralism,' with Yi's principle, and Eul's refutation of that claim.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "Alice: Every proposition concerns only one subject of discourse, such as mathematics or ethics, and there is no proposition that is about nothing. Furthermore, a proposition is true or false only relative to the subject of discourse it concerns. Therefore, it is inappropriate to simply say, \"Proposition p is true\" or \"Proposition q is false.\" Instead, we should say things like \"Proposition p is mathematically true\" or \"Proposition q is ethically false.\" A proposition is not true in relation to any subject of discourse other than its own. That is, an ethical proposition p is not mathematically true. However, according to the Law of Excluded Middle, every proposition is either true or false. In other words, if a proposition is not true, then it is false, and if it is not false, then it is true. At a glance, my view seems to conflict with the Law of Excluded Middle, because a proposition can be mathematically true without being ethically true. However, it is a contradiction to say that a proposition is both mathematically true and not mathematically true, but it is not a contradiction to say that it is mathematically true and not ethically true.Bob: That’s not so. A contradiction arises if you accept both your view and the Law of Excluded Middle. Let’s call the proposition “Murder is wrong” r. Since r is an ethical proposition, it is not mathematically true. According to your view, all truth and falsity are relative to a subject of discourse, so the statement “r is not mathematically true” is also true relative to some specific subject of discourse. Since it is clear that the truth/falsity of a value judgement about murder is not a mathematical subject, let’s assume that the statement “r is not mathematically true” belongs to the subject of ethics. By our assumption, “r is not mathematically true” is ethically true. However, in your view, since every proposition belongs to only one subject of discourse, an ethically true proposition is not mathematically true. Therefore, the statement “r is not mathematically true” is not mathematically true. But, according to the Law of Excluded Middle, for any proposition p, if “p is not true” is not true, then p is true. Therefore, r is mathematically true. This contradicts our assumption that r is not mathematically true. <question> Which of the following analyses regarding the above debate are correct? Select all that apply from <statements>.<statements>(a) Alice does not deny that for a proposition p about a subject of discourse S, if p is not s-true, then p is s-false.(b) If, in “it is not true that ‘p is not true’,” the first ‘true’ and the second ‘true’ cannot be about the same subject of discourse, Bob’s argument is weakened.(c) Even if we assume that the proposition “r is not mathematically true” belongs to the subject of discourse of art rather than ethics, Bob’s conclusion is derived in the same way. <choices>① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Alice does not deny that for a proposition p about a subject of discourse S, if p is not s-true, then p is s-false.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If, in “it is not true that ‘p is not true’,” the first ‘true’ and the second ‘true’ cannot be about the same subject of discourse, Bob’s argument is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Even if we assume that the proposition “r is not mathematically true” belongs to the subject of discourse of art rather than ethics, Bob’s conclusion is derived in the same way."
    },
    "original_rationale": "To summarize the given passage:[Alice’s Argument](1) Every proposition belongs to only one subject of discourse.(2) A proposition belonging to subject s is either s-true or s-false.(3) A proposition belonging to subject s is not r-true for any other subject r.(4) Claims (1)–(3) do not conflict with the Law of Excluded Middle.[Bob’s Reasoning](1) Let’s call “Murder is wrong” r.(2) r is ethically true.(3) Therefore, r is not mathematically true. (Derived from (2) and Alice’s claims.)(4) The statement “r is not mathematically true” is ethically true. (Derived from (3) under the assumption that it belongs to the subject of ethics.)(5) The statement “r is not mathematically true” is not mathematically true. (Derived from (4) and Alice’s claims.)(6) Therefore, r is mathematically true. (Derived from (5) and the Law of Excluded Middle’s principle of double negation.)<Analysis of the statements>(a) The relevant principle here is the Law of Excluded Middle: for the restricted case of a single subject of discourse s, any proposition that is not s-true is s-false, and any proposition that is not s-false is s-true. Alice asserts that her claims do not contradict the Law of Excluded Middle. Thus, she does not deny this interpretation of the law. (a) is a correct analysis.(b) In “it is not true that ‘p is not true’,” if the first ‘true’ and the second ‘true’ cannot both be about the same subject of discourse, we cannot say, for example, “it is not mathematically true that ‘r is not mathematically true’.” This undermines step (5) in [Bob’s Reasoning], thereby weakening Bob’s argument. (b) is a correct analysis.(c) Even if we suppose that the statement “r is not mathematically true” belongs to the subject of art instead of ethics, step (4) in [Bob’s Reasoning] only changes so that “r is not mathematically true” becomes artistically true. Since artistic truth is not mathematical truth, step (5) still follows, and consequently Bob’s reasoning proceeds as before. (c) is a correct analysis.Since (a), (b), and (c) are all correct analyses, the answer is ⑤."
  },
