    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "Alice: Humans interact with the world based on perception. However, sometimes humans perceive objects incorrectly. The ability to perceive in a way that accurately corresponds to the external world was important in human evolution, as it can make a difference in actual behavior. That's why distinguishing between accurate representation and misrepresentation is important.Bob: With perception alone, we cannot distinguish between accurate representation and misrepresentation. Visual perception is determined only by the information delivered to the retina. At this time, there may be multiple external objects corresponding to the same perception, but we cannot know which one is the real one. For example, a brownish-yellow surface is perceived as a neutral yellow when its surroundings are red, and a greenish-yellow surface is also perceived as neutral yellow when its surroundings are green. In these cases, we perceive only the neutral yellow and have no way of knowing what the actual color of the surface is.Alice: So, what you're saying is that it's difficult to tell the difference between an unripe and a ripe banana, right? If I can't know what I'm seeing, I can't pick and eat a ripe banana. This would be a disadvantage for humans in the course of evolution.Bob: Of course, it would be nice to be able to identify and eat only ripe ones. However, we don't need to know precisely at every moment whether it is unripe or fully ripe. There are more yellow bananas within our range of action. Supermarket shelves are full of yellow bananas. So if you eat based on the perception of yellow, you'll end up eating ripe bananas. <question> Which of the following analyses of the above debate are appropriate? Choose the correct ones from <statements> as they are.<statements>(a) Even if the perceiver can know which of the multiple objects producing the same perception most likely corresponds accurately to that perception, Alice's claim is not weakened.(b) If two circles of different sizes can be perceived as the same size depending on the size of the circles surrounding each, then Bob's claim is weakened.(c) Regarding the statement \"Some perceptions correspond accurately to external objects,\" Alice does not agree but Bob does. <choices>① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) Even if the perceiver can know which of the multiple objects producing the same perception most likely corresponds accurately to that perception, Alice's claim is not weakened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If two circles of different sizes can be perceived as the same size depending on the size of the circles surrounding each, then Bob's claim is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Regarding the statement \"Some perceptions correspond accurately to external objects,\" Alice does not agree but Bob does."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Alice claims that representations correspond to external objects, and that it is important for the perceiver to know which object their perception corresponds to. If one cannot know which object the perception is corresponding to, it would ultimately be a disadvantage for humans in the process of evolution. Bob refutes Alice's claim by arguing that the perceiver can only know their internal perception and cannot know the external object corresponding to a particular perception. The same perception can correspond to multiple external objects, and the perceiver, with only information delivered to the retina, cannot know what the actual object corresponding to the perception is.<Analysis>(a) If the perceiver can know which of the multiple objects producing the same perception most likely corresponds accurately to that perception, then the perceiver is more likely to be able to distinguish between accurate representation and misrepresentation. This is because the perceiver will judge that the object which most likely corresponds accurately to that perception is what the perception represents. Therefore, Alice's claim that it is important for the perceiver to know which object the perception accurately corresponds to is not weakened. (a) is an appropriate analysis.(b) If two circles of different sizes can be perceived as the same size depending on the sizes of the circles surrounding them, this is an example similar to Bob’s case: it illustrates that two different objects can correspond to the same perception. Thus, it does not weaken Bob’s claim. (b) is not an appropriate analysis.(c) Since Alice argues that the ability to perceive in a way that accurately corresponds to the external world is important, she would agree with the statement that “Some perceptions correspond accurately to external objects.” Therefore, the assertion in (c), that Alice does not agree with this statement, is not an appropriate analysis. (Meanwhile, Bob might also agree with this statement, since he does not deny the possibility of a correct correspondence between perception and object altogether.)Since only (a) is an appropriate analysis, the answer is ①."
  },
