    "id": "2024_21",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "21",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to read opinions on whether there are generalized criteria applicable to art criticism, if so, to what extent generalization is possible, and how these critical standards can be applied to specific works, and to analyze their implications.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "Art criticism is a linguistic activity that evaluates works of art. A critic pays attention to the structural features or the representational and expressive properties of a work, and on this basis, presents reasons that provide the grounds for aesthetic evaluation of the work. Based on the following <Critique>, Alice and Bob present their views.<Critique>- Evaluation: Michelangelo’s <Pietà> is excellent.- Reason: Michelangelo’s <Pietà> looks lifelike.Alice: Someone who thinks the evaluation in <Critique> is valid might claim that the standard \"If an artwork W looks lifelike, then W is excellent\" was applied in <Critique>. However, this standard cannot be applied to Warhol's <Brillo Box>. Even though <Brillo Box> has the same appearance as an actual soap box, that does not necessarily make it excellent. Therefore, it cannot be established that \"If property F is attributed to artwork W, then W is excellent\" serves as a general criterion for criticism.Bob: There is no generalized standard of criticism that can be applied without exception to all works of art. However, works of art can be categorized as belonging to at least one specific category. In that case, we can find a generalized standard of criticism that guarantees excellence, in the sense that a work realizes the purpose of its category—for example: \"For an artwork W belonging to category C, if property F contributes to the purpose of C, then F makes W excellent.\" The evaluation in <Critique> can be seen as applying the standard: \"For artwork W belonging to the category of Renaissance sculpture, as long as the property of 'lifelikeness' contributes to the purpose of Renaissance sculpture, 'lifelikeness' makes W excellent.\"<question> Which of the following analyses about the above text is correct? Select all correct answers as indicated in <statements>.<statements>(a) According to Alice, a standard for criticism cannot be generalized in any way, so evaluations must always be made only from the perspective of individual works.(b) When evaluating a painting, the judgment \"Any work of art with unity is excellent, so this work is excellent\" applies the 'generalized standard for criticism' advocated by Bob.(c) The claim, \"Even if 'an implausible plot,' which is a typical attribute that undermines the excellence of a play, contributes to the purpose of the Theater of the Absurd, there still cannot be a generalized standard for criticism of the Theater of the Absurd,\" does not contradict Alice’s position but contradicts Bob’s position. <choices>① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) According to Alice, a standard for criticism cannot be generalized in any way, so evaluations must always be made only from the perspective of individual works.",
      "statement_2": "(b) When evaluating a painting, the judgment \"Any work of art with unity is excellent, so this work is excellent\" applies the 'generalized standard for criticism' advocated by Bob.",
      "statement_3": "(c) The claim, \"Even if 'an implausible plot,' which is a typical attribute that undermines the excellence of a play, contributes to the purpose of the Theater of the Absurd, there still cannot be a generalized standard for criticism of the Theater of the Absurd,\" does not contradict Alice’s position but contradicts Bob’s position."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Art criticism consists of a critic’s evaluation and the reasons provided in support of that evaluation. Therefore, discussion concerning the existence of a generalized critical standard capable of supporting these reasons is essential. To solve this problem, one must accurately grasp the possible perspectives arising in the debate between universalists, who assert the existence of a generalized standard, and particularists, who deny such a standard, and appropriately analyze the implications.<Explanation> (a): Alice’s argument is that \"If a property F is attributed to artwork W, then W is excellent\"—that is, a generalized standard of criticism—cannot be established. Therefore, according to Alice, such a generalized standard cannot be established at this broad level. However, this does not necessarily entail that a less general (i.e., more specific or limited) standard can never be established. The claim that even on such a limited level, no critical standard can be generalized is, in fact, stronger than what Alice actually argued. Thus, the assertion that evaluation must always be made only from the perspective of individual works does not strictly follow from Alice’s argument. Therefore, (a) is not a correct analysis.(b): When evaluating a painting, the assertion \"Any work of art with unity is excellent, so this work is excellent\" presupposes that \"Any unified work of art is excellent\" applies without exception to all works of art. However, Bob asserts there is no generalized standard for criticism that can be applied without exception to all artworks. Thus, (b) is not a correct analysis.(c): Alice’s position is that there is no generalized standard for criticism—that is, no property guarantees the excellence of all works of art. Therefore, it does not contradict Alice’s position to claim that there cannot be a generalized standard of criticism even for the Theater of the Absurd. Bob’s position, however, is that there is a generalized standard, at least at the level of category—for example, properties that contribute to realizing the purpose of a particular category. But (c) claims that even if \"an implausible plot\" contributes to the purpose of the Theater of the Absurd, there still can be no generalized standard for criticism for this category—so (c) does contradict Bob’s position. Thus, (c) is a correct analysis.Since only (c) is a correct analysis, the answer is ②."
  },
