    "id": "2024_22",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "22",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand a specific view concerning whether emotions include appropriate evaluative beliefs, and to determine what could be a counterargument to this view.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "Alice: Emotions always require an appropriate evaluative belief. Fear of an object is based on the belief that the object is dangerous to me, and sadness over some event is grounded in the belief that the event is a significant loss for me. If I hold beliefs that contradict these evaluative beliefs, then I am either not experiencing an emotion or am both affirming and denying a claim at the same time. Bob: Not only is it fully possible, but it is also in fact common, to experience emotions without holding the appropriate evaluative beliefs. For instance, someone might firmly believe that a spider in front of them is not dangerous to them, yet still feel fear toward the spider. Furthermore, it is evident that animals and infants also experience emotions like fear. However, animals or infants without linguistic ability do not possess evaluative concepts such as “danger” at all, and thus cannot hold beliefs such as “something is dangerous to me.” <question> Which of the following from <statements> can serve as a counterargument to Bob’s line of reasoning? <statements> (a). Not only is it fully possible, but it is also common, to hold contradictory beliefs. There is little difference, either in possibility or in frequency, between holding contradictory beliefs and holding emotions that contradict evaluative beliefs. (b). The claim that emotions always require appropriate evaluative beliefs is not the same as claiming that having such evaluative beliefs is sufficient for feeling the corresponding emotions. Sensations like pleasure or pain are essential aspects of emotion, and animals or infants can easily experience these sensations. (c). Having a concept does not necessarily mean having the ability to express it linguistically. If an animal has a tendency to flee rapidly when a predator approaches, then regardless of whether it knows the word “danger,” it can be regarded as having a belief about the danger posed by the predator. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) . Not only is it fully possible, but it is also common, to hold contradictory beliefs. There is little difference, either in possibility or in frequency, between holding contradictory beliefs and holding emotions that contradict evaluative beliefs.",
      "statement_2": "(b) . The claim that emotions always require appropriate evaluative beliefs is not the same as claiming that having such evaluative beliefs is sufficient for feeling the corresponding emotions. Sensations like pleasure or pain are essential aspects of emotion, and animals or infants can easily experience these sensations.",
      "statement_3": "(c) . Having a concept does not necessarily mean having the ability to express it linguistically. If an animal has a tendency to flee rapidly when a predator approaches, then regardless of whether it knows the word “danger,” it can be regarded as having a belief about the danger posed by the predator."
    },
    "original_rationale": "According to Alice, an appropriate evaluative belief is a necessary condition for having emotions. That is, if I have an emotion, I always have the proper evaluative belief. Additionally, if I hold evaluative beliefs and also hold beliefs that contradict them, I am either not experiencing the emotion or I am simultaneously affirming and denying a particular claim. Bob points out two problems with the argument that appropriate evaluative beliefs are necessary for emotion. First, it is not only possible but common to experience emotion without holding the appropriate evaluative belief. Secondly, animals and infants do not possess evaluative concepts such as “danger” and thus cannot have the belief that something is dangerous to them, but they clearly can experience emotions like fear. <Explanation of the options> (a). If it is possible and common to hold contradictory beliefs, Bob is not making an argument against this possibility or its frequency. Furthermore, (a) asserts that it is possible and common to have emotions that contradict evaluative beliefs, but Bob argues that it is possible and common to experience an emotion, such as fear, without holding the evaluative belief (for example, that the object is dangerous to oneself). Therefore, even if it is common to have emotions that contradict evaluative beliefs, this is compatible with Bob’s claim. Thus, (a) cannot serve as a counterargument to Bob’s claim.(b). The two problems Bob points out are criticisms of Alice’s assertion that emotions always require the proper evaluative belief. However, (b) states that the claim that emotions always require the proper evaluative belief is not equivalent to claiming that having such an evaluative belief is a sufficient condition for emotion, and that sensations like pleasure and pain are essential components of emotion, which animals and infants can easily feel. Thus, (b) serves rather as a supplementary explanation of Alice’s position, not as a counterargument to Bob’s reasoning.(c). In Bob’s second argument, a crucial premise is that animals and infants do not possess evaluative concepts such as “danger.” This premise is inferred from the argument that they lack linguistic abilities. As described in (c), if linguistic ability is not a necessary condition for possessing a concept—if one can possess a concept without being able to express it linguistically—then (c) refutes the premise of Bob’s argument and can therefore serve as a counterargument to Bob’s reasoning."
  },
