    "id": "2024_24",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "24",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to determine whether a presented hypothesis is weakened or strengthened based on presented experimental results, where the hypothesis concerns how people judge an actor's morality when the actor acts under situational pressure.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "<Hypothesis> People judge Action X, which is performed under situational pressure, and the morality of the actor as follows: - If X is bad, they judge it as voluntary; if X is good, they judge it as coerced.- If X is judged as voluntary, people judge the actor’s morality based on X, but if X is judged as coerced, they don’t use X to infer morality.<Experiment> 100 participants are divided into Group 1 and Group 2. Group 1 reads Passage 1 and Group 2 reads Passage 2, respectively.Passage 1: Alice and Bob encounter a homeless person. Alice tells Bob to give all the money he has to the homeless person. Bob gives all the money he had to the homeless person. → Since the action is good, it is considered coerced. No judgment of morality.Passage 2: Alice and Bob encounter a homeless person. Alice tells Bob to take the homeless person’s money. Bob takes the homeless person’s money. → Since the action is bad, it is considered voluntary. Judgment of morality.After reading the passage, each group is asked whether Bob’s action was voluntary or coerced, and whether Bob is moral or not. <question> Which of the following evaluations about the text is/are correct according to <statements>? <statements> (a) If most people in Group 1 who answered that Bob’s action was coerced also answered that Bob is moral, the <hypothesis> is weakened.(b) If most people in Group 1 answered that Bob’s action was coerced, but most in Group 2 answered that Bob’s action was voluntary, the <hypothesis> is weakened.(c) If most people in Group 1 answered that they don’t know whether Bob is moral or not, but most in Group 2 answered that Bob is immoral, the <hypothesis> is weakened. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If most people in Group 1 who answered that Bob’s action was coerced also answered that Bob is moral, the <hypothesis> is weakened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If most people in Group 1 answered that Bob’s action was coerced, but most in Group 2 answered that Bob’s action was voluntary, the <hypothesis> is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If most people in Group 1 answered that they don’t know whether Bob is moral or not, but most in Group 2 answered that Bob is immoral, the <hypothesis> is weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "According to the <hypothesis>, when an actor performs an action under situational pressure, people’s judgment of the actor’s morality differs depending on whether the action itself is good or bad. If the action is good, people judge the action as coerced, and if the action is judged as coerced, they do not judge the actor’s morality based on it. On the other hand, if the action is bad, people judge the action as voluntary, and if it is judged as voluntary, they judge the actor’s morality based on it. In Passages 1 and 2, Bob’s actions can be seen as a good action and a bad action, respectively. Therefore, according to the <hypothesis>, people in Group 1 would judge Bob’s action as coerced and would not judge Bob’s morality from it, whereas people in Group 2 would judge Bob’s action as voluntary and judge Bob’s morality based on it.<Explanation of the Statements>(a) Since Bob’s action in Passage 1 is a good action, according to the <hypothesis>, people would judge Bob’s action as coerced and would not judge Bob’s morality based on his action. If most people in Group 1 who answered that Bob’s action was coerced also answered that Bob is moral, this means they are judging Bob’s morality based on his action. This is contrary to the prediction of the <hypothesis> and thus weakens it. Statement (a) is a correct evaluation.(b) Since Bob’s action in Passage 1 and Passage 2 are, respectively, a good action and a bad action, according to the <hypothesis>, people would judge the former as coerced and the latter as voluntary. Therefore, if most people in Group 1 judge the former as coerced and most in Group 2 judge the latter as voluntary, this matches the prediction of the <hypothesis>. Thus, such a result would not weaken the <hypothesis>. Statement (b) is an incorrect evaluation.(c) Since Bob’s actions in Passage 1 and Passage 2 are, respectively, good and bad, according to the <hypothesis>, people would not judge Bob’s morality from Passage 1 but would make judgments about his morality in Passage 2. Therefore, if most people in Group 1 answer that they don’t know whether Bob is moral, and most in Group 2 answer that Bob is immoral, this matches the prediction of the <hypothesis>. Thus, such a result would not weaken the <hypothesis>. Statement (c) is an incorrect evaluation.Only (a) is correct, so the answer is ①."
  },
