    "id": "2024_25",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "25",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to grasp the structure of an argument that the necessity of norms and values cannot be derived from the nature of reason.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "(a) It is not possible to derive the necessity of ethical norms or values from the nature of human reason. (b) Norms and values reflect social and historical contingency. (c) If we were placed in different social and cultural conditions than we are now, we would have faced different practical problems and possessed different systems of norms and values. (d) No ethical norm can arise solely from the fact that we are rational beings, and all values depend on our evaluative perspectives. (e) Ethical norms are not \"facts of reason\" that can be derived from the nature of human reason. (f) While we may be able to derive the laws of pure logic and mathematics from the laws of reason, we cannot, in the same way, deduce the moral laws that we truly accept. (g) The source of value must be sought in the evaluative attitudes of particular agents. (h) What makes something valuable ultimately lies in the fact that we regard it as valuable. <question> Which of the following is the most appropriate analysis of the structure of the given argument? <choices> (in DOT) ① digraph G1 { b -> c; c -> a; h -> g; f -> e; g -> e; a -> d; e -> d; } ② digraph G2 { b -> c; c -> a; f -> e; h -> g; a -> d; e -> d; g -> d; } ③ digraph G3 { c -> b; b -> d; f -> e; h -> g; d -> a; e -> a; g -> a; } ④ digraph G4 { c -> b; f -> e; h -> g; b -> a; e -> d; g -> d; d -> a; } ⑤ digraph G5 { c -> b; b -> d; h -> g; f -> e; g -> e; d -> a; e -> a; }",
