    "original_rationale": "The given argument can be briefly summarized as follows. It is not possible to derive the necessity of ethical norms or values from the nature of human reason. The grounds for this are as follows: (Ground 1) Norms and values reflect social and historical contingency, and (Ground 2) No ethical norm can arise solely from the fact that we are rational beings, and all values depend on our evaluative perspectives. Both (Ground 1) and (Ground 2) are in turn supported by further premises, and schematically the argument has the following structure. (Below, for example, (Ground 1-1) is a premise supporting (Ground 1), and (Ground 2-2-1) is a premise supporting (Ground 2-2).)(Conclusion) It is not possible to derive the necessity of ethical norms or values from the nature of human reason. (ⓐ) (Ground 1): Norms and values reflect social and historical contingency. (ⓑ) (Ground 1-1): If we were placed in different social and cultural conditions, we would have faced different practical problems and possessed different systems of norms and values. (ⓒ) (Ground 2): No ethical norm can arise solely from the fact that we are rational beings, and all values depend on our evaluative perspectives. (ⓓ) (Ground 2-1): Ethical norms are not \"facts of reason\" that can be derived from the nature of human reason. (ⓔ) (Ground 2-1-1): While we may be able to derive the laws of pure logic and mathematics from the laws of reason, we cannot, in the same way, deduce the moral laws that we truly accept. (ⓕ) (Ground 2-2): The source of value must be sought in the evaluative attitudes of particular agents. (ⓖ) (Ground 2-2-1): What makes something valuable ultimately lies in the fact that we regard it as valuable. (ⓗ)Answer explanation: ④ The argument structure diagram that best satisfies the analysis explained above is ④."
