  {
    "id": "2024_27",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "27",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to analyze psychological hypotheses about factors influencing juror decisions and experimental designs to test these hypotheses, and to correctly determine whether given experimental results weaken or strengthen the hypothesis.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "Even though jurors infer, based on probabilistic evidence, that it is highly likely the defendant is responsible for the case, there is a tendency for them to hesitate in returning a guilty verdict or a verdict in favor of the plaintiff. There is a <hypothesis> that explains this phenomenon. According to this <hypothesis>, even if evidence that does not explicitly present who is responsible for the event is itself considered valid, its value as information is evaluated as low. Therefore, such information has less influence on the verdicts of jurors. In other words, there is a psychological difference for jurors between testimony such as “There is an 80% probability that the defendant is responsible,” and “Based on evidence that has an 80% probability of being correct, the defendant is responsible.” In order to test this hypothesis, the researchers conducted an <experiment>. In the <experiment>, mock jurors were made to read the following case summary: “Alice sued bus company B for suspicion that B’s bus hit her dog while they were out walking. In the city where Alice lives, there are only two companies: Company B operates only blue buses and Company G operates only gray buses, but Alice is color-blind and could not confirm the color of the bus that caused the accident.” After randomly splitting the mock jurors into two groups, Group 1 was presented only with Investigator's Testimony X, while Group 2 was given both Testimonies X and Y. X: As a result of applying tire matching technology, 8 out of B’s 10 buses and 2 out of G’s 10 buses were a perfect match with the tire tracks collected from the scene of the accident. Y: Based on the tire track evidence, I believe that it was B’s bus that hit the plaintiff’s dog. The mock jurors were then asked to indicate the probability that B’s bus actually hit the dog and to render a verdict on B. As a result of the experiment, the value for ‘subjective probability’—the probability the mock jurors believed B was responsible—was the same for both groups, and the ‘plaintiff verdict rate’—the proportion of mock jurors in each group who concluded that B was responsible—was lower than the subjective probability in both groups. <question> Select, from the <statements> below, only those evaluation(s) of the above text that are appropriate, as they are stated. <statements> (a) If the plaintiff verdict rate in Group 1 is significantly lower than that in Group 2, the <hypothesis> is weakened. (b) If the difference between subjective probability and plaintiff verdict rate is significantly greater in Group 1 than in Group 2, the <hypothesis> is strengthened. (c) If, when testimony from a witness who saw a gray bus hitting Alice’s dog is additionally presented to both groups, the plaintiff verdict rate in Group 2 decreases significantly more than in Group 1, the <hypothesis> is weakened. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(s) of the above text that are appropriate, as they are stated. <statements>",
      "statement_2": "(a) If the plaintiff verdict rate in Group 1 is significantly lower than that in Group 2, the <hypothesis> is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(b) If the difference between subjective probability and plaintiff verdict rate is significantly greater in Group 1 than in Group 2, the <hypothesis> is strengthened.",
      "statement_4": "(c) If, when testimony from a witness who saw a gray bus hitting Alice’s dog is additionally presented to both groups, the plaintiff verdict rate in Group 2 decreases significantly more than in Group 1, the <hypothesis> is weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "According to the probabilistic evidence, even the jurors acknowledge that it is highly probable that the defendant is responsible, yet when actually rendering a verdict, a general tendency is observed in which they do not follow this probabilistic evidence. Given the probabilistic evidence, it would seem natural for a verdict to be returned finding the defendant responsible; however, in reality, contrary to such rational judgment, jurors hesitate to enter a verdict of responsibility against the defendant. This phenomenon is named the Wells effect, after its discoverer, Wells. This experiment is part of a series of experiments conducted to verify the <hypothesis> relating to the Wells effect. According to the <hypothesis>, no matter how statistically reliable the probabilistic evidence appears, if the evidence does not clearly specify who is responsible for the incident, it has less influence on the verdict of the juror. In this <experiment>, X corresponds to evidence that does not explicitly state who is responsible, while X and Y together constitute evidence that explicitly identifies the party responsible. <Explanation of the choices> (a): According to the <hypothesis>, since Group 1 is only presented with probabilistic evidence, its members would be hesitant to return a plaintiff-favoring verdict against B, and thus the plaintiff verdict rate would be lower. On the other hand, Group 2 is not only given probabilistic evidence but also the investigator’s testimony explicitly stating B’s responsibility, so their plaintiff verdict rate should be higher. Therefore, if the plaintiff verdict rate for Group 1 is significantly lower than Group 2, this does not weaken but rather strengthens the <hypothesis>. Thus, (a) is not an appropriate evaluation. (b): The text states that the subjective probability was the same for both groups, and the plaintiff verdict rate in each group was lower than the subjective probability. As explained in (a), in accordance with the <hypothesis>, Group 1’s plaintiff verdict rate should be low, while Group 2’s should be relatively higher. Thus, the difference between subjective probability and plaintiff verdict rate would be greater in Group 1 than in Group 2. Therefore, if the difference between subjective probability and plaintiff verdict rate is significantly greater in Group 1 than in Group 2, the <hypothesis> is strengthened. (b) is an appropriate evaluation. (c): This new testimony, which clearly states who is responsible for the incident, serves the same effect as Y. However, this testimony is to the effect that G, not B, is responsible, so it is at odds with the testimony Y, asserting B’s responsibility. As explained in (a), according to the <hypothesis>, the plaintiff verdict rate of Group 1 would already have been relatively low compared to that of Group 2. Therefore, upon introduction of this new testimony, there would be fewer jurors whose judgment changes in Group 1 than Group 2. In contrast, since the plaintiff verdict rate in Group 2 had been relatively high, a greater proportion in that group might change their verdict based on the new information. That is, the plaintiff verdict rate might decrease more in Group 2 than in Group 1 as a result of the new testimony. Accordingly, if the plaintiff verdict rate in Group 2 decreases significantly more than in Group 1 after the new testimony, this does not weaken the <hypothesis>. Thus, (c) is not an appropriate evaluation."
  },
