    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "<Theory> People tend to find it easier to process information when it is presented in a familiar order. The feeling that information processing is easy leads to a sense of familiarity with the subject, and as a result, the preference for the subject increases. Since the main ingredient and final product inherently contain the concept of temporal flow in the information itself, if consumers are first presented with the main ingredient of a product and then the final product made from that ingredient, it is expected that consumers’ preference for the product will be higher than if the information is presented in the reverse order.However, this effect does not appear with the same strength for everyone. The lower the familiarity with the product, the greater the effect, and the higher the familiarity, the smaller the effect.<Experiment> A total of 60 men and 60 women, selected randomly, were first surveyed for their familiarity with olive soap. According to the survey results, men generally had low familiarity, while women had high familiarity. The male and female participants were divided into two groups each. One group in each gender was shown an advertisement in which the main ingredient, olive oil, was presented before olive soap; the other group was shown an advertisement in which olive soap was presented before olive oil. Afterwards, the ease of information processing regarding olive soap and the preference for the product were measured for each of the four groups. <question> Which of the following, according to <statements>, is a correct assessment regarding the above text? <statements> (a) If men had a significantly higher preference for olive soap when the information was presented in the ‘olive oil–olive soap’ order, compared to the reverse order, then <Theory> would be supported. (b) If women felt that information processing was easier when the information was presented in the ‘olive soap–olive oil’ order than in the reverse order, but men did not feel this way, then <Theory> would be supported. (c) If, among individuals with similar familiarity with olive soap in all groups, there was no significant difference in product preference between men and women, then this result is compatible with <Theory>. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If men had a significantly higher preference for olive soap when the information was presented in the ‘olive oil–olive soap’ order, compared to the reverse order, then <Theory> would be supported.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If women felt that information processing was easier when the information was presented in the ‘olive soap–olive oil’ order than in the reverse order, but men did not feel this way, then <Theory> would be supported.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If, among individuals with similar familiarity with olive soap in all groups, there was no significant difference in product preference between men and women, then this result is compatible with <Theory>."
    },
    "original_rationale": "<Rationale>The elements of <Theory> are as follows:Ⓐ People tend to feel that information processing is easier when information is presented in a familiar order.Ⓑ The sense that information processing is easy leads to a sense of familiarity with the subject.Ⓒ If this sense of familiarity with the subject increases, preference for the subject also increases.Ⓓ This effect is greater when familiarity with the product is lower, and smaller when familiarity is higher.According to <Theory>, Ⓐ → Ⓑ → Ⓒ, and Ⓓ means that ‘familiarity’ moderates this effect.<Explanation of statements> (a) According to <Theory>, if information is presented in the ‘olive oil–olive soap’ order rather than the ‘olive soap–olive oil’ order, people will feel that information processing is easier (Ⓐ); the sense that information processing is easier will lead to greater familiarity with the target (Ⓑ); and greater familiarity with the target will increase liking (Ⓒ). Also, this effect will be stronger for men, who have lower familiarity (Ⓓ). Thus, (a) is a correct assessment.(b) According to <Theory>, though there may be differences in degree, both women and men should feel that information processing is easier when information is presented in the ‘olive oil–olive soap’ order compared to the reverse. As described in (a), men would feel this effect more strongly than women. Thus, (b) is not a correct assessment.(c) According to Ⓒ, people with similar familiarity should also have similar product preferences. Therefore, if men and women with similar familiarity do not show a significant difference in preference, this result is compatible with <Theory>. Thus, (c) is a correct assessment.Therefore, only (a) and (c) are correct assessments, so the answer is ③."
  },
  {
    "id": "2024_29",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "29",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to grasp the core elements of arguments explaining economic behavior and market operations, properly analyze the structure of the debate, and compare and evaluate each argument.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "Alice: Economic behavior is the action of independent and rational individuals pursuing their own self-interest. The foundation of the ideal market, where perfect competition and self-regulation occur, is precisely the behavior of such atomized and rational people. Social relationships among people only hinder the competitive market.Bob: But, in reality, the market doesn’t function so perfectly. Coercion and deception also occur in the market. Of course, even coercion and deception arise from the pursuit of self-interest. Can the market really exert enough self-regulation to suppress people’s coercion and deception? At the very least, a certain degree of trust among people must be present.Charlie: The source of such trust is generalized morality. There exists an implicit agreement that one must respect others, and people mostly follow that agreement automatically. Humans naturally obey the commands of the norms and value systems we agree upon, because these are thoroughly internalized through socialization. Because morality is strongly shared, orderly transactions are guaranteed.Bob: However, in reality, it’s rare to find transaction situations where we can confirm that generalized morality is at work and that economic behavior is based on trust. To explain the general existence of orderly transactions in the market, we must pay attention to the fact that the intentional actions of agents are rooted in their current, concrete social relationships. What fosters trust and suppresses wrongdoing in the market are these specific private relationships and their networks. We prefer to trade with people who have a good reputation, not simply relying on generalized morality. Moreover, rather than depending only on general reputation, we try to gather information from acquaintances who know the trading partner well. Of course, we also try to maintain our own good reputation. The assumption of atomized individuals cannot explain reality. <question> Which of the following analyses of the above debate is/are correct according to the statements in <statements>? <statements> (a). Both Alice and Bob assume individuals who pursue their own self-interest. (b). Alice does not agree, but Bob does agree, with the claim that the social nature of relationships, which naturally develop as economic relations are sustained, is positive for economic life. (c). The concrete social relationships in which individuals are involved at the time of decision-making are more important to Bob than to Charlie. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) . Both Alice and Bob assume individuals who pursue their own self-interest.",
      "statement_2": "(b) . Alice does not agree, but Bob does agree, with the claim that the social nature of relationships, which naturally develop as economic relations are sustained, is positive for economic life.",
      "statement_3": "(c) . The concrete social relationships in which individuals are involved at the time of decision-making are more important to Bob than to Charlie."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Alice takes the utilitarian, classical and neo-classical economic perspective. Charlie holds an extreme sociological position. Alice assumes under-socialized actors, while Charlie assumes over-socialized actors. In contrast, Bob criticizes both these positions for presupposing atomized individuals free from the context of social relations when explaining economic behavior, and emphasizes that even for rational actors, their private relationships and networks matter. <Explanation of items> (a). Alice explicitly states, “Economic behavior is the action of individuals pursuing their own self-interest.” Although Bob refutes Alice's opinion, Bob also asserts that coercion and deception arise in the process of pursuing self-interest, indicating that Bob also assumes individuals pursue their own self-interest. Thus, (a) is a correct analysis. (b). Alice considers social relationships to be an impediment to competitive markets, so she would not agree that the social nature of relationships, which naturally develop as economic relations are sustained, is positive for economic life. However, Bob, seeing that concrete social relationships foster trust, would agree with the claim. Thus, (b) is also a correct analysis. (c). Bob considers the concrete social relationships an individual maintains at the time of decision-making to have an important impact on intentional action, whereas Charlie focuses on generalized morality and does not consider current concrete social relationships to be very important in behavior. No matter what the present social relationships are, people follow the internalized, generalized morality due to socialization. Thus, (c) is a correct analysis. Since (a), (b), and (c) are all correct, the answer is ⑤."
  },
  {
    "id": "2024_37",
    "year": "2024",
    "problem_idx": "37",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to appropriately analyze and evaluate a text describing the phenomenon where, upon the transmission of DNA containing genetic information from parents to offspring, parental genes are not functionally equally inherited due to DNA methylation, leading to the exclusive expression of either paternal or maternal alleles.",
    "domain": null,
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "Mendelian genetics is based on the idea that ‘ⓐit does not matter whether a particular gene comes from the sperm or the egg.’ However, in mammals, it has been found that for some genes, it is important whether they came from the sperm or the egg, and only the allele derived exclusively from either the sperm or the egg is expressed. This phenomenon can occur due to DNA methylation, a process in which a methyl group (–CH₃) attaches to DNA. During spermatogenesis and oogenesis, existing DNA methylation is reset, and new, sex-specific DNA methylation occurs. The Surani research team experimentally demonstrated the idea that ‘ⓑthe activity of a gene at a specific region of DNA can differ depending on whether this region was inherited from either parent.’ The research team created genetically modified mice with a specific DNA inserted that makes it easy to measure the degree of methylation. They investigated the methylation level of this DNA in the offspring of these mice, and found that the DNA inherited from the mother was highly methylated, whereas the DNA inherited from the father was methylated to a lesser extent. DNA methylation is related to the regulation of gene expression. Regulation of gene expression by DNA methylation can occur either through ‘ⓒa mechanism in which the methyl group interferes with the binding of a regulatory protein to the DNA’ or ‘ⓓa mechanism in which a regulatory protein binds to the DNA via the methyl group.’ At this time, the regulatory protein can either activate or suppress the expression of the gene. During the early embryonic development of mice, only gene X derived from the father is expressed, and the gene X derived from the mother is not, because a specific regulatory protein binds only to the DNA of the maternally inherited gene X. <question> Which of the following evaluations regarding the above passage is/are appropriate as stated in <statements>? <statements> (a) The experimental results of the Surani research team reinforce ⓐ. (b) If Prader-Willi syndrome appears in a child only when a particular chromosomal abnormality is inherited from the father but not when inherited from the mother, then ⓑ is reinforced. (c) If only the DNA of gene X inherited from the mother is methylated, then the regulation of gene X's expression corresponds to ⓓ among the mechanisms ⓒ and ⓓ. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) The experimental results of the Surani research team reinforce ⓐ.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If Prader-Willi syndrome appears in a child only when a particular chromosomal abnormality is inherited from the father but not when inherited from the mother, then ⓑ is reinforced.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If only the DNA of gene X inherited from the mother is methylated, then the regulation of gene X's expression corresponds to ⓓ among the mechanisms ⓒ and ⓓ."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The passage explains that the phenomenon where only the allele derived from either the sperm or the egg is exclusively expressed can occur due to DNA methylation, and that the methylation pattern of DNA and gene activity may differ depending on which parent the DNA was inherited from. The passage also describes how the presence or absence of regulatory protein binding due to DNA methylation can affect gene expression, and that these regulatory proteins can either activate or suppress gene expression. Based on the content of the passage, one must determine if the experimental findings or information presented in the options reinforce or weaken the ideas stated in the passage, and also determine whether the regulatory protein activates or suppresses gene expression.Option (a): The passage describes that for some genes, it is important whether they were inherited from the sperm or the egg, and that the exclusive expression of either the paternally or maternally inherited allele may be due to sex-specific DNA methylation patterns established during gametogenesis. The Surani research team’s experiment demonstrates that the pattern of DNA methylation differs between DNA inherited from the sperm and that inherited from the egg. This result weakens, rather than reinforces, the idea that it does not matter whether a gene comes from the sperm or the egg. Therefore, (a) is not an appropriate evaluation.Option (b): If a particular chromosomal abnormality leads to Prader-Willi syndrome when inherited from the father, but not when inherited from the mother, this supports the idea ‘that the activity of a gene at a specific region of DNA can differ depending on whether this region was inherited from either parent’ (ⓑ). Thus, (b) is an appropriate evaluation.Option (c): In the latter part of the passage, it is explained that “only gene X derived from the father is expressed, and the maternally inherited gene X is not, because a specific regulatory protein binds only to the DNA of the maternally inherited gene X.” From this statement, we can determine that this specific regulatory protein suppresses gene X expression. Moreover, if only the DNA of the maternally inherited gene X is methylated, the specific regulatory protein must be binding to methylated DNA. Therefore, gene X is regulated by a mechanism in which a regulatory protein binds to DNA via the methyl group, corresponding to ⓓ among the mechanisms ⓒ and ⓓ. Thus, (c) is an appropriate evaluation.Only options (b) and (c) are appropriate evaluations based on the passage, so the answer is ④."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_01",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "1",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the content of the debate surrounding the shortening of the mandatory service period for non-commissioned officers and officers, to accurately understand the rationale behind the arguments, and to determine whether given information strengthens or weakens each viewpoint.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "Country X, which operates a compulsory military service system, stipulates in its \"Military Service Act\" that the mandatory service period for those required to serve is 3 years for rank-and-file soldiers, 7 years for non-commissioned officers (NCOs), and 10 years for commissioned officers. Recently, an amendment to the \"Military Service Act\" has been submitted to the National Assembly of country X, which would reduce the mandatory service period for NCOs and officers to the same level as that of rank-and-file soldiers. The following is a debate between Alice and Bob regarding this amendment.Alice: I am opposed to the amendment. The reason the mandatory service period for officers and NCOs is longer than for rank-and-file soldiers is that, in order to equip themselves with job competencies suitable for their rank, they are appointed after a long period of training at the country's expense. For example, air force pilots or NCOs requiring technical expertise have to undergo lengthy education on expensive specialized equipment. The current mandatory service period is the minimum time required for the country to fully utilize the job competencies of officers and NCOs.Bob: I think differently. The mandatory service of officers and NCOs has both the character of fulfilling the constitutional duty of national defense and the character of realizing the constitutional right to choose one’s occupation. A three-year service period, like that for rank-and-file soldiers, leans more toward the character of fulfilling the national defense duty, but any service period exceeding that is more strongly characterized as occupational activity. Forcing service beyond three years seems to excessively restrict the occupational freedom and the pursuit of happiness of officers and NCOs. <question> Which of the following analyses regarding this debate is/are correct? Choose all correct options from <statements> as they are.<statements>(a) If, due to the advancement of information technology, the automation and modernization of the military have rapidly progressed and the time and cost required to enhance job competency have been significantly reduced compared to the past, Alice’s argument is weakened.(b) According to Country X's \"Military Service Act,\" if individuals can choose among rank-and-file soldier, NCO, and officer at their own will, and only qualified applicants are selected for officers and NCOs, this fact strengthens Bob’s argument.(c) If Country X’s Constitutional Court has judged that the provision of the \"Military Service Act\" setting the mandatory service period at 3 years for rank-and-file soldiers does not violate the constitution, then Alice’s argument is strengthened and Bob’s argument is weakened. <choices>① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If, due to the advancement of information technology, the automation and modernization of the military have rapidly progressed and the time and cost required to enhance job competency have been significantly reduced compared to the past, Alice’s argument is weakened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) According to Country X's \"Military Service Act,\" if individuals can choose among rank-and-file soldier, NCO, and officer at their own will, and only qualified applicants are selected for officers and NCOs, this fact strengthens Bob’s argument.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If Country X’s Constitutional Court has judged that the provision of the \"Military Service Act\" setting the mandatory service period at 3 years for rank-and-file soldiers does not violate the constitution, then Alice’s argument is strengthened and Bob’s argument is weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The amendment aims to shorten the mandatory service period for NCOs and officers to the same level as rank-and-file soldiers. The core of the debate between Alice and Bob is as follows:Alice: The current mandatory service period is the minimum period required for the country to fully utilize the job competencies of officers and NCOs.Bob: Forcing service beyond three years amounts to an excessive restriction on the occupational freedom and the right to pursue happiness of officers and NCOs.Alice is opposed to the amendment (in favor of maintaining the status quo), and Bob supports the amendment (in favor of shortening the mandatory service period for NCOs and officers to that of rank-and-file soldiers).<Explanation of options>(a) If the advancement of information technology causes rapid military automation and modernization, significantly reducing the time and cost required to enhance job competency compared to the past, it can be said that Alice’s view—namely, that the current service period is the minimum required for full utilization of officers’ and NCOs’ job competencies—is weakened. Therefore, (a) is a correct analysis.(b) The fact that there is a choice regarding modes of compulsory service, and that an individual chooses their path knowing the current service period, actually weakens Bob’s argument. Therefore, (b) is an incorrect analysis.(c) The Constitutional Court's judgment that the provision setting the mandatory service period at 3 years for rank-and-file soldiers does not violate the constitution only implies that the compulsory service system itself is constitutional, and is unrelated to whether the service period for NCOs and officers should be shortened—the point under debate between Alice and Bob. Therefore, (c) does not either strengthen or weaken Alice’s or Bob’s argument, making it an incorrect analysis.Since only (a) is a correct analysis among the options, the answer is ①."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_02",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "2",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand the content of the debate surrounding the proposed amendment that permits appeals only for transfer and expulsion among the disciplinary measures against student perpetrators of school violence, and to determine whether given information strengthens or weakens each viewpoint.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "In the face of the growing severity of school violence, as public opinion has risen that the current regulations are insufficient to protect victims and provide prompt remedies, a proposed amendment has been submitted to the National Assembly. Current Regulation – Article ○ (Appeal Request by the Perpetrating Student) If the perpetrating student or their guardian has an objection to \"any measures\" imposed by the Autonomous Committee, they may file an appeal with the Metropolitan or Provincial Student Disciplinary Adjustment Committee within 15 days from the date the measure was received. Proposed Amendment – Article ○ (Appeal Request by the Perpetrating Student) If the perpetrating student or their guardian has an objection to a \"transfer or expulsion measure\" imposed by the Autonomous Committee, they may file an appeal with the Metropolitan or Provincial Student Disciplinary Adjustment Committee within 15 days from the date the measure was received. The following <Opinion> was presented regarding this matter. <Opinion> Parents have the right to participate in the educational process of their underage children, so when the school imposes a disadvantageous measure on a student, they also have the right to express their opinion on the matter. The proposed amendment, by allowing appeals only in cases of transfer and expulsion, \"infringes ⓐ upon such rights of the parents.\" Furthermore, since the amendment permits appeals only to perpetrating students who have received transfer or expulsion measures, it \"results in the unjust discrimination of other perpetrating students and their guardians who have received other measures ⓑ.\" Therefore, the current regulation should be maintained. <question> Which of the following analyses about the <Opinion> is/are correct in the <statements> below? <statements> (a) If legal remedies are available by other means for measures for which appeals are not permitted, ⓐ is mitigated. (b) If the harm suffered by perpetrating students due to transfer or expulsion cannot be restored even if such measures are overturned in a subsequent lawsuit—unlike with other measures—then ⓑ is weakened. (c) If it is the responsibility of schools and society to ensure that all perpetrating students are given the opportunity to appeal and thereby grow into exemplary members of society, then ⓐ is weakened and ⓑ is strengthened. <choices> ① (b) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (a), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If legal remedies are available by other means for measures for which appeals are not permitted, ⓐ is mitigated.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If the harm suffered by perpetrating students due to transfer or expulsion cannot be restored even if such measures are overturned in a subsequent lawsuit—unlike with other measures—then ⓑ is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If it is the responsibility of schools and society to ensure that all perpetrating students are given the opportunity to appeal and thereby grow into exemplary members of society, then ⓐ is weakened and ⓑ is strengthened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Unlike the current regulation, which permits appeals for all measures imposed on students who commit school violence, the proposed amendment allows appeals only for transfer and expulsion measures, thereby narrowing the scope of measures subject to appeal. In response, the <Opinion> argues that the amendment infringes upon the right of parents (the right to express opinions regarding disadvantageous measures by the school) when their children receive measures other than transfer or expulsion; and that by allowing only students who have been given transfer or expulsion to appeal, it results in the unjust discrimination ⓑ of those students and their guardians who have received other measures. <Explanation of the choices> (a) If legal remedies are available by other means for measures for which appeals are not permitted, then parents of students who have received disadvantageous measures from the school can turn to such legal remedies, even if they do not have the opportunity to state their opinions through an appeal. Thus, the claim that the amendment infringes upon parents’ right to express opinions ⓐ is mitigated. Therefore, (a) is not a correct analysis. (b) If the harm suffered by perpetrating students due to transfer or expulsion cannot be restored—even if such measures are later overturned through a lawsuit—then perpetrating students who receive transfer or expulsion measures are in a different position from those who receive other measures. Therefore, allowing appeals only to students who received transfer or expulsion measures can be seen as reasonable differentiation. Thus, the claim that the amendment results in unjust discrimination against other students and guardians ⓑ is weakened. Therefore, (b) is a correct analysis. (c) If it is the responsibility of schools and society to ensure all perpetrating students are given an opportunity to appeal and grow into exemplary members of society, then this means that students and parents who received measures other than transfer or expulsion should also be given an opportunity to appeal—thus, the claim that the amendment infringes upon the parents’ right to express opinions ⓐ is not mitigated. Therefore, (c) is not a correct analysis. Only (b) is a correct analysis from the given choices, so the correct answer is 1."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_05",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "5",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to correctly evaluate <claims> based on an accurate understanding of the justification for content control of contracts concluded by decision-making.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "To control a contract concluded by the parties’ free will, there must be a justified reason. There exist two claims about this justification: Claim A, which states that it is to correct market failure arising from information asymmetry, and Claim B, which states that it is to provide protection from a power imbalance. <Claims> A: Information asymmetry causes market failure by creating a situation in which relevant circumstances significant for the conclusion and content of the contract are unequally distributed between parties. The risk of qualitative deterioration of products resulting from market failure is borne entirely by the party with inferior information. In order to correct market failure caused by information asymmetry, contracts must be controlled. Information asymmetry can be resolved simply by providing the relevant information to the counterparty. Information already known by the other party or information such as market price is considered as having been provided. B: In the hands of the strong, a contract becomes a powerful weapon, while in the hands of the weak, it is a blunt tool. The right to self-determination in contracts is guaranteed only when the parties have equal bargaining power. If one party is a minor and the other is an adult, or if only one party is a state, as in cases where contracts are concluded in a state of power imbalance, only one party’s self-determination is protected, so the contract must be controlled. (a). If Alice, an adult, hands over a manual containing all information about her property to Bob, a minor who has graduated from college, and then enters into a sales contract with him, the control of this contract is not justified by A, but is justified by B. (b). If Charlie, a minor, sells his bicycle at a price much lower than the market price to David, an adult whom he has never met before through an online brokerage platform, the control of this contract is justified by A but not justified by B. (c). If adult Eve and State X both know all information regarding a certain piece of land and then enter into a sales contract regarding that land, the control of this contract is justified neither by A nor by B. <question> Which of the following, among the statements in <statements>, are correct evaluations of the <claims> above? <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": null,
    "original_rationale": "The core content of each claim is as follows:A: This claim seeks the justification for contract control in information asymmetry. It argues that market failure arising from information asymmetry ultimately causes the risk of qualitative deterioration of products, and that this risk should be controlled because it is borne entirely by the party with inferior information.B: This claim seeks the justification for contract control in protecting contracting parties from power imbalance. In the presence of a power imbalance, only one party’s right to self-determination is protected, so contracts must be controlled.<Explanation for each statement>(a). According to A, information asymmetry is resolved as long as Alice (an adult) hands over a manual containing all the information about her property to Bob (a college graduate but minor). Therefore, control of the contract by A is not justified. On the other hand, since Alice is an adult and Bob is a minor, a power imbalance exists between the parties according to B. Therefore, contract control based on B is justified. Thus, (a) is a correct evaluation.(b). For (b), according to A and B, the fact that Charlie (a minor) sold his owned bicycle to David (an adult stranger) via an online brokerage platform is not a significant issue for determining whether contract control is justified. Also, in cases where Charlie, a minor, sells his bicycle at a price lower than the market, the market price is considered publicly available information, so even if a minor sells at a low price, there is no information asymmetry. However, since Charlie is a minor and David is an adult, this alone creates a power imbalance between the parties. Therefore, the contract control between Charlie and David is not justified by A, but is justified by B. Therefore, (b) is an incorrect evaluation.(c). Eve (adult) and State X both know all information about the land in question, so there is no information asymmetry. However, since one of the parties is the state, a power imbalance exists. Therefore, control of the contract between Eve and State X is not justified by A, but is justified by B. Thus, (c) is not a correct evaluation.Of the options, only (a) is a correct evaluation; thus, the answer is ①."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_08",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "8",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to accurately understand and evaluate the view on how the state manages public goods.",
    "domain": "Norms",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "A public good is a commodity that can be collectively used by the public, and its ownership belongs to the people. Anyone can access and use public goods, and no one can be prohibited from using them. However, if public goods are not properly managed, their value inevitably decreases. To prevent such a decline in benefits, the state manages public goods under the name of \"administration.\" However, there is an issue of inefficiency in such cases, so the following <opinion> has been put forward regarding how the state should manage public goods.<opinion>Alice: Since the management of public goods has been completely delegated to the state by the people, the state can manage public goods directly or have a third party do so. In order to efficiently manage public goods and guarantee a quality of service appropriate to the usage price, there is a need to privatize the management of public goods. However, in cases where the state directly manages public goods, citizens have granted the state discretion regarding management methods on the condition that they do not bear any costs exceeding what they would bear under direct state management. The state must satisfy this condition.Bob: Privatization inevitably leads to considerations of profit, so in the end, the cost of using public goods, which was previously managed by the state, will ultimately rise, or there will be a decline in service quality relative to previous prices. Therefore, the state should adopt “co-governance” as an alternative to privatization. Except in cases where it is necessary to prevent a decrease in benefits, the state should not be directly involved in the management of public goods; instead, members of society who use public goods should resolve issues that arise on a self-governing basis. If co-governance in civil society fails, public goods will remain unmanaged. Therefore, members of society must strive to prevent the failure of co-governance. <question> Of the analyses regarding <opinion>, which of the following <statements> are correct? <statements> (a) According to Alice, if, after the privatization of public good X, the usage price exceeds what citizens would have paid if the state had managed it directly, the state cannot make citizens bear the excess portion.(b) According to Bob, if co-governance by members of society fails, the state may become directly involved in the management of public goods.(c) Research indicating that the state can control the usage price of public goods while preventing a qualitative decline in services through privatization would strengthen Alice's opinion and weaken Bob's opinion. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) According to Alice, if, after the privatization of public good X, the usage price exceeds what citizens would have paid if the state had managed it directly, the state cannot make citizens bear the excess portion.",
      "statement_2": "(b) According to Bob, if co-governance by members of society fails, the state may become directly involved in the management of public goods.",
      "statement_3": "(c) Research indicating that the state can control the usage price of public goods while preventing a qualitative decline in services through privatization would strengthen Alice's opinion and weaken Bob's opinion."
    },
    "original_rationale": "In the passage, opinions advocating the management of public goods through privatization and those advocating management through \"co-governance\" are introduced. The main points of each opinion are as follows.Alice: This view argues that since citizens have fully delegated the management of public goods to the state, the state can have a third party manage public goods, and, in order to efficiently manage public goods and guarantee service quality appropriate to the usage price, management should be privatized rather than handled directly by the state.Bob: This view, considering the problems of privatization, argues that public goods should be managed through \"co-governance\" and that except for special circumstances, the state should not become directly involved in managing public goods.Explanation of <statements>:(a) According to Alice, even if the state does not directly manage public goods but instead entrusts them to a third party through measures such as privatization, citizens have granted the state discretion over management methods on the condition that they are not required to bear costs exceeding what they would have borne under direct state management. Therefore, after privatization, if the usage price of public good X exceeds what citizens would have paid under direct state management, the state cannot require citizens to bear the excess portion. Thus, (a) is a correct analysis.(b) According to Bob, if \"co-governance\" fails, then public goods remain unmanaged. If public goods are unmanaged, a decline in benefits will inevitably occur, so the state must act to prevent this decline. In such situations, even according to Bob, the state may directly participate in the management of public goods. Therefore, (b) is a correct analysis.(c) Research showing that through privatization, the state can control the usage price of public goods while preventing a decline in service quality would strengthen Alice's argument that it is possible to guarantee service quality commensurate with usage price through privatization, and it would weaken Bob’s argument, which points out that privatization leads to increased usage prices or a decline in service quality. Therefore, (c) is also a correct analysis.Since (a), (b), and (c) in the <statements> are all correct analyses, the answer is ⑤."
  },
