    "id": "2025_16",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "16",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to accurately understand the content of the given experiment and its implications, and to judge whether additional evidence strengthens or weakens a hypothesis.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "When someone is in trouble and needs help on the street, some passersby engage in prosocial behavior and help the person, while others just walk by. In order to predict whether a passerby will help, what should we identify? Should we know whether the passerby is generous or cold-hearted? Or should we identify external factors apart from personality traits? In order to investigate this, Alice, a psychologist, conducted the following experiment. Alice made 50% of the participants feel good by letting them smell the scent of fresh bread while walking, whereas the other 50% were not exposed to the scent. Immediately after, an assistant playing the role of a passerby dropped a file folder in front of each participant. As a result, 87.5% of the people who smelled the bread helped the passerby, while only 4% of those who did not smell the bread helped. Based on this, Alice came to the following conclusion: Regardless of personality, whether or not a person smelled the bread determines their behavior. In other words, the basis for predicting people’s behavior lies in situational factors, not personality traits. To explain this mechanism, Alice established the following hypothesis: ⓐ “The decisive factor influencing a person’s behavior is not personality but situational factors.” According to this hypothesis, the situational factor of having smelled fresh bread elevated the participants’ moods, which led to a motivation to help others. A small and unexpected good fortune made the person more generous. Based on the above experiment, Alice argued that there is a correlation between ‘prosocial behavior’ and ‘situational factors’. It is surprising that situational factors, rather than personality, determine behavior, but what is even more remarkable is ⓑ that “the factor inducing prosocial behavior can be very trivial or insignificant.” <question> Based on the above passage, which of the following evaluations regarding ⓐ and ⓑ are correct? Select all correct options from <statements>. <statements> (a) If it is found that most people who did not help the passerby were also known to behave selfishly in daily life, ⓐ is strengthened. (b) If it is found that the majority of the participants in Alice’s experiment were known to have altruistic personalities compared to those who were not, ⓐ is weakened. (c) If instead of exposing participants to the smell of bread, 50% of them were allowed to win a valuable prize and the other 50% were not, and the proportion of people who helped was similar to the bread smell experiment, then ⓐ is strengthened, but ⓑ is not weakened. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If it is found that most people who did not help the passerby were also known to behave selfishly in daily life, ⓐ is strengthened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If it is found that the majority of the participants in Alice’s experiment were known to have altruistic personalities compared to those who were not, ⓐ is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If instead of exposing participants to the smell of bread, 50% of them were allowed to win a valuable prize and the other 50% were not, and the proportion of people who helped was similar to the bread smell experiment, then ⓐ is strengthened, but ⓑ is not weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The passage explains an experiment that supports the situationalist perspective—that moral behavior of an actor can emerge from situational factors rather than from the person’s personality. One of the points demonstrated by this experiment is that simply smelling a pleasant scent like fresh bread may cause an individual to engage in prosocial behavior. The derived hypothesis is as follows: The decisive factor influencing a person’s behavior is not personality but situational factors. One noteworthy aspect of the experiment is that the factor influencing the actor’s behavior could be a very trivial situational element.Explanation of <statements>:(a) If most people who did not help the passerby were also known to act selfishly in daily life, this would serve to weaken rather than strengthen ⓐ. This is because their failure to help might be attributed not to the situational factor (not smelling bread) but rather to their selfish personality. Therefore, (a) is not a correct evaluation.(b) Even if it is revealed that most participants in Alice’s experiment had altruistic personalities, this does not weaken ⓐ. This is because the bread smell experiment still demonstrates that even altruistic people’s behavior can change depending on the mood brought on by a situational factor. Therefore, (b) is not a correct evaluation.(c) If, in a revised setup, the same result is observed when half the participants win a valuable prize rather than smelling bread, it supports the hypothesis that situational factors determine behavior, so ⓐ is strengthened. As for ⓑ, since it only asserts that the influencing situational factor can be trivial—even receiving a valuable prize counts as a situational factor, and does not undermine ⓑ. Therefore, (c) is a correct evaluation.Since only (c) correctly evaluates the statements, the answer is ②."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_17",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "17",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to appropriately analyze and evaluate the paradox of 'intention' and 'regret' and the explanation of its structure.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argument Analysis",
    "answer": "4",
    "original_question": "Let us ask a participant in a bet to choose between $1 and $10, instructing them to make a choice that they will later regret. The participant is informed in advance that only if they make a regretful choice will they be awarded an additional $100. Choosing the option that yields more money is considered to be the rational choice, for which there will be no regret; any other choice is considered a regretful one. At first glance, \"ⓐ the rational choice in this bet\" appears to be selecting $1. This is because giving up $10 to take $1 would be a regretful choice, and thus the $100 would be awarded. However, if this is the case, choosing $1 would no longer be a regretful choice, so the $100 would not actually be paid out. Although the choice is made only once, whether it is regarded as a regretful choice changes continuously, causing the payment or non-payment of the $100 to endlessly oscillate between the two. The same thing happens if $10 is chosen. Since choosing $10 instead of $1 is not a regretful choice, the $100 is not paid. In that case, however, this choice becomes a regretful one, so the $100 should then be paid; but then, the choice of $10 again becomes not a regretful choice. Here too, the $100 endlessly oscillates between being awarded and not awarded. Thus, it is impossible to say what the rational choice is in this bet. Let us examine the structure of this bet, following the flow from the point at which one contemplates what choice to make (point 0) through to the point at which one looks back on one’s choice (point 2). The moment the choice between $1 and $10 is made, point 1, lies between points 0 and 2. The intention behind this choice is to experience regret at point 2. The object of this intention is a future event that has not yet occurred. In contrast, regret concerns the past, which has already happened. The participant in this bet intends at point 0 to regret at point 2 the choice made at point 1. But precisely because this intention is realized, the regretful choice made at point 1 becomes a non-regretful choice. And this process repeats endlessly. \"ⓑ The intention when viewing from point 0 to point 2\" and \"the regret when looking back from point 2 to point 1\" lead to a paradoxical outcome. <question> Which of the following analyses about the above passage is correct? Choose every correct statement from <statements>. <statements> (a) If the rules of the bet are changed so that the additional $100 is awarded no matter which choice between $1 and $10 the participant makes, then making a regretful choice becomes impossible. (b) If the rules of the bet are changed so that the additional $100 is awarded only if one does not regret their choice, then ⓐ is to choose $10. (c) For both choosing $1 and choosing $10 in this bet, the intention at ⓑ is the same: to bring about regret at (the subsequent point). <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If the rules of the bet are changed so that the additional $100 is awarded no matter which choice between $1 and $10 the participant makes, then making a regretful choice becomes impossible.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If the rules of the bet are changed so that the additional $100 is awarded only if one does not regret their choice, then ⓐ is to choose $",
      "statement_3": "10. ",
      "statement_4": "(c) For both choosing $1 and choosing $10 in this bet, the intention at ⓑ is the same: to bring about regret at (the subsequent point)."
    },
    "original_rationale": "This bet is structured in such a way that if one anticipates that they will regret their choice and acts accordingly, they ultimately do not regret it, and thus if they switch to the opposite choice they regret it again, losing the prize, and the situation keeps reversing itself. The crucial point here is: \"Although the choice is made only once, whether it is regarded as a regretful choice keeps changing.\" In other words, on the single choice between $1 and $10, the evaluation of whether it is a good or regretful choice keeps flipping. The first paragraph presents this as a sort of thought experiment with a paradoxical outcome. The second paragraph analyzes its logical structure.Explanation of <choices> (a): If $100 is awarded no matter whether $1 or $10 is chosen, the total prize becomes $101 or $110, respectively. According to the conditions given in the passage, it is assumed that one would regret receiving less money. Thus, choosing $1 would still be a regretful choice. Therefore, (a) is not a correct analysis.(b): Since the regret-free choice is the one that yields the greater amount, choosing $10 would be the regret-free choice. In this case, one receives an additional $100, which means the choice remains the rational (regret-free) one. Conversely, if one chooses $1, it is regretful, so the $100 is not paid. Again, the evaluation does not change. Since making the choice that yields more money is rational, the rational choice ⓐ is to choose $10. Thus, (b) is a correct analysis.(c): In the second paragraph, it is stated: \"The intention behind this choice is to experience regret at point 2,\" which clarifies that whether one chooses $1 or $10, the intention at that point is to bring about regret later. Also, the first paragraph shows that choosing $1 targets 'regret of having chosen $1 over $10,' while choosing $10 targets 'regret of not receiving the additional $100.' Thus, (c) is a correct analysis.Since only (b) and (c) are correct in <choices>, the answer is ④."
  },
