    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "(a) The social sciences, which explore human beings and social phenomena, cannot be said to be the same as the natural sciences, which deal with natural phenomena. (b) If there were no differences in their explanatory logic or in their methodology, the social sciences would also be science and thus not much different from the natural sciences. (c) The logic of explaining the actions of active agents with intentions and purposes is clearly different from the logic of explaining natural phenomena. (d) We explain people's actions through reasons. (e) An important feature of explaining actions by reasons is that such explanations have a justificatory dimension. For example, (f) when we explain why Cheolsu (Alice) opened the window by saying that he wanted fresh air, it reveals that this was the appropriate action to take in that situation. (g) The normative aspect of action explanations cannot be found in causal explanations such as explaining gas expansion through temperature increase. (h) If all human actions and social phenomena were merely a kind of physical phenomenon, then social science and natural science could be seen as similar in methodology. (i) However, the claim that all the various phenomena in this world can be reduced to mere physical phenomena is unconvincing. Therefore, (j) there is no reason to believe that there are no differences in methodology between social science and natural science. <question> Which of the following most appropriately analyzes the structure of the above argument? <choices> (in DOT) ① digraph G1 { f -> e; d -> c; e -> c; g -> c; i -> h; h -> j; c -> b; j -> b; b -> a; } ② digraph G2 { f -> e; d -> c; e -> c; g -> c; h -> j; i -> j; b -> a; c -> a; j -> a; } ③ digraph G3 { f -> e; e -> d; g -> d; i -> h; h -> j; d -> c; b -> a; c -> a; j -> a; } ④ digraph G4 { f -> e; d -> c; e -> c; g -> c; c -> a; i -> h; a -> j; b -> j; h -> j; } ⑤ digraph G5 { f -> e; e -> d; g -> d; b -> c; d -> c; a -> j; c -> j; h -> j; i -> j; }.",
