    "original_rationale": "Assessment Objective: This question evaluates the ability to accurately analyze the structure of the argument in a passage regarding the methodology and metaphysics of the social sciences.How to solve: The correct answer is ②. The conclusion of the given argument is ⓐ. This can be inferred from ⓑ, ⓒ, and ⓓ. If we logically trace the sentence corresponding to the \"if\" part of the conditional statement in ⓑ — \"if there were no differences in their explanatory logic or in their methodology,\" — we can see that the combination of ⓒ and ⓓ directly denies precisely this part of ⓑ. ⓒ asserts that the logic of explaining human actions in social sciences is different from that for natural sciences, and ⓓ states that there is a methodological difference between social science and natural science. Therefore, the latter part of the conditional in ⓑ — \"the social sciences would also be science and thus not much different from the natural sciences\" — cannot be inferred. ⓐ asserts this. Recognizing this core structure, we see that the rest of the sentences provide subordinate arguments supporting ⓒ and ⓓ. (e) supports (d) by providing an example, and the combination of (c), (d), and (g) together supports ⓒ by arguing that the logic of explaining human behavior is different from that for natural phenomena. In addition, (i) directly denies the first part of the conditional in (h), so the latter part of (h) cannot be inferred. Since (j) asserts this, we can see that the combination of (h) and (i) supports (j). Answer Explanation: Among answer choices ①~⑤, only ② correctly analyzes the structure of the argument, while ①, ③, ④, and ⑤ do not. Therefore, the correct answer is ②."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_22",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "22",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand various views on the existence of a group and, based on the information provided in the prompt, to determine what can be inferred from each view.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "Alice, Bob, and Charlie formed a dance group called “Samshingi.” The following are discussions about the existence of the group. A: There is no such thing as a group. The only things that exist are the members of the group. For example, the statement “Samshingi performed” does not make sense; instead, one should say “Alice, Bob, and Charlie performed together.” B: Samshingi is a new entity distinct from the three individuals, but it is identical to the mere collection of Alice, Bob, and Charlie. Samshingi, as the collection of Alice, Bob, and Charlie, has the three as its parts and occupies a specific space. C: Even if the members change, Samshingi can continue to exist. Samshingi comes into existence only when the three form the group, but it is different from each individual or their mere collection. Samshingi should be seen not as something that occupies a particular space, but as an abstract entity. <question> Which of the following can be properly inferred from the above? Choose all correct statements from <statements> as they are. <statements> (a) Both A and B agree that only Alice, Bob, and Charlie exist, and that the group Samshingi does not exist. (b) Suppose that after the formation of Samshingi, Alice, Bob, and Charlie become interested in chess and form a chess club called “Checkmate.” B agrees, but C does not, that Samshingi and Checkmate are identical. (c) Both A and C agree that Samshingi continues to exist even if Alice is replaced by a new member. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
