      "statement_3": "(c) Both A and C agree that Samshingi continues to exist even if Alice is replaced by a new member."
    },
    "original_rationale": "This problem presents various perspectives on the existence of social groups. Each perspective is as follows: A: According to A, groups do not exist. Only the individual members exist. From this viewpoint, the term “Samshingi” does not refer to any entity. Therefore, strictly speaking, the statement “Samshingi performed” cannot be true. B: According to B, the group exists as a concrete entity. The group is identical to the mere collection of its members. For instance, Samshingi is identical to the collection of Alice, Bob, and Charlie, and since the collection occupies a particular space, the group is a concrete entity. In this view, “Samshingi performed” can be understood as “the collection of Alice, Bob, and Charlie performed,” and if the collection did perform, the sentence is true. C: According to C, the group can continue to exist even when its members are replaced. The group, as an entity, is different from each member or their collection and, since it does not occupy a specific space, is considered an abstract entity. Such an abstract entity comes into existence only when the group is formed. <statements> analysis (a) According to A, the group does not exist, and only the individual members do. Therefore, there is no group Samshingi that is distinct from Alice, Bob, and Charlie. According to B, however, the group does exist and is identical to the mere collection of the members. Because A agrees but B does not, (a) is not a correct inference. (b) According to B, Samshingi is identical to the collection of Alice, Bob, and Charlie. Checkmate is also identical to the collection of Alice, Bob, and Charlie. Therefore, Samshingi and Checkmate are the same entity. According to C, a group only comes into existence when it is formed, and since Samshingi and Checkmate were formed at different times, they are not the same. B agrees and C disagrees, so (b) is a correct inference. (c) According to A, Samshingi does not exist regardless of whether members are replaced. According to C, Samshingi is an entity capable of persisting even when its members are replaced. Therefore, A does not agree but C does, so (c) is not a correct inference. Only (b) is a correct inference, so the answer is ②."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_23",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "23",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to understand two different viewpoints on the question 'What is a proposition?' and, based on the information provided in the passage, to determine what can be inferred from each viewpoint.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "5",
    "original_question": "The meaning that a sentence carries is commonly called a \"proposition.\" Below are two different views on what a proposition is. Alice: The proposition expressed by a sentence is the set of possible worlds in which that sentence is true. For example, the sentences \"Suchul is tall\" and \"Suchul is a student\" express different propositions, since the set of possible worlds where Suchul is tall and the set of possible worlds where Suchul is a student are different sets. If a certain sentence is true in every possible world, then the proposition it expresses is the set of all possible worlds. For instance, the sentence \"3 is odd or not odd\" expresses the proposition which is the set of all possible worlds. Bob: A proposition is a kind of ordered pair. For example, the proposition expressed by the sentence \"3 is odd\" can be understood as an ordered pair composed of the object referred to by \"3\" and the property referred to by \"is odd.\" If we let the object referred to by \"3\" be m and the property referred to by \"is odd\" be F, then the proposition expressed by \"3 is odd\" is <m, F>. As another example, the sentence \"Suchul loves Heeyoung\" expresses a proposition that can be understood as an ordered triplet composed of the object referred to by \"Suchul,\" the object referred to by \"Heeyoung,\" and the binary relation referred to by \"loves.\" If the object referred to by \"Suchul\" is a, the object referred to by \"Heeyoung\" is b, and the binary relation referred to by \"loves\" is r, then the proposition expressed by \"Suchul loves Heeyoung\" is <a, b, r>. <question> Which of the following can be correctly inferred? Choose as many as applicable from <statements>. <statements> (a). Both Alice and Bob would agree that, provided \"Suchul\" and \"Heeyoung\" refer to different objects, the sentences \"Suchul loves Heeyoung\" and \"Heeyoung loves Suchul\" express different propositions. (b). A person who believes that the sentences \"A round square exists\" and \"3 is odd and not odd\" have different meanings would oppose Alice's view. (c). If \"Morning Star\" and \"Evening Star\" refer to the same object, then someone who believes that the sentences \"The Morning Star is beautiful\" and \"The Evening Star is beautiful\" have different meanings would oppose Bob's view. <choices> ① (b) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (a), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) . Both Alice and Bob would agree that, provided \"Suchul\" and \"Heeyoung\" refer to different objects, the sentences \"Suchul loves Heeyoung\" and \"Heeyoung loves Suchul\" express different propositions.",
      "statement_2": "(b) . A person who believes that the sentences \"A round square exists\" and \"3 is odd and not odd\" have different meanings would oppose Alice's view.",
      "statement_3": "(c) . If \"Morning Star\" and \"Evening Star\" refer to the same object, then someone who believes that the sentences \"The Morning Star is beautiful\" and \"The Evening Star is beautiful\" have different meanings would oppose Bob's view."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The passage introduces two different perspectives on the question of what a proposition is. Each view is as follows: Alice: According to Alice, the proposition expressed by a sentence is the set of possible worlds in which the sentence is true. For example, the proposition expressed by the sentence \"Suchul is tall\" is the set of all possible worlds where \"Suchul is tall\" holds. If a certain sentence is true in all possible worlds, then the proposition it expresses is the set of all possible worlds; if a sentence is false in all possible worlds, the proposition it expresses is the empty set. Bob: According to Bob, a proposition is a sort of ordered pair built from the referents of its sub-expressions. For example, the proposition expressed by \"3 is odd\" is the ordered pair consisting of the object referred to by \"3\" and the property referred to by \"is odd.\" \"4 is odd\" expresses the ordered pair of the referent of \"4\" and the referent of \"is odd.\" Since the referents of \"3\" and \"4\" are not identical, these two ordered pairs are not identical, so the two sentences express different propositions.<Explanation> (a). According to Alice, \"Suchul loves Heeyoung\" expresses the proposition as the set of possible worlds in which it is true that Suchul loves Heeyoung, and \"Heeyoung loves Suchul\" expresses the set of possible worlds in which it is true that Heeyoung loves Suchul. These two sets are not identical. Thus, the two sentences express different propositions. On the other hand, according to Bob, if \"Suchul\" refers to a, \"Heeyoung\" refers to b, and \"loves\" refers to the binary relation R, then \"Suchul loves Heeyoung\" expresses the proposition <a, b, R>, and \"Heeyoung loves Suchul\" expresses <b, a, R>. Since a and b are different, <a, b, R> and <b, a, R> are also different. Therefore, both Alice and Bob would agree that the two sentences express different propositions, making (a) a valid inference.(b). Both \"A round square exists\" and \"3 is odd and not odd\" are false in every possible world. Therefore, according to Alice, the proposition expressed by both sentences is the empty set, and thus the same. Anyone who believes that the two sentences have different meanings would oppose Alice's view, so (b) is a valid inference.(c). If \"Morning Star\" and \"Evening Star\" refer to the same object (let's denote it as a), and the property referred to by \"is beautiful\" as G, then according to Bob, \"The Morning Star is beautiful\" and \"The Evening Star is beautiful\" both express the proposition <a, G>. Therefore, anyone who believes these two sentences have different meanings would object to Bob's view, making (c) a valid inference.All of (a), (b), and (c) are valid inferences, so the answer is ⑤."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_24",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "24",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to appropriately analyze philosophical debates regarding fiction and non-fiction.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "2",
    "original_question": "Alice: In art, fiction and non-fiction can be distinguished by whether their content is fabricated or factual. For example, the reason “The Tale of Hong Gildong” is fiction is because its content is invented by the author and did not actually happen. On the other hand, the content of “The Annals of the Joseon Dynasty” consists of things that really happened, and thus the Annals are non-fiction.Bob: It is correct that the term ‘fiction’ generally refers to something that is fabricated. However, at least in the case of artistic fiction, this is not a satisfactory definition. This is because fictional works of art are generally a mixture of things that are made up and things that are factual. Taking into account our conventions of appreciating artworks, fiction and non-fiction in art can be distinguished not by how similar or different their content is to actual facts, but instead by what kind of mental attitude is appropriate for properly appreciating that content. To properly appreciate fiction, one must participate in imagining the presented content; to properly appreciate non-fiction, one must hold a belief about the presented content. For example, to properly appreciate “The Tale of Hong Gildong,” one must take part in imagining the content that “Hong Gildong established the state of Yuldoguk.” If “The Tale of Hong Gildong” were a non-fictional work, we would consider it appropriate to have a belief in the corresponding content, rather than participating in imagining it.Charlie: When appreciating non-fictional works, it is of course appropriate to hold beliefs about the content of the work. However, it does not follow that participating in imagining the content of a non-fiction work is an inappropriate way of appreciating it. Even while watching a non-fiction work such as a documentary dealing with the reality of war, we can vividly imagine the horrific events that occurred, and doing so is an appropriate way to appreciate the work. <question> Which of the following analyses of the debate is/are correct? Choose all that apply from <statements>.<statements>(a) If it is appropriate for us to participate in imagining while reading “The Annals of the Joseon Dynasty”, then Alice’s argument is strengthened while Bob’s argument is weakened.(b) Both Bob and Charlie agree that holding beliefs about the content of non-fictional works is an appropriate way to appreciate them.(c) According to Charlie, among fictional works, there are those for which participating in imagination is an inappropriate way of appreciating them. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If it is appropriate for us to participate in imagining while reading “The Annals of the Joseon Dynasty”, then Alice’s argument is strengthened while Bob’s argument is weakened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) Both Bob and Charlie agree that holding beliefs about the content of non-fictional works is an appropriate way to appreciate them.",
      "statement_3": "(c) According to Charlie, among fictional works, there are those for which participating in imagination is an inappropriate way of appreciating them."
    },
    "original_rationale": "<Rationale>The passage discusses the debate among Alice, Bob, and Charlie on what criteria can distinguish fiction and non-fiction in art. The main points of each position are as follows: Alice: In art, fiction and non-fiction are distinguished by whether their content corresponds to actual events.Bob: In art, fiction and non-fiction are distinguished by what kind of mental attitude we should have toward the work’s content in properly appreciating it. That is, in the case of fiction, we must take an imaginative attitude, while in the case of non-fiction, we must take a believing attitude. Thus, fiction and non-fiction are distinguished according to their association with imagination and belief, respectively.Charlie: While it is certainly appropriate, when appreciating non-fictional works, to hold beliefs about the content, this does not mean that participating in imagining the content is inappropriate. For example, even when appreciating a non-fiction work that deals with the reality of war, it is appropriate to imagine vividly in our minds the horrific events that occurred in it.<Explanation for the items>(a) Alice does not expressly state any position concerning the relationship between imagination and fiction, or between non-fiction and imaginative participation. Therefore, even if participating in imaginative engagement while reading “The Annals of the Joseon Dynasty” is deemed appropriate, Alice’s position is not correspondingly strengthened. (a) is not a correct analysis.(b) Bob states that if “The Tale of Hong Gildong” were a non-fiction work, it would be appropriate to have a belief in its content, which means Bob agrees that holding beliefs about the content of non-fiction is an appropriate way to appreciate it. Meanwhile, Charlie argues that in addition to holding beliefs, it is also appropriate to imagine the content of a non-fictional work. Thus, both agree that holding beliefs about non-fictional content is appropriate. (b) is a correct analysis.(c) Charlie argues that, regarding non-fictional works, holding beliefs about their content as well as imagining it are both appropriate. However, Charlie does not make any claims regarding fictional works. (c) is not a correct analysis.Therefore, only (b) is a correct analysis, and the answer is ②."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_25",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "25",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to appropriately analyze the debate concerning the effect that a creator's act of approving changes to a work's attributes has on the work's identity and meaning.",
    "domain": "Humanities",
    "category": "Argumentation and Rebuttal",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "An artist created an artwork by placing an intricately crafted artificial flower inside a transparent cubic acrylic box with sides about 1 meter long, and installing a fluorescent light on one face. He named the work \"ⓐ Two Types of Permanence\" and sold it to an art museum. He instructed the museum to keep the piece always connected to power, but that when the fluorescent light eventually reached the end of its lifespan, it should be left as is and not replaced. Years later, the fluorescent light finally ceased to function. Judging it important to display the work in its original appearance, the museum suggested to the artist that the light should be replaced with a new one whenever it failed. Although the artist strongly objected, he eventually agreed to allow the light to be replaced, out of concern that refusing the museum's request might make it difficult to display and sell works in the future. A debate arose among critics regarding the impact of the artist's approval on the identity and meaning of the piece. Alice: Since replacing the fluorescent light is based on the artist's approval, this change does not alter the identity of the work. However, because this is a change in an essential attribute of the work, the work should now be seen as having only a superficial meaning, unlike before. Bob: The artist only approved the alteration of the work’s physical attribute due to the museum's pressure. This act of approval does not reflect the artist's true intention. Since the identity of the work lies in the artist’s true intention, even if the work’s physical attribute has changed, its identity remains the same as before, and thus its meaning has also not changed. Charlie: The work was complete at the moment it was made public, and any subsequent act of approval cannot alter its identity—even if that approval aligns with the artist's true intentions. <question> Which of the following analyses regarding the above debate is/are correct? Select all correct options from <statements> as they appear. <statements> (a) According to Alice, a change in some physical attribute of the work can alter its meaning. (b) According to Charlie, an act of approval by the creator after the fact has the same effect as the physical act of making the work at the time of creation. (c) If the museum secretly replaced the fluorescent light of ⓐ with a new one without the creator's knowledge, both Bob and Charlie agree that the meaning of ⓐ could change. <choices> ① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) According to Alice, a change in some physical attribute of the work can alter its meaning.",
      "statement_2": "(b) According to Charlie, an act of approval by the creator after the fact has the same effect as the physical act of making the work at the time of creation.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If the museum secretly replaced the fluorescent light of ⓐ with a new one without the creator's knowledge, both Bob and Charlie agree that the meaning of ⓐ could change."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Alice claims that as long as a change in the work’s attribute occurred with the creator’s approval, it may not damage the identity of the work, yet she also asserts that in this case there has been a change in meaning. On the other hand, Bob asserts that the identity and meaning of the work depend on the artist’s true intention, and that if the act of approval does not reflect the artist's true intention, it cannot affect the work’s identity or meaning. Charlie believes that the identity of the work is completed at the moment it is made public, and that subsequent changes in physical attributes or acts of approval have no effect on the work’s identity. <options> Explanation (a): Alice sees that the change of attribute from “the fluorescent light has reached the end of its lifespan” to “the fluorescent light is continuously functioning” changes the meaning of the work. Thus, Alice does believe that a change in a physical attribute of the work can alter its meaning. (a) is a correct analysis. (b): If an act of approval by the creator after the fact had the same effect as the act of physically creating the work, then post-approval could change its attributes, identity, or meaning. This contradicts Charlie’s view, so (b) is an incorrect analysis. (c): If the museum replaced the light in ⓐ with a new one without the artist’s knowledge, then it would be a change in physical attribute independent of the artist's actual intention. Since Bob claims that the identity and meaning depend on the artist’s actual intention, he would not agree that such unilateral action by the museum could change the meaning of ⓐ. Thus, (c) is an incorrect analysis. Since only (a) is the correct analysis in the options, the answer is ①."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_26",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "26",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to determine the logical impact of additional experimental results on the hypothesis applied and the conclusion derived when verifying the presence of minimal consciousness in brain-damaged patients recovering from a coma.",
    "domain": null,
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "The minimum level of functional status required for a brain-injured patient recovering from a coma to regain normal function is called the minimally conscious state. The minimally conscious state can be diagnosed by determining the presence or absence of top-down cognitive control ability. Top-down cognitive control refers to the cognitive ability used to process information with a specific purpose in order to perform an action. If a brain-injured patient understands the instruction \"Move your left index finger\" and carries out the instructed action, that patient can be said to be in a minimally conscious state. However, even if a patient is in a minimally conscious state, due to paralysis they may not be able to show behavioral responses. Applying the \"ⓐ hypothesis,\" which states that the supplementary motor area (SMA) responds not only when a person actually moves their body but also when they imagine moving, Alice tried to verify the minimally conscious state in brain-injured patients A and B, who showed no behavioral response. Alice instructed Patient A: \"Imagine curling and stretching both big toes.\" The SMA of A showed a response. Alice concluded that A was in a minimally conscious state. Alice then conducted the same experiment with B, but there was no response in B’s SMA. Alice concluded that B was not in a minimally conscious state. <Experiment> Participants without brain injury were asked to perform the following tasks. First, they were instructed, \"Curl and stretch both big toes,\" and the movement of the toes was confirmed. Next, they were told, \"Just imagine curling and stretching both big toes.\" Then, they were instructed, \"Imagine playing table tennis.\" <question> Which of the following analysis statements about the above passage are correct? Choose the correct ones from <statements>. <statements> (a) If the SMA responded in all three cases in the <Experiment>, Alice’s conclusion about A is reinforced. (b) If, in <Experiment>, there was no SMA response when only movement imagery was instructed—unlike when actual movement was instructed—Alice’s conclusion about B is reinforced. (c) If, in <Experiment>, there was no SMA response when instructed to imagine playing table tennis, but it was revealed that the participant imagined someone else playing table tennis, then ⓐ is reinforced. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If the SMA responded in all three cases in the <Experiment>, Alice’s conclusion about A is reinforced.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If, in <Experiment>, there was no SMA response when only movement imagery was instructed—unlike when actual movement was instructed—Alice’s conclusion about B is reinforced.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If, in <Experiment>, there was no SMA response when instructed to imagine playing table tennis, but it was revealed that the participant imagined someone else playing table tennis, then ⓐ is reinforced."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The passage presents both the ⓐ hypothesis—which is applied when verifying a minimally conscious state in severely paralyzed, non-communicative brain-injured patients—and the <Experiment>. If a behavioral instruction concerning movement is given and the patient understands and responds appropriately, the diagnosis is that minimal consciousness is present. However, if the patient is incapable of producing final muscular movement, it would be hasty to declare minimal consciousness absent just because of a lack of behavioral response. Thus, Alice applies the hypothesis ⓐ that the supplementary motor area responds even when a person merely imagines their own movement, just as if they were actually moving. After instructing the patient to imagine their own movement (motor imagery), Alice determines—based on the SMA response—that A has minimal consciousness and B does not.<Experiment> describes healthy participants given instructions both to move and to imagine movement. Explanation for <statements>:(a) If ⓐ is true, both actual movement and imagery of the movement should yield SMA responses in non-brain-injured participants. Therefore, if SMA responded in all three cases—both when actual movement was instructed and when imagination was instructed—this supports ⓐ. Thus, Alice’s conclusion about A, derived using ⓐ, is also reinforced. (a) is a correct analysis.(b) If ⓐ is true, the SMA should respond when a healthy person imagines movement. Thus, if in <Experiment> the SMA did not respond to movement imagery (unlike when movement was actually performed), ⓐ would be weakened. Accordingly, Alice’s conclusion about B—derived using ⓐ—is also weakened. (b) is an incorrect analysis.(c) If ⓐ is true, the SMA should respond when a healthy person imagines performing a movement. Therefore, if there was no SMA response during the table tennis imagery instruction in <Experiment>, ⓐ would be challenged. However, if it is revealed that the participant was imagining someone else playing, not themselves, this means the experiment was not properly controlled and does not constitute firm evidence against ⓐ; at best, it means ⓐ is not weakened, but this is not the same as saying it is reinforced. Therefore, (c) is an incorrect analysis.Since only (a) is correct, the answer is ①."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_28",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "28",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to correctly judge whether experimental results strengthen or weaken a hypothesis, based on an understanding of an experiment that verifies differences in memory recall rates resulting from variations in emotional expressions displayed on the face and differences in expressions between the learning and testing phases.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "3",
    "original_question": "Empirical studies examining the effects of differences in emotional facial expressions on memory typically involve showing participants photographs of faces displaying negative expressions (such as anger or crying) or emotionally neutral, expressionless faces. After a certain period of time, participants are then asked to identify which faces they have seen before from among a set of various photographs. At this point, differences in emotional expressions between the photos shown during the learning phase and those shown during the memory test phase can cause differences in memory performance. Therefore, to examine the effect of emotional expressions on facial memory, changes in memory rates due to mismatches in emotional expressions between the learning and test phases must be considered. For this purpose, the following <hypotheses> were tested through the following <experiments>.<Hypotheses> A: The memory rate for faces with negative expressions is higher than that for faces with neutral expressions. B: The influence of expression congruence between the learning and test phases on memory rate is greater than the difference in memory rates between negative and neutral expressions.<Experiments> Experiment 1: Participants were randomly divided into two groups. One group learned faces with negative expressions, and the other group learned faces with neutral expressions. In the test phase, both groups were tested on memory using facial expressions identical to those shown during the learning phase. Experiment 2: All participants learned faces with negative expressions. During the test phase, they were randomly divided into two groups; one group was tested with faces showing negative expressions, while the other group was tested with faces showing neutral expressions. <question>  Which of the following <statements> is/are true when evaluating the above passage? <Statements> (a) If the results of Experiment 1 show that the memory rates of the two groups are similar, Hypothesis A is weakened. (b) If the results of Experiment 2 show that the memory rates of the two groups are similar, Hypothesis A is weakened. (c) If the results of Experiment 1 show that the memory rates of the two groups are similar, and the results of Experiment 2 show that the group tested with negative expressions has a higher memory rate than the group tested with neutral expressions, then Hypothesis B is strengthened. <choices> ① (a) ② (b) ③ (a), (c) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If the results of Experiment 1 show that the memory rates of the two groups are similar, Hypothesis A is weakened.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If the results of Experiment 2 show that the memory rates of the two groups are similar, Hypothesis A is weakened.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If the results of Experiment 1 show that the memory rates of the two groups are similar, and the results of Experiment 2 show that the group tested with negative expressions has a higher memory rate than the group tested with neutral expressions, then Hypothesis B is strengthened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "Two hypotheses about the differences in memory rates depending on emotional expressions and the congruence of expressions between the learning and test phases are presented. Hypothesis A is “The memory rate for faces with negative expressions is higher than that for faces with neutral expressions”; Hypothesis B is “The congruence of facial expressions between the learning and test phases has a greater effect on memory rate than the difference between negative and neutral expressions.”In Experiment 1, participants are divided into two groups at the learning stage to study either faces with negative expressions or faces with neutral expressions, and are then tested using photos with the same expressions as those in the learning phase. Therefore, Experiment 1 is designed to test Hypothesis A. In Experiment 2, all participants are shown faces with negative expressions during the learning phase, and are then tested on either negative or neutral expressions during the test phase. This allows for an examination of part of Hypothesis B: the effect of the match between expressions in the learning and test phases on memory. Note that Experiment 2 does not test Hypothesis B in its entirety, but only a part of it.<Explanation> (a): If the results of Experiment 1 show similar memory rates for the two groups, this means that there is no difference in memory rates between negative and neutral faces, thereby weakening Hypothesis A. Thus, (a) is a correct evaluation.(b): Since Experiment 2 involved participants learning faces with the same (negative) expression, it cannot evaluate differences in memory rates due to differences in emotional expressions. Therefore, Experiment 2 does not have any implications for Hypothesis A. Thus, even if similar memory rates are observed in Experiment 2, this neither weakens nor strengthens Hypothesis A. Therefore, (b) is incorrect.(c): If the results of Experiment 1 show similar memory rates for the two groups, it means there is no difference in memory rates between negative and neutral expressions. If, in Experiment 2, the group tested with negative expressions achieves higher memory rates compared to the group tested with neutral expressions, this means that the congruence between learning and test phase expressions increases memory performance. Therefore, one can conclude that the match between expressions in the learning and test phases influences memory. From the results of both experiments, one can deduce that “the effect of expression congruence between the learning and test phases on memory rate is greater than the effect of the type of expression (negative vs. neutral).” Therefore, (c) is a correct evaluation.Since only (a) and (c) are correct, the answer is ③."
  },
  {
    "id": "2025_29",
    "year": "2025",
    "problem_idx": "29",
    "objective": "This question assesses the ability to correctly determine whether the results of an <experiment> strengthen or weaken a given hypothesis.",
    "domain": "Society",
    "category": "Argument Evaluation & Analysis",
    "answer": "1",
    "original_question": "Various studies on gender inequality in workplaces with a high proportion of men demonstrate that women receive relatively fewer opportunities and lower evaluations compared to men, even when accounting for their actual abilities and achievements. This structural situation faced by women makes it difficult for them to fully exhibit their abilities on teams carrying out projects that require creativity. Creative projects generate synergy when team members gather and engage in active interaction together. However, if women are restricted in their opportunities to demonstrate creativity during team activities, or if their creative expressions themselves are undervalued, women will not be able to fully realize their capabilities within team activities. In this context, “ⓐWomen will display greater creativity in environments where they work separately from men rather than environments where they work together with men.” To test this, the following <Experiment> was conducted.<Experiment>Forty male singers and forty female singers were recruited, and then paired at random to form 40 mixed-gender duets. Of the 40 pairs, 20 were randomly assigned to the control group; each pair recorded the same song in the studio together, accompanied by musicians. The remaining 20 pairs were assigned to the experimental group: the male singer in each pair recorded the same song in the studio with the musicians, while the female singer, alone in the studio, listened to the recording of the male singer and the musicians and recorded her own part, thereby completing the song. There were five musicians in total, all of whom were men, and the same musicians played in all 40 duets. After the recordings were complete, a panel of experts with equal numbers of men and women listened to the songs and evaluated the creative expression of the male and female singers by scoring them. <question> Which of the following in <statements> correctly evaluates the <Experiment>? <statements> (a) If the female singers’ scores were higher in the experimental group than in the control group, ⓐ is supported.(b) If the total score of all female singers was higher than that of all male singers, ⓐ is supported.(c) If the female singers’ scores in the control group were slightly lower than those of the male singers, but in the experimental group the female singers’ scores were higher than those of the male singers, ⓐ is weakened. <choices>① (a) ② (c) ③ (a), (b) ④ (b), (c) ⑤ (a), (b), (c)",
    "statements": {
      "statement_1": "(a) If the female singers’ scores were higher in the experimental group than in the control group, ⓐ is supported.",
      "statement_2": "(b) If the total score of all female singers was higher than that of all male singers, ⓐ is supported.",
      "statement_3": "(c) If the female singers’ scores in the control group were slightly lower than those of the male singers, but in the experimental group the female singers’ scores were higher than those of the male singers, ⓐ is weakened."
    },
    "original_rationale": "The hypothesis presented is that “women will display greater creativity in environments where they work separately from men rather than in environments where they work together with men,” and an <Experiment> is provided to test this. In the <Experiment>, the group where female singers collaborate in singing with male singers and male musicians serves as the control group, while the group where female singers perform separately from the male singer and musicians serves as the experimental group.Explanation of <statements>:(a) If ⓐ is true, then female singers will achieve higher creativity scores when not collaborating with men compared to when they do collaborate. Therefore, if the female singers’ scores in the experimental group are higher than in the control group, it means their scores were higher when not working with men, which supports ⓐ. Thus, (a) is a correct evaluation.(b) For example, suppose the results showed that female singers had higher creative expression scores than male singers in the control group, that the scores of female and male singers were similar in the experimental group, and that the male singers’ scores in the control and experimental groups were comparable. Even though the total score for all female singers exceeds that of all male singers, this could actually mean that female singers performed better when collaborating with men, which would oppose ⓐ. Therefore, the statement “the total score of all female singers was higher than that of all male singers” does not necessarily support ⓐ. Thus, (b) is not a correct evaluation.(c) For instance, suppose the male singers’ scores in the control and experimental groups are similar. If female singers scored slightly lower than the male singers in the control group, but outperformed the male singers in the experimental group, this means the female singers’ scores were higher in the experimental group than in the control group, which supports ⓐ, not weakens it. Thus, it cannot be said that “if the female singers’ scores in the control group were slightly lower than those of the male singers, but in the experimental group the female singers’ scores were higher than those of the male singers, ⓐ is weakened.” (c) is not a correct evaluation.Therefore, only (a) provides a correct evaluation, so the answer is ①."
  },
